<FIRST>r a AM-PTLTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0703 07-24 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PTL Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0703,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Begins Deliberations in Tax Trial of PTL Aides</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 1-2 to UPDATE with jury deliberating three hours
before leaving.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David and James Taggart lied when they
said PTL founder Jim Bakker authorized them to take ministry money
they used to buy property and jewelry, a prosecutor said Monday
before deliberations began in the Taggarts' tax evasion trial.
   The jury started deliberations just after 5 p.m. on the 12th day
of the trial. Jurors left after three hours and were to resume
Tuesday.
   ``In a nutshell, this case is about power,'' prosecutor David
Brown said in his closing statement in the brothers' trial. ``The
power David Taggart and his brother exercised at PTL to line their
own pockets.''
   The Taggarts are charged with evading $525,000 in income taxes
after spending nearly $1.2 million in PTL money on personal
luxuries such as condominums, jewelry, expensive cars and designer
clothes. The trial began July 5.
   If convicted, each brother could be sentenced to 25 years in
prison and face fines of more than $1 million.
   The defense rested Thursday following two days of testimony from
the Taggarts, who began at PTL as piano players. U.S. District
Judge Robert Potter gave no reasons for then postponing Friday's
session.
   Within a few years of joining PTL in the late 1970s, David
Taggart, 32, was Bakker's top personal aide. James, 35, was the
interior designer at PTL's Heritage USA Christian retreat just
south of Charlotte.
   Before his closing remarks, defense attorney Ben Cotten placed
items from such exclusive New York stores as Cartier and Gucci on a
bench in front of the jury. ``If what is on trial here is a
lifestyle you don't like, then we didn't need a trial at all,'' he
said.
   Brown told the jury that the government's case was made more
difficult by some of the witnesses _ including the two defendants.
   ``If you're not offended by the evidence of how they spent the
money they took from PTL ... you should be offended by the fact
that both defendants got on the stand and lied,'' Brown said.
   He said there was ample evidence to support the government's
case.
   David Taggart showed ``audacity and greed'' when he testified he
was entitled to be paid at a level similar to Bakker.
   ``Jim Bakker never authorized it, never, not once. David Taggart
took the stand and lied to you and David Taggart and James Taggart
conspired to take money from PTL and not pay taxes on it,'' Brown
said. He referred to Taggart's testimony that he had authority from
Bakker to take large cash advances and use PTL blank checks.
   David Taggart testified last week that his way of accounting for
the $1.2 million was to submit documentation to justify it, receive
a tax form from PTL that called the cash advances income or that
the cash advances would be considered a loan which would be
converted into a bonus.
   Cotten used his closing arguments to return to testimony about a
verbal agreement he said was reached between David Taggart and
Bakker in 1983. He asked the jurors not to dismiss the agreement
simply because it was an oral contract.
   Cotten said Bakker agreed to give David Taggart access to the
same resources he enjoyed. ``The intent was not to beat the IRS out
of money. It was to have PTL shoulder the burden,'' Cotten said.'
</TEXT>
