<FIRST>r a AM-ActressSlain     07-24 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Actress Slain,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Accused of Killing Actress Said to Have Gone to Samantha Smith's
Hometown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man accused of killing actress Rebecca
Schaeffer reportedly traveled to the Maine hometown of Samantha
Smith, the young girl whose 1983 visit to the Soviet Union drew
international attention
   Police investigators were told that Robert John Bardo, now 19,
ran away and traveled to Maine four or five years ago to be near
the Smith girl, the Tucson Citizen reported Saturday.
   In July 1983, Miss Smith, then 11, went to the Soviet Union for
a two-week tour at the invitation of the late Soviet leader Yuri
Andropov. She had written a letter to Andropov, asking the world
leader whether he favored war.
   In an unusual move, he responded to her letter, telling her the
Soviet people had peaceful intentions and inviting her to visit his
country.
   Two years later, on Aug. 25, 1985, she and her father were
killed in a plane crash near Auburn, Maine.
   Dan Andrews, a Los Angeles homicide detective, said he heard the
Smith story from an acquaintance of Bardo. Andrews would not
identify the acquaintance.
   Detective Sgt. Charles Armijo said Bardo's father, Phillip A.
Bardo Jr., told Tucson police detectives after his son's arrest
that the son had developed the obsession for Miss Smith and had run
away to find her.
   Armijo said detectives were told Bardo had gotten within several
blocks of the Smith home but was picked up by police when he asked
for directions. Bardo was returned to his parents.
   Bardo was arrested in Tucson last Wednesday, one day after Ms.
Schaeffer was gunned down at her apartment building in Los Angeles.
   He is jailed in lieu of $1 million bail, and his lawyer has said
Bardo will fight extradition to California.
   Neither Armijo nor Andrews indicated they thought Bardo was
thinking of harming the young girl.
   Bardo's father, Phillip, declined to comment on the Smith matter.
   ``We're not discussing anything with anyone,'' the elder Bardo
said. ``Later on we'll release a statement, but we're kind of
sorting it out ourselves right now.''
</TEXT>
