<FIRST>u a AM-BusShooting 1stLd-Writethru a0716 07-24 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Shooting, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0716,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Man Charged in Bus Shootings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with suspect charged. Picks up
4th graf, `Witnesses said...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police issued a murder warrant Monday for
a 44-year-old drifter accused of killing two people aboard a county
bus and wounding another motorist while stealing his car.
   Joseph Besaraba was charged with two counts of murder, one count
of armed robbery, one count of attempted murder, said Hollywood
Police Det. Darron Cansiglione.
   Police circulated a photo of Besaraba among homeless men at the
food program of the First Lutheran Church in Fort Lauderdale. The
man reportedly used the program as an address.
   ``The police contacted us early yesterday because they said they
had this address,'' First Lutheran Pastor Robb Grimm told The Miami
Herald. Late Monday, police announced they had signed a warrant for
Besaraba, known by the nickname ``Crazy Joe'' to other homeless men
at the shelter.
   ``He was wild and spontaneous,'' said Larry Brown, who knew
Besaraba from the shelter.
   Witnesses said the gunman had been drinking wine at the stop in
front of a supermarket in Hollywood, a suburb north of Miami. He
stepped into the door of the bus after it pulled up and opened fire
at the driver and sprayed bullets through bus windows.
   ``The door opened. He stood up, reached under his shirt and
pulled out a gun,'' said Devin Oppy, 28, a passenger in the rear of
the bus. ``The driver looked at him and he shot him three times in
the head. He didn't say a word. People were screaming and jumping
on the floor. I kept saying, `Get down!'''
   Sydney Granger, 43, a driver for the Broward County Transit
Authority, was killed. An immigrant from Grenada with several
children, he was making his last round and had about 30 minutes
left on his shift. The passenger on the bus had been identified but
his name was not released by midday Monday until next of kin could
be told.
   No special safety procedures were planned after the shooting,
because it appeared to be a random incident, ``nothing that could
be deemed a vendetta against bus drivers,'' said Joel Volinski, a
spokesman for Broward County Transit.
   He said two bus drivers who knew the victim stayed out of work
Monday, but most drivers had shown ``a surprisingly stable
reaction.''
   ``We've tried to have our own supervisors and superintendents
keep a greater visibility and availability to the operators,'' he
said. ``They might be at transfer locations or in their car where
certain buses are scheduled to stop.''
   After the initial shootings, the gunman walked through the
supermarket parking lot to an intersection and banged his gun on
the window of a car, witnesses said.
   Scott Yaguda, 31, a tourist from Alexandria, Va., surrendered
his car and was walking away when the gunman shot him three times
in the lower left leg and twice in the back, witnesses said.
   ``The (gunman) seemed like he didn't have a care in the world,''
said Susan Miller, 40, who ran to call police. ``He just lifted his
arm and bang, bang, bang.'' She said Yaguda ``was backing away. He
had no reason to shoot him.''
   Yaguda was in Memorial Hospital in critical but stable condition
Monday, hospital spokeswoman Cynthia Wine said.
</TEXT>
