<FIRST>r a AM-HUD-Coors     07-24 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Coors,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Coors Letter Allegedly Cleared Way For Denver Project's Approval</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Coors, the wealthy Colorado brewer and a
friend of President Reagan, wrote Samuel R. Pierce Jr. to endorse a
request for more than $16 million in rent subsidies for Denver
housing projects, according to a published report.
   The New York Times reported in its Monday editions that the
endorsement two years ago by Coors came as the request appeared
headed for rejection.
   The Times based the information on Coors on internal government
documents.
   It also quoted former senior housing official Thomas T. Demery
as saying a HUD selection committee was told that Pierce, then the
department's secretary, wanted the Denver application given ``very
careful consideration, which it was.''
   The newspaper said the finding followed other revelations that
during the Reagan administration, the Department of Housing and
Urban Development was more likely to approve projects endorsed by
prominent Republicans, former Reagan aides and friends of Pierce.
   Documents showed the Denver proposal was originally left off a
list of 1987 applications to be recommended for financing.
   On Aug. 12, 1987, Coors wrote Pierce urging him to ``look into
this matter and give it your favorable approval.''
   One week after the letter was written, the selection panel met
in Washington and approved the Denver request, the Times said
documents showed.
</TEXT>
