<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     07-24 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORCO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kayla Mull raises petite potbellied pigs
that skateboard, squeal and sit up for their supper.
   One pig plays ``Swine Lake'' on the piano; a swimming pig has
been known to perform the ``swine dive.''
   ``They are new and marginally hip,'' said Carolyn Gray, a writer
for Pet Care Report. ``They are friendly, relaxed, and you can
housebreak them, which are the big three as far as I'm concerned.''
   The little swine are selling big in Beverly Hills.
   ``Yes, it's a trend. If you have your BMW, you have to have a
pig now,'' said an owner of two little pigs who wanted his name
withheld because of zoning violations. (The mini-pigs, originally
bred in China, can be raised legally only in areas zoned for
livestock.)
   ``They make really darling pets,'' said Gwenna Blackmore of
Rolling Hills Estates. ``They are clean, smart, and they are fun.''
   ``They are easier to potty train than a dog,'' said Micky, Ms.
Blackmore's daughter, who bought a male pig when it was one month
old. ``He sits on command. Of course, you have to give him a treat,
which is just about anything.''
   Ms. Mull, a 37-year-old microbiologist, is leading the pack of
pig breeders. Prices for the pigs start at $1,500 each.
   ``Everyone who has ever owned a pet pig, even for a week or two,
will tell you how much fun it was,'' she said. ``Even if it ended
up as dinner in six months.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man sporting a scruffy white beard and
macho persona swaggered off with top honors in the Ernest Hemingway
Look-alike Contest as this city ended a weeklong tribute to the
author.
   The Hemingway Days Festival attracted more than 6,000 visitors
to celebrate what would have been ``Papa's'' 90th birthday. The
festival also included fishing and writing contests, as well the
dedication of the Hemingway postage stamp.
   Richard Royston, a 55-year-old investor from Atlanta, beat out
47 other entrants Sunday.
   ``I know right now half my English professors from college are
jubilant and the other half are turning over in their graves,''
Royston said.
   Ray Mize, from Washington D.C., placed first among 607 entrants
in the festival's short story contest.
   His work, entitled ``The Blooding,'' is a Midwestern folk tale
of how people become hardened to life. Bob Shacochis, a writer for
Harper's magazine and one of several judges, described the
adventure as ``a story as American as Thanksgiving dinner'' and
``crystal clear.''
   Hemingway wrote classics such as ``For Whom the Bell Tolls,''
``A Farewell to Arms,`` ``The Snows of Kilimanjaro'' and ``Green
Hills of Africa,'' while living in Key West in the 1930s.
</TEXT>
