<FIRST>r a PM-PsychiatristVideos Bjt   07-24 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Psychiatrist Videos, Bjt,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Psychiatrist Puts Expertise Into Videos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAY FORMANEK Jr.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MORGANTOWN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it comes to teaching medical
students about mental illness, Don Fidler doesn't go by the book.
He makes movies.
   ``A lot of the videotapes I make are designed to make people
feel like they really are in the patient's shoes,'' said Fidler, an
adolescent psychiatrist at Chestnut Ridge Hospital and an associate
professor of psychiatry at West Virginia University.
   ``Like, what does it feel like to be psychotic. The audience
gets confused. They really begin to take on some of the feelings
that are being portrayed.''
   Fidler, 40, has produced more than 100 features since he began
using videotapes as a teaching tool a decade ago while at the
University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.
   About half are for sale to medical schools throughout the
country. The videos range from 8 minutes to two hours in length and
cost from $50 to $1,200.
   A year and a half ago, Fidler began working on a new educational
series called ``Medicine Playhouse'' at West Virginia. Each episode
presents an emotional, medical or philosophical problem typically
faced by health professionals.
   A question-and-answer session with an expert in the field is
held after each show.
   ``It's sort of a Lake Wobegone approach to medical education,''
Fidler said, referring to the mythical place made famous by
humorist Garrison Keillor on his radio show, ``A Prairie Home
Companion.''
   Students say the videos are a good learning tool.
   ``It's much more helpful for a medical student to observe a
patient,'' said Kellie Gooding, 24, a third-year student at the
medical school.
   ``It stays in your mind much longer if you can actually see a
schizophrenic or whatever, rather than just reading about it. You
might just remember something a couple of days if you read it. If
you see it on the screen, you might remember it for the rest of
your life.''
   ``The videos show a really comprehensive picture,'' said Sloane
Blair, 23, also a third-year student. ``It shows you as it is _
real people in real life. In a book, they would break a subject
down into one component and then another.''
   Some of the videotapes, Fidler said, make medical students
squirm.
   In one video, shot in black-and-white and titled simply,
``Depression,'' a loud clock ticks in the background as cameras
close in from different angles on the troubled face of an actor.
   ``It's just 15 minutes long but it seems like it runs for an
eternity,'' Fidler said. ``I've had people actually come up and
tell me they feel suicidal after watching it, even though the word
is never mentioned.''
   In another, called ``Paranoia,'' a man grows more and more
anxious as passengers riding on a city bus turn around in their
seats and begin staring at him.
   He admits his videos may not be right for everyone.
   ``About 10 or 15 percent of the students don't learn well using
the videotapes,'' Fidler said. ``They'd be better off with books or
a lecture. Some people just aren't good visual learners.
   ``But that's OK. I don't think many lectures in medical school
reach 85 percent of the students,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
