<DOCNO> AP890724-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 0155EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene     07-24 0720</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Considers Duty on Imports of Canadian Pork</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prospective U.S. levy on imports of
unprocessed fresh, chilled and frozen pork from Canada could add
further to a growing number of live hogs coming across the border,
according to an Agriculture Department analysis.
   Last week the Commerce Department ruled in a ``final
determination'' that Canada's pork is being subsidized. The ruling
now goes to the U.S. International Trade Commission, which has 45
days to decide whether the imports are hurting American hog farmers.
   If the commission agrees with the Commerce ruling, the Bureau of
Customs will be ordered to collect countervailing duties on imports
of Canadian pork to offset the benefits of the subsidies.
   The Commerce investigation did not include processed or
preserved pork products such as canned hams, bacon, sausage or
ground pork. Countervailing duties have been levied on imports of
live hogs from Canada the past four years.
   Overall, the United States is the world's largest pork importer,
with about 1.14 billion pounds, carcass weight equivalent, imported
last year, approximately 7 percent of U.S. consumption, according
to the department's Economic Research Service.
   Canada supplied almost 45 percent of the 1988 pork imports;
Denmark, 29 percent; and Poland, 11 percent. The remainder comes
mainly from other Eastern European countries.
   Pork imports during the first four months of this year totaled
about 333 million pounds, down 17 percent from January-April 1988,
the report said. Imports from Canada and Denmark were
``substantially below'' the year-earlier level, while shipments
from Eastern Europe were up slightly.
   ``Canadian hog and pork prices remain below last year, which has
encouraged domestic consumption and diverted some supply from the
export market,'' the report said. ``Despite near-record year-ago
hog slaughter, Canadian statistics indicate that total exports of
pork through the end of May were about 8 percent below 1988
levels.''
   Earlier this year there was a wide spread between western
Canadian hog prices and U.S. prices, the report said. That provided
a strong incentive for western Canadian producers to ship live hogs
to the U.S. market.
   The spread narrowed in April, and imports of live hogs from
Canada declined to less than half of their March level _ but still
were 18 percent more than a year earlier.
   Hog imports from all sources for the January-April period
totaled 475,845 head, the report said. That was 125 percent above
the same period in 1988.
   Canadian production this year is expected to be down about 2
percent from 1988 because of herd liquidations prompted by lower
hog prices.
   ``The addition of a countervailing duty deposit on fresh,
chilled and frozen pork imports from Canada is expected to
reinforce the existing shift towards imports of Canadian hogs,''
the report said.
   Shayle D. Shagam, an economist in the USDA agency, said in
another report that the world pork trade is small relative to total
production and that a handful of countries are involved.
   China is the largest pork producer, accounting for almost a
third of the world's total last year, but the country's huge
population requires most of the production, Shagam said. Last year
China was the fourth largest pork exporter, with live hogs and pork
going to Hong Kong, and frozen pork to Eastern Europe and the
Soviet Union.
   On an individual country basis, the United States is the second
largest pork producer but ranks fourth when the 12-nation European
Economic Community and Eastern Europe are included.
   As well as being the leading pork importer, the United States is
sixth in the world as an exporter. Japan is the biggest market for
U.S. pork. Mexico is another large buyer.
   Canada ranks seventh in the world as a pork producer, turning
out much more than it requires domestically, Shagam said. Exports
currently are about 22 percent of Canada's production. Almost 90
percent goes to the United States and 9 percent to Japan. Canada
was third as an exporter last year.
   ``As a result of large domestic pork supplies, imports by the
United States will remain fairly steady, with Canada increasing its
relative share of the market,'' Shagam said.
   But Shagam added that the mix between hogs and pork from Canada
will depend on relative wage rates in the meatpacking industry and
U.S. countervailing duties on imports from there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
