<FIRST>r w PM-Hunts-Taxes     07-24 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hunts-Taxes,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bunker Says He's Trying to Forget Silver Thursday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nelson Bunker Hunt says he's trying to forget
the spring of 1980, when his silver-buying binge crashed to an end
and began unraveling one of the world's greatest fortunes.
   He used to be in the oil business, in ranching and farming, he
told U.S. Tax Court Judge Jules G. Korner III. ``Lately, it's
hiring lawyers and defending lawsuits.''
   The Hunt brothers' tax case begins its third week today and is
expected to last about a month.
   Bunker Hunt is contesting $155 million in 1982 taxes the
Internal Revenue Services says are owed from the dissolution of a
partnership set up to pay off the brothers' debts.
   His brother William Herbert is contesting more than $158 million
in 1982 taxes, while younger brother Lamar, owner of the Kansas
City Chiefs football team, is contesting $505,377 in taxes.
   Bunker testified Friday, ``I don't go around trying to remember
what happened in the spring of 1980. It caused me tremendous
losses, it caused me tax problems.''
   Banks once eager to lend him money ``were trying to get their
arms around as much collateral as possible,'' he said _ to the
point of demanding ``pictures on the wall'' and even his brother's
Rolex watch.
   Hunt told the court he could not recall whether one document he
signed was five or 5,000 pages long or whether he signed a
promissory note for $272 million after Silver Thursday, the day in
late March 1980 when silver prices collapsed.
   Bunker and Herbert owned one-third of the world's supply of
silver bullion from a silver-shopping spree that began in 1973,
government attorneys claim.
   As the price tumbled to $10 an ounce from $50 an ounce, the
brothers found themselves with debts totaling as much as $2 billion
and creditors threatening the family's beloved Placid Oil Co.
   Bank creditors ``dictated'' the terms of the partnership with
Placid set up to repay the Hunt brothers' debts from their soured
silver investments, he said.
   ``The net effect was we didn't have control over our business.
That's why I'm sitting here in court, because of the structure the
banks put us in,'' Hunt said.
   Since then, Bunker, Herbert and Placid have filed for protection
from creditors in U.S. Bankruptcy Court; Bunker and Herbert have
been accused of attempting to corner the silver market by the
Commodity Futures Trading Commission; and a jury in New York last
year found Bunker, Herbert and two others had conspired to
manipulate and monopolize the silver market and defraud investors.
   Bunker, the first of the brothers to testify in the non-jury
trial, recalled one day after Silver Thursday when he signed
documents while surrounded by attorneys.
   ``I signed documents for three or four hours, just as fast as I
could,'' he said. ``There must have been thousands and thousands of
documents I signed, they would probably go to the ceiling of this
room here if they were stacked up end to end.''
   Bunker said he remembers Walter Fraker, Placid's vice president
and chief financial officer, telling him that the banks ``were
calling all the shots, it was pretty much their party'' as they set
up the partnership to repay the silver loans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890724-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 0216EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-HouseDemocrats     07-24 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-House Democrats,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Democrats Looking for New Campaign Talent</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: St Germain in 6th and 9th grafs is CQ</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like scouts in major league baseball, a
pair of House Democrats are looking for talent to keep their team
winning atop Capitol Hill.
   But figuring out which potential congressional candidates might
get a contract from the voters is a tricky task of balancing the
facts _ such as money _ with the intangibles, appearance and that
``hungry look.''
   Rep. Beryl Anthony, D-Ark., chairman of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, and Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla., the
committee's recruiting chairman, met this weekend with potential
candidates in Rhode Island and New Hampshire _ the two targeted
congressional districts Democrats say they might take from the GOP.
   In 1988, Democrats in the House picked up seats despite the big
GOP win on the presidential level. ``We out-hustled and we
out-recruited the Republican Party in terms of candidates,'' said
Synar.
   On their first trip of the 1990 cycle, the Democrats' task
wasn't finding the potential candidates; it was looking for which
one was most likely to win.
   In Rhode Island, Anthony and Synar met with four Democrats
interested in trying to unseat freshman Rep. Ronald Machtley,
R-R.I., who beat longtime incumbent Democrat Fernand St Germain
after St Germain's personal finances became the subject of a
federal probe.
   They consider Machtley a fluke, and the national Democrats want
to mount a strong challenge in 1990.
   Party rules don't allow the national Democrats to take sides in
a primary, so they can't handpick their candidate. But they can
pressure the locals to unite behind a candidate.
   Scott Wolf, who nearly beat St Germain in the primary last year,
told Anthony and Synar he was in the race. State Reps. Rene
Lafayette and Jeff Teitz said they also were lookin, as did Rhode
Island Secretary of State Kathleen Connell.
   In separate meetings with each, Anthony and Synar tried to learn
about the public skills and personal drive of the candidate:
   ``What would get you into it?''
   ``How much money can you raise by the end of the year?''
   ``What do you think of (other Democratic candidate)''
   They ask about local issues and how the national party can help,
and dole out advice.
   ``You realize the easiest way to clear the field is to have the
money,'' Synar tells one. And eventually, he warns, that may
involve something like mortgaging one's home to stay in the race.
   The two congressmen repeated the process in Manchester, in New
Hampshire's first congressional district. There, incumbent
Republican Bob Smith has announced for the Senate and Democrats say
they've got a good shot.
   ``We'd love to have a toehold up here,'' said Anthony. New
Hampshire is the only New England state with no Democrats in the
House or Senate.
   Again, the Democrats would like to avoid a costly and divisive
primary but it appears one is down the road.
   Conservative Democrat Bob Stephen, a state senator and
Manchester restaurateur, has already formed an exploratory campaign
committee. Joe Keefe, an attorney and moderate who lost to Smith
last year, says he's in it, too.
   And two others are looking, former state party chairman George
Bruno and stockbroker and party activist Jim Demers, who ran in
1986.
   ``If all of us go at it ... I don't think the seat is
winnable,'' warns Bruno, urging the national officials to do what
they can to help avoid a primary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890724-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 0223EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SovietMiners     07-24 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Miners,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Flex New-Found Muscle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Strikes, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROKOPYEVSK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every working day, Alexander S.
Kutlakhmetov boards an orange bus with six shoulder-high wheels
that carries him and other miners 43 miles across the rolling
Siberian plateau to the Taldinski Severni Open Pit Mine.
   On Friday, Kutlakhmetov, known as Sasha, boarded the bus for the
first time in more than a week. He sped off to explain to other
miners the details of a 35-point agreement that ended the first
Soviet industrial strike in 60 years.
   Lurching along the bumpy, thinly asphalted road that links city
and mine, the bus passed birch, aspen and pine forests, tiny
settlements of log cabins with carved wooden trims and kitchen
gardens. Small herds of goats and cows, and an occasional horse,
could be seen in the lanes.
   As the sun rose slowly, burning off a thick morning mist, the
bus arrived at the pit's brick headquarters, and the miners began
to slap each other's shoulders in greeting and discuss the
agreement that ended their unprecedented strike.
   Sasha stepped up to the landing and, waving the agreement, began
to explain.
   ``Do we get three years maternity leave?'' shouted one woman,
who worked in the mine offices.
   ``That's in there,'' replied Sasha.
   ``What about the time it takes us to get here on the bus?''
shouted a man.
   ``We'll get paid from the time we check in, but not for
commuting,'' said Sasha.
   The session continued for a half hour, as miners asked about
grievances that were advanced at Taldinski Severni but may or may
not have been included in the demands of the strike committee
formed the week before for the Kuznetsk Coal Basin, the country's
second largest coal-producing region.
   At last, the workers were satisfied that if they had not won
every point, they had at least seized the right to strike, a right
not guaranteed by Soviet law. They beamed with new-found confidence.
   ``It's a victory over the system that we've had in the Soviet
Union for the past 70 years, a system in which we work hard but get
little in return,'' said Pyotr A. Menayev, an engineer.
   Another miner, Viktor N. Sizikov, agreed that it was a victory,
but ``it would have been a bigger victory if we had continued the
strike.''
   Sensitive to the doubts of miners like Sizikov, the regional
strike committee renamed itself the Workers' Committee and remained
in session to pressure authorities to keep the bargain.
   ``If they don't, we go back on strike. That's in the
agreement,'' said Kutlakhmetov.
   Mine managers, who backed most of the strike demands, were
pleased at the most import government concession _ allowing mines
to form local assocations that will have a greater say in running
the industry, which remains under the general control of the Coal
Mining Ministry.
   ``It is better to be master in your own house,'' said Viktor G.
Shevnin, the main production engineer at the mine. ``The strike
will improve our lives. And the agreement will move us closer to
real economic independence.''
   The miners, still skeptical of the government's intention of
keeping the deal, boarded the bus once again to drive the final few
miles to the pit.
   Deep down in the crater, Valery E. Demski clambered into the
cabin of a giant crane and began using the controls to scoop small
mountains of coal into oversize dump trucks, resuming delivery of
fuel to the state.
   ``We got little concrete,'' said Demski, as he operated the
shovel. ``Maybe there will be more.''
   Another worker in the crane cabin, Yuri V. Gorlov, nodded his
head, and said, ``It was right to strike.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890724-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 0218EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i BC-Japan-Stocks     07-24 0026</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Stocks,0025</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Up In Tokyo</HEAD>
