<HEAD>Dollar Falls Against Yen Despite Uno Resignation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with closing Nikkei, dollar figures.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key barometer rose and
the dollar fell against the Japanese yen Monday despite news that
Prime Minister Sousuke Uno will resign.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 issues, which gained 234.56
points last Friday, added 193.90 points or 0.69 percent, to finish
at 34,093.33.
   The dollar started at 143.25 yen, up 1.10 yen from last Friday's
142.15 yen close, but fell steadily, ending the day at 141.95 yen.
   On the stock market, ``it appears that the market shrugged off
the election results,'' said Curtis King, a trader with Nomura
Securities.
   In an election for half the seats of Japan's upper house of
Parliament Sunday, the pro-business Liberal Democratic Party lost
its majority for the first time in 34 years. Uno announced he will
resign to take responsibility for the defeat.
   Interest-sensitive issues were bought during the day because
traders believed interest rates in the United States might rise
higher than they had expected, King said.
   ``At about 10:10 a.m. the news about Uno resigning triggered the
market to begin taking profits,'' he said.
   The market got sluggish afterward, although housing-related
issues picked up, King said.
</TEXT>
