<FIRST>r a PM-ArizonaGovernor     07-24 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arizona Governor,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mecham Still Looms Large on Arizona Political Stage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a year after former Gov. Evan Mecham
was driven from office in disgrace, he casts a shadow over Arizona
politics as he campaigns to regain his old job.
   Mecham's conservative ideas dominate the Republican agenda and
his successor, Democratic Gov. Rose Mofford, has been unable to
marshal support in her own party or win battles with the GOP
majority in the Legislature.
   Mecham was elected in 1986 in a three-way race; he got just 40
percent of the vote. That inspired a law requiring the governor to
receive at least 50 percent of the vote.
   Some Mecham supporters admit he would have trouble winning a
clear majority. But they say he may have enough solid support to
overcome any moderate Republican opponent in the primary.
   That leaves many Republicans in a quandary. What they'd really
like, said freshman state Sen. Jerry Gillespie, is ``somebody with
Mecham's philosophy but not his cantankerousness, at least as he's
been portrayed.''
   Mecham, whose only opponent so far is millionaire developer J.
Fife Symington III, exudes confidence about the September 1990
primary, and the general election that follows.
   ``I'm going to win the cotton-picking election,'' he said. ``You
can mark that on the wall if you wish.''
   The blunt-talking, 65-year-old auto dealer with four failed
gubernatorial campaigns behind him stunned Arizona Republicans with
his 1986 victory.
   From the start, he demonstrated a remarkable ability to offend
many groups. In his first month in office, he rescinded the state's
Martin Luther King Jr. holiday, questioning the civil rights
leader's stature and saying that former Gov. Bruce Babbitt had
lacked the authority to decree the holiday.
   Mecham also endorsed a book that characterized blacks as
``pickaninnies,'' stated that a political enemy was spying on him
with laser beams, and was reported to have associates with criminal
records.
   He was impeached in February 1988 on charges of misusing a state
protocol fund, obstructing a probe into a death threat and
concealing a developer's $350,000 campaign loan.
   The Senate convicted and ousted him two months later on the
first two charges before voters could make their own decision in a
recall election that had been scheduled for May. The Senate dropped
the loan concealment charge, and a jury subsequently acquitted him
of wrongdoing.
   Mecham earlier this month challenged his impeachment and
demanded the reinstatement of $570,000 in expenses.
   Mecham was succeeded by Mrs. Mofford, who since 1975 had been
secretary of state, a largely ceremonial, elected post similar to
the lieutenant governor in other states.
   Mrs. Mofford enjoyed popularity and bipartisan support early on,
but she failed to get her way on several key issues during the
legislative session that ended in June.
   Moderate Republicans sided with conservatives in opposing
Mofford initiatives to increase taxes and spending, instead cutting
the state's contribution to government pension funds.
   Mecham has advocated slashing taxes and state spending.
   The Legislature also defeated Mrs. Mofford's bid to restore the
King holiday.
   ``Rose basically is still trying to find her sea legs,'' said
state Rep. Peter Goudinoff, a University of Arizona political
science professor.
   Mrs. Mofford, 67, said she will run for re-election, although
aides say she hasn't yet begun fundraising. No other Democratic
candidate has announced.
   The perfect candidate, Gillespie said, would combine Mecham's
conservatism with Mofford's geniality.
   Some sense the impeachment is unfinished business for many
Arizonans.
   ``I think Arizona needs to vote on the Mecham situation,'' said
Rep. Leslie Johnson, who cast one of the few votes against
impeachment last year. Still, she added, ``We cannot allow any one
person to be the issue of the campaign.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890724-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 0429EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Mexico-Economy     07-24 0722</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Economy,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>Debt Reduction Vital To Economic Recovery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Mexico-Debt, Bjt ^By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The agreement with foreign banks to reduce
Mexico's debt burden will give Mexico both more cash for investment
and an important psychological boost after years of austerity and
stagnation.
   ``The resources that were being sent outside the country can now
be channeled into investment, growth and creating jobs,'' President
Carlos Salinas de Gortari said in a triumphant televised address
Sunday night.
   Mexico's total debt burden is estimated at $107 billion _ with
$54 billion owed to private banks _ and the agreement is expected
to cut billions from the amount Mexico has to pay to service its
debt to the banks.
   Mexico got into trouble during the oil boom, when developing
nations and banks thought the price of oil would keep going up.
   When the price crashed in 1982, Mexico was suddenly left without
enough money to make payments on the billions it had borrowed.
   The result was six years of belt-tightening under the
administration of President Miguel de la Madrid.
   The government had to take harsh measures to get the money to
make payments and that left little for development. Private
companies, too, couldn't borrow money to invest in new plants or
equipment.
   Mexico's economy slowed down and inflation went up _ to over 150
percent annually some years. The peso dropped like a brick against
the dollar from eight to the dollar in the mid-1970s to 2,500 to
the dollar today.
   The average Mexican paycheck lost about half its buying power.
The austerity affected everything from the peso to pollution _ 95
percent of all cars in Mexico City are more than five years old,
most bought before the crash.
   ``Every day we worked harder but we were worse off,'' Salinas
said.
   The country of 85 million was under additional social pressure
because of demographics. One million young people were entering the
job market every year, but the country had trouble creating even
half that many jobs.
   The pressure was also visible in the erosion of the governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party's power in last year's
presidential election. Salinas won with barely 50 percent of the
vote, the lowest margin in the history of a party that has given
Mexico 60 years of stable government.
   Some of the pressure was relieved by emigration, which continues
as one of many factors that gives the United States an interest in
its southern neighbor's stability.
   Mexico was able to argue that it deserved consideration from the
banks because it had done everything asked by creditors and had
worked hard to restructure its economy.
   It joined the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade and stopped
protecting its economy from foreign competition. The idea, which
has been working, was to reduce prices in Mexico and make Mexican
industry more competitive on international markets.
   Salinas was careful to get President Bush, Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady and institutions such as the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund on board before tackling the private
banks that were reluctant to write off billions in debt.
   He also made dramatic crackdowns on corruption and the drug
trafficking that had infuriated the United States.
   In his speech, Salinas said that some of the money saved under
the new agreement will go to building infrastructure _ roads, dams,
communications _ that he hopes will lay the basis for an eventual
growth rate of 6 percent a year.
   Economists say part of what Mexico gains will go to buying back
debt at a discount. The rest can be used for investment in
infrastructure that could prime the pump for the private sector.
   With fewer payments to make the government will need to borrow
less money, putting less pressure on domestic credit markets and
making more available for the private sector at lower rates.
   More importantly, Salinas hopes increased confidence and the
perception of victory will attract foreign investment and help
bring back billions invested abroad by wealthy Mexicans.
   Nevertheless, Salinas warned his countrymen, economic recovery
will not come overnight.
   ``The agreement does not mean that by some magic trick our
problems will cease to exist,'' he said. He promised firm guidance
of the economy and honest management of the nation's resources.
   ``Everybody must continue pushing productivity and maintaining
order,'' Salinas said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890724-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 0456EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Uno     07-24 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Uno,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Caretaker Prime Minister Who Didn't Last</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Japan, Bjt ^By LARRY THORSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Sousuke Uno became prime minister on June 2,
he was widely expected to be a caretaker who with luck might serve
until October while his scandal-plagued party put together a
political reform package.
   His luck turned out to be very bad.
   Now he will go down in Japanese postwar history as rivaling for
shortness the two-month tenure that Prime Minister Tanzan Ishibashi
had from December 1956 to February 1957.
   Seldom has a respectable political career crumbled as fast as
Uno's. He was in office less than a week when a weekly newsmagazine
published a former geisha's allegation that he had paid her to be
his mistress.
   Publishing the story broke a taboo about revealing details of
politicians' private affairs. The 66-year-old Uno, who is married,
was deeply embarrassed facing opposition questions in parliament as
to whether he was suitable to represent Japan abroad when his
ex-mistress had complained in print about the way he had treated
her.
   It was about the last thing Uno might have expected to happen to
him.
   Elders in his Liberal Democratic Party selected him to be prime
minister because his experience as foreign minister would stand
Japan in good diplomatic stead. He was clean of the bribery scandal
that ruled out all the prime ministerial contenders in the party,
and otherwise uncontroversial.
   But allegations against Uno widened, with publications finding
other women who claimed sexual relations with him. On June 28,
Japanese papers reported that Uno had asked party leaders to let
him resign because of the embarrassment.
   ``I didn't become prime minister because I wanted to,'' Uno was
quoted as saying.
   But he was persuaded to stay on. He attended the summit of the
world's seven leading industrial democracies in Paris in mid-July
and led the Liberal Democrats into what became their worst
electoral defeat in three decades in Sunday's voting for half the
seats in the upper house of Parliament.
   Uno's ``woman problem,'' as Japanese media dubbed his personal
scandal, was one of many the Liberal Democrats faced in the
election campaign. They were distrusted because of the bribery
scandal, disliked because of a new sales tax imposed in April,
suspected because market-liberalization measures were seen
threatening the livelihoods of farmers.
   This morning, Uno was calm as he faced reporters and said he
would leave office as soon as the party could replace him.
   ``Ultimate responsibility'' for the election defeat was his, he
said, and he hoped the party would choose a new head ``promptly.''
   If that process, as expected, takes three or four weeks, Uno
will not go down in history as beating Ishibashi's record for a
short tenure. But it will be a close call.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890724-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 0531EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-FranceFashion     07-24 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France Fashion,0738</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lacroix Still Signs Clothes with Fun, Fantasy and Luxury</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian Lacroix, maintaining his reputation as a
young creator, brought out a collection of fun, fantasy, lace and
furs on the first day of haute couture showings for next winter.
   As Paris sweltered under a rare heatwave, top couturiers on
Sunday unveiled their luxurious, befurred and feathered models for
cooler weather.
   Lacroix's pouf skirt finally ran out of steam. But he's kept a
taste for beautiful, opulent fabrics and top-heavy outfits full of
quirky, funny ideas.
   He's a man who takes chances with these expensive fabrics and he
usually wins, though not always. The applause after the show was
tepid.
   Bernard Arnault, head of the Agache financial consortium backing
Lacroix, waffled when asked if the eccentric, creative designer is
still a hot money-maker. ``His clothes are beautiful. That's all
that counts,'' he said.
   Lacroix's clothes with the draped fichu shoulder, the big hoods
or head scarves and collars over tiny skirts are great on the
runway, but perhaps not at every party, no matter how splashy.
   He used a lot of browns, dolling up pinstriped jackets with
draped satin fronts and sable cuffs, sometimes teamed with a
mole-colored velvet skirt. Mixing up textures with abandon, he put
a tiny lame ``damasked'' bolero over a trapeze minidress in shades
of mustard and burgundy, with a quilted velvet panel on the skirt.
   Some of the luxury fantasy was hilarious, till one tried to tote
up the cost of the enormous sable parka topping chocolate shorts
with braided silk cornrows flipping over them like a reggae singer
gone wild _ a mini-fantasy well over $30,000.
   Lacroix's violet jersey dress was a soothing contrast to all the
show-off fabrics. His little shortie flared coats in faille and
satin were wearable. There were wonderful moments like the long,
slinky carmine velvet coat with huge sparkling buttons worn over
slimming pants embroidered with stars.
   The brown and khaki silks were always topped up with lively
shades of coral, saffron, turquoise or gold.
   For evening, Lacroix's hand-painted pink and green tulle
ballerina fantasies and jeweled tunics looked like a Midsummer
Night's Dream of luxury. Other ballerina numbers were in rich red
velvet and black, always sparkling with touches of gold.
   The dazzling jeweled boleros and jackets looked like a treasure
trove of Ali Baba's Cave.
   And after Christian discovered his mom's lace-edged satin
slip-dress, his versions of lace for the runway simply took off in
a froth of glory.
   The heavy guipure effects, the lame-embroidered dresses in
khaki, cream and gold, the damasked and brocade dresses with
pheasant or ostrich-feather trim harked back to the best of the
negligee looks in the Twenties and Thirties. But things were always
a bit on the wild side _ a la Christian Lacroix.
   Japanese couturiere Hanae Mori, celebrating 35 years in the
fashion business and a new shop in Paris, showed beautifully
crafted clothes with more workmanship than fantasy.
   Her fit and cut are always impeccable, and the swirling
red-black-green harlequin coat over a pine green short sheath is
anything but stodgy. Her full-skirted grey flannel suits with black
velvet decor and the Mori trademark butterfly pins should please
her faithful regulars.
   Her true couture details _ like satin basketweaving basque
waists in suits _ testified to her craftsmanship. She was lavish
with fancy fabrics, but her lame-flecked or sequin-embroidered lace
numbers were demure rather than daring.
   The dresses that made one want to weep with joy were the chiffon
prints in Mori's ``old'' style _ the feather-light chiffon print
landscapes with the most delicate Japanese prints of flowers, trees
and birds.
   Torrente's forte is showbiz, and she wisely showed plenty of
spangled numbers to look great onstage or at a gala dinner.
   Her three full, long cashmere wraparound coats in emerald,
cardinal and rust looked light, easy and warm. Her saffron fitted
spencer jacket over an aubergine long, slinky skirt is a good way
of easing into evening.
   And she went all out for late-day glitz: a few jet embroidered
dresses had discreet trains. Colorful patchwork jackets had fur or
ostrich-feather cuffs. The all-sequined slink would be fine for
midnight at Las Vegas. Easier to wear would be the tuxedos with big
pearl pink satin lapels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
