<FIRST>r a PM-HearinKidnapping     07-24 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hearin Kidnapping,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wealthy Woman's Abduction Still Mystery One Year Later</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year after a wealthy woman was abducted
after a bridge party, authorities don't know whether she is alive
but they promise surprises when a lawyer goes on trial in
connection with her disappearance.
   Annie Laurie Hearin, then 72, disappeared from her Jackson home
on July 26, 1988. Her husband of 49 years, Robert, reported her
missing.
   Newton Alfred Winn, a St. Petersburg, Fla., lawyer, faces
federal charges of conspiracy to kidnap, extortion by mail and
perjury in connection with Mrs. Hearin's disappearance. He is to
stand trial Aug. 28 in Hattiesburg.
   The case has been chronicled in newspapers and magazines and
featured on the national television programs, ``Unsolved
Mysteries,'' and ``Inside Story.''
   But FBI spokesman Stewart Murphy said in an interview last week
that much remains to be told, and some will be revealed during the
trial.
   Court-appointed defense attorney John Colette agreed. ``There
will be a great deal of surprises,'' he said.
   The only word from Mrs. Hearin or her abductors has been a vague
ransom note left at the scene and a blood-stained note from Mrs.
Hearin dated Aug. 10.
   The ransom note demanded that Hearin settle matters with 12
franchisers sued by School Pictures of Mississippi Inc., a company
formerly controlled by Hearin.
   Although the kidnappers never made any specific demands, Hearin
paid a total of $1 million to the 12 franchisers after receiving
the note from his wife. Hearin's worth is estimated at between $100
million and $200 million.
   Winn was one of the franchisers. He voluntarily returned the
money.
   According to court records, a federal judge had ordered Winn to
pay $90,000 in June 1983 and $153,883 in 1984 to the Jackson-based
School Pictures. Winn has said he lost his life's savings,.
   According to information released so far, Winn's arrest stemmed
from statements by an unnamed woman who says he paid her $500 to
dye her hair and otherwise disguise herself, travel to Atlanta and
mail what is believed to be the Aug. 10 note from Mrs. Hearin.
   The woman hasn't been charged, authorities said.
   Mrs. Hearin's family has declined to comment on the anniversary
of her disappearance.
   But Oralee Buie, who played bridge with Mrs. Hearin just hours
before her abduction, said the adjustment without her friend of
almost 50 years has been trying.
   ``It's just very discouraging,'' she said. ``There's always hope
since we don't know, but it's hard to hold onto that hope.''
</TEXT>
