<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     07-24 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Retreating in Calm, Late-morning Trading, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was retreating in quiet European
trading late this morning as commercial banks sold the U.S.
currency.
   Gold prices moved slightly higher.
   Traders said the foreign exchange market wasn't showing much
reaction to the defeat of Japan's Liberal Democratic Party in
Sunday's parliamentary election and the subsequent announcement by
Premier Sousuke Uno that he would resign.
   Traders said a political change in Japan had been widely
expected for weeks and was already fully discounted in the yen's
exchange rates.
   Traders said they expected trading conditions to remain calm at
least until the opening of the New York market.
   They said the European market was thin because it was the
vacation season. They said they didn't expect any new initiatives
to come from the European players over the next few weeks.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.20 yen to a closing 141.95 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 142.28 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Friday:
   --1.9049 West German marks, down from 1.9055
   --1.6445 Swiss francs, down from 1.6455
   --6.4566 French francs, up from 6.4460
   --2.1519 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1350
   --1,376.25 Italian lire, up from 1,371.50
   --$1.8888 Canadian, up from $1.8880
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.6210 to buy one pound, compared with $1.6185 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $371.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Friday's $371.50. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $372.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $372 unchanged from late Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 10 cents to close at a bid
$372.99. Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.21 a troy
ounce, unchanged from Friday.
</TEXT>
