<FIRST>r i PM-Iran-Executions     07-24 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Executions,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Convicted Drug Traffickers Hanged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran today hanged 22 people convicted of
drug smuggling or prostitution, including nine women and four
Afghan nationals, the official Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, said the men were hanged in
public squares around Tehran and the women at a jail outside the
capital.
   It said they were convicted of smuggling, selling and
distributing heroin and opium, prostitution and spreading
corruption.
   The hangings brought to 810 the number of officially reported
executions under an anti-narcotics law that mandates the death
penalty for possession of even small quantities of drugs. The law
took effect in January.
   IRNA said a six-month grace period for addicts to kick the habit
expired Sunday and they would be rounded up and sent to labor camps
and other rehabilitation centers.
   Law enforcement officials have said they have identified 80
percent of Iranian drug addicts. Authorities have said that 1
million Iranians are involved in drug abuse but unofficial
estimates put the figure at 2 million of the country's 50 million
population.
</TEXT>
