<FIRST>r a PM-Newspage-TourdeFrance     07-24 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newspage-Tour de France,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>LeMond Takes Tour With Dramatic Win in Race's Final Stage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmits to change category code.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greg LeMond tried to become just another American
in Paris, but he had a hard time going unnoticed at the Moulin
Rouge.
   Less than six hours earlier on Sunday, he had won the Tour de
France, the famed French cycling race. He staged a miraculous
comeback to win the 2,020-mile, 23-day race by the closest victory
margin ever _ eight seconds over Laurent Fignon of France.
   So, it's no surprise he was greeted by applause at the Moulin
Rouge, the famous nightclub.
   The victory completed a dramatic recovery for LeMond from
misfortune suffered after he became the first American to prevail
in cycling's most famous race in 1986.
   In April 1987 he was accidentally shot by his brother-in-law
while hunting. Then he had an emergency appendectomy followed by
shin surgery. All of which made him miss the Tour in 1987 and 1988.
   He came back this year with low expectations.
   ``One month ago, I didn't think I would be in the top 10, top
20,'' LeMond said. ``But through the race I got more confident.''
   Confident enough to overcome Fignon's apparently insurmountable
50-second lead in the final stage, a 15-mile time trial from
Versailles to Paris.
   ``I went all out,'' LeMond said. ``I didn't think I was going to
win. The worst thing I could have done was lose by a second _ the
worst thing.''
</TEXT>
