<FIRST>r i PM-Canada-Fires     07-24 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canada-Fires,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Province Declares State of Emergency to Fight Forest Fires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The provincial government has declared
a state of emergency to fight raging forest fires and help house
thousands the blazes have left homeless.
   About 18,000 people have been airlifted from remote Indian
reserves and farms in the province, where the fires have swept
through nearly 2 million acres of dense evergreen forest.
   ``Virtually all of northern Manitoba is on fire and we're just
hoping some of our major centers are not going to be affected,''
Emergency Measures Minister Albert Driedger said on Sunday. ``Once
you get 15 minutes out of Winnipeg, all you see is smoke.''
   Hot, dry and windy weather fanned the flames of more than 400
fires across northern Saskatchewan, Manitoba and Ontario. Lightning
is blamed for most blazes, but police believe people started at
least two.
   Weather forecasts preducted thundershowers today, but officials
fear that may mean more lightning fires. A change in wind direction
today could cause additional problems, the Natural Resources
Department said.
   Driedger declared the state of emergency Sunday night.
   ``What was needed was the power to get placements (for
evacuees), equipment, supplies,'' he said.
</TEXT>
