<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 0902EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CannibalismDig     07-24 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cannibalism Dig,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pelvic Bone Supports Alferd Packer Claim of Self Defense</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Alferd is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE CITY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Recovery of five skeletons from a
115-year-old grave in Deadman's Gulch has given investigators new
clues about the deaths of confessed cannibal Alferd Packer's gold
prospecting companions.
   Scientists removing the skeletal remains Sunday found distinct
scrape marks on bones from two of the skeletons, indicating they'd
been cut and scraped or ``defleshed,'' said Walter Birkby, curator
of physical anthropology at the University of Arizona.
   There were punch marks in one bone, which scientists said were
probably made by a coyote eating the remains after the spring thaw
of 1874.
   On Saturday, they found a bullet hole in a right pelvic bone _
possible support for Packer's claim that one member of the party
killed the other four and that Packer shot that man in self-defense.
   Packer emerged from the mountains in April 1874, but the remains
of his companions weren't found and buried until that August.
   The Packer Project, which includes forensic anthropologists, a
forensic pathologist, and an expert on fibers and tool marks on
bones, packed the bones up Sunday for detailed laboratory study and
reconstruction.
   They hope their work will determine whether one hatchet was used
to kill four of the men and another was used on the fifth.
   That would support Packer's story that Shannon Wilson Bell
killed the first four with a hatchet before Packer killed Bell in
self-defense, shooting him in the stomach and hitting him on the
head with a hatchet.
</TEXT>
