<FIRST>r a PM-ExxonValdez     07-24 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Valdez,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Divers Back to Work Removing Hanging Plates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divers preparing the crippled Exxon Valdez to
enter San Diego Harbor went back to work today cutting away massive
steel plates dangling from the ship's hull.
   Three plates were severed over the weekend from the tanker that
ran onto a reef in Alaska's Prince William Sound March 24 and
spilled 11 million gallons of crude oil in the nation's worst oil
spill.
   The plates, which ripped loose as the ship was being brought to
San Diego for repairs, must be removed so the tanker can enter
shallow San Diego Bay.
   Among the plates removed was a slab weighing an estimated 50
tons and measuring 72 feet long and 68 feet across. Another cut
Sunday was 30 feet long and 35 feet across, said Exxon spokeswoman
Jan Cool.
   The plates won't be salvaged because they are too heavy, Ms.
Cool said.
   Instead, divers allowed them to fall 3,000 feet to the ocean
floor, Cool said.
   Some of the plates were hanging 90 feet below the surface, and
San Diego Bay is only about 40 feet deep in some spots.
   The Valdez was about 54 miles off San Diego and six miles
northeast of on San Clemente Island.
   California officials worried about possible pollution have yet
to reach agreement with Exxon on terms governing the tanker's
entrance into the harbor.
</TEXT>
