<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 0938EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain     07-24 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Prepares To Shuffle Cabinet As Gov't Popularity Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher summoned Cabinet
ministers for private interviews today ahead of what aides called
changes aimed at halting her Conservative government's slide in
popularity.
   A senior Thatcher aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
a ``freshening'' of the 22-member Cabinet would likely be announced
this evening.
   Apart from the Cabinet changes, Mrs. Thatcher appeared virtually
certain to appoint a new chairman of her Conservative Party
following a drubbing by socialists in June 15 elections for the
European Parliament.
   Speculation of an unexpected change increased after Energy
Secretary Cecil Parkinson, a Thatcher favorite whose political
career was interrupted after an extramarital liaison six years ago,
arrived today at her 10 Downing St. office.
   Parkinson, who is married, resigned from the Cabinet in 1983
after news broke that his secretary, alleged to be his mistress,
was pregnant. Mrs. Thatcher reappointed him when she won a third
successive five-year term in elections in June 1987.
   Also summoned today were Education Secretary Kenneth Baker, a
moderate in the mainly right-wing Cabinet, who is widely expected
to replace the current Conservative Party Chairman, Peter Brooke,
and Environment Secretary Nicholas Ridley.
   Ridley, chain-smoking scion of an aristocratic family, was
expected to become the new Trade and Industry Secretary, replacing
Lord Young, a non-career politician who has said he wants to resume
his business interests.
   Ridley, accused by critics of mishandling the current passage
through Parliament of a controversial property tax, is blamed by
large sections of the party for increasing the government's current
unpopularity.
   But Mrs. Thatcher, who has the sole power to appoint Cabinet
ministers, has publicly defended him.
   Changes in about 90 government posts which do not carry Cabinet
rank, were expected Tuesday.
   Mrs. Thatcher's government has trailed the revived socialist
opposition Labor Party in public opinion polls for several months.
   In the latest poll by Harris, published Sunday in The Observer,
a liberal weekly, Labor was seven points ahead of the Conservatives
with 44 percent support. The remainder was split among minority
parties.
   The 2,000 voters questioned were critical of the government for
its handling of the National Health Service, public transport, the
new property tax, proposals to privatize water supply and rising
inflation.
   No margin of error was given for the nationwide poll, conducted
Thursday and Friday by telephone.
   In the European elections, Labor garnered 40.1 percent of the
vote, compared with the Conservatives' 34.7 percent.
   Adding to Mrs. Thatcher's problems is a revival of labor union
militancy, including a wave of public transportation strikes.
   Inflation, the cornerstone of Mrs. Thatcher's rigorous economic
policies since she won power 10 years ago, is now back among the
highest in the Western world at 8.3 percent.
</TEXT>
