<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Strike 2ndLd-Writethru a0482 07-24 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Strike, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0482,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Calls Miners' Strike Biggest Test Of His Tenure</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 16th pvs, `Several deputies...' to UPDATE
with Gorbachev saying Moscow should not determine local election schedules.
Pickup 17th pvs, `Gorbachev proposed...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev told legislators today that
the strikes that have swept the Soviet Union's major coal fields
for nearly two weeks have been the ``biggest test'' of his four
years in power.
   He blamed coal ministry and local officials rather than the
miners for the unrest _ which halted work at mines in all the
country's major coal fields _ but he said ``deciding such questions
by striking will ruin our tasks.''
   The Soviet president said most striking miners have returned to
work, including at least half the 300,000 miners in the country's
biggest coal basin, the 121-mine Donetsk region in the Ukraine.
   ``We are coming out of a very serious crisis, the biggest test
during the four years of perestroika,'' Gorbachev told the Supreme
Soviet, referring to his program of restructuring economic and
political life.
   On Sunday, Gorbachev said in a rare television interview that he
was ``inspired'' by the workers' initiative although he disagreed
with their tactics. He also said he understood why the miners
mistrusted a government that long ignored them.
   The strikers in the Donetsk basin were among the last holdouts
from the nationwide coal strike that started in western Siberia
July 11 and spread to the Arctic Circle and Central Asia.
   The strikes began to ebb Friday as the Siberia strikers returned
to work Friday after exacting promises of higher pay, better food,
clothing and housing and greater control over their industry.
   The government said those concessions would apply to striking
miners nationwide.
   Strikers in the Donetsk have held out for legal guarantees from
the Supreme Soviet that the government would keep the promises it
made to miners in a settlement signed Saturday by strike leaders
and government officials.
   A lawmaker from the Pechora coal basin in the far north told the
Supreme Soviet that miners around the city of Vorkuta also remained
on strike, in part due to ``disinformation'' by the media.
   Miner Vladimir P. Lushnikov said state-run media reported
erroneously that the Vorkuta strike ended.
   According to recent reports, miners remained on strike at 11 of
the 13 mines in Vorkuta and at all 12 mines in Chervonograd in the
western Ukraine.
   Lawmakers speaking at today's Supreme Soviet session, which was
broadcast nationally with a slight tape delay, said the strikes
showed that the country needed more effective unions.
   ``We have to admit that the trade unions don't have the workers'
faith,'' said Lithuanian deputy Kazimeras Uoka. ``We have to give
them the right to establish independent trade unions.''
   Soviet unions act as adjuncts of the government, handling the
distribution of various benefits rather than fighting for workers'
rights.
   Several deputies from mining regions also called for moving up
local elections from spring to this fall to give voters a chance to
oust officials who were insensitive to miners' needs.
   Gorbachev responded that decisions on how the local elections
are run should be taken in the republics, not in Moscow, even if
that means election laws and schedules will vary from place to
place.
   ``Shall we torpedo and limit this?'' he asked. ``We will hardly
succeed, commanding from here.''
   Gorbachev proposed that instead of waiting for elections, all
local councils around the country hold immediate meetings to
``examine the concrete situations in all regions with the aim of
activizing the work of our councils everywhere.''
   Alexei Boiko from the Donetsk appealed to Gorbachev and Prime
Minister Nikolai I. Ryzhkov to meet with a delegation of his
region's miners to hasten a resolution of its waning strikes.
   The walkout in the region began on July 15.
   More than 5,000 strikers continued demonstrating Sunday on the
central square in the city of Donetsk, 900 miles south of Moscow,
and miners at each pit were deciding for themselves whether to
resume work, a strike leader said in a telephone interview.
   The settlement in the Donetsk included earlier pension
eligibility, pay increases and longer vacations.
   Gorbachev told the Supreme Soviet the strikes dealt a serious
blow to the economy, but he reassured his countrymen that ``our
perestroika will give results despite the tests we are undergoing.''
   The labor unrest is the country's worst in 60 years and would
have been unthinkable before Gorbachev came to power in 1985 and
loosened restrictions on civil liberties.
   At the strikes' peak, reports indicated half the coal industry's
1 million workers were off the job.
</TEXT>
