<DOCNO> AP890724-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1017EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan 2ndLd-Writethru a0486 07-24 0870</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0486,0899</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier To Resign After Governing Party Suffers Worst Electoral Setback</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with comment from Liberal Democrat,
businessman. Pickup 8th pvs, ``In the ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sousuke Uno announced today he will
resign after his scandal-plagued party suffered a stinging
electoral defeat, losing control of a house of parliament for the
first time in its 34 years.
   ``It was a very difficult election,'' Uno told a nationally
televised news conference.
   Uno has been prime minister less than two months, but he said
his party's loss of control of parliament's upper house in Sunday
elections ultimately is his responsibility.
   The long-governing Liberal Democrats have seen their popularity
plummet over an influence-peddling scandal, a new 3 percent sales
tax and the liberalization of agricultural imports, which farmers
say hurts their livelihood.
   Uno has been criticized for alleged extramarital affairs,
including with a geisha who said he paid her to be his mistress for
several months.
   He said he hoped a successor could be found ``promptly.''
Analysts said the process could take several weeks.
   Uno's resignation will result in the dissolution of the Cabinet
and restructuring of the governing party's leadership.
   But some Liberal Democrats said this would not solve the
problems.
   ``It's a question of why we lost,'' said Yohei Koono, a liberal
lower house lawmaker. ``If our choice of policies is wrong, we need
to change it.''
   Business leaders urged thorough political reforms from the party
that guided Japan's rapid postwar economic growth.
   ``We should not allow this to have an adverse effect on economic
activity or the people's lives,'' said Eishiro Saito, chairman of
the powerful Japan Federation of Economic Organizations.
   In the balloting for half the 252 seats in parliament's upper
house, the big winner was the Japan Socialist Party, led by Takako
Doi, the first woman leader of a major Japanese party.
   Of 126 seats at stake, the Socialists won 46, the Liberal
Democrats 36. The Socialists' total strength in the chamber rose
from 43 to 66; the Liberal Democrats' fell from 142 to 109.
   Rengo (Confederation), a new labor-based group, won 11 seats and
the centrist Clean Government Party 10, with the rest split among
smaller parties.
   Ms. Doi said her party quickly will call a meeting of opposition
leaders to form a coalition against the Liberal Democrats, who
still hold 293 of the 512 seats in parliament's more powerful lower
house.
   Any coalition is expected to be fragile. While most major
opposition parties have called for abolishing the new sales tax,
they vary broadly on other issues such as defense policy, relations
with the United States, and nuclear power.
   With the loss of their majority in the upper house, however, the
Liberal Democrats will face greater difficulties in passing
legislation.
   The upper chamber can vote down bills and delay, but not block,
the budget and treaties.
   Ms. Doi called her party's victory ``the people's verdict,'' and
said Uno's decision to step down was ``only natural.''
   She said the Socialists' first priority is to pass a bill in the
upper house abolishing the sales tax. Such a bill is unlikely to be
approved by the lower house, however, and a standstill over the
issue could add to pressure for early elections for the lower
chamber. Legally, they do not have to be held for 12 months.
   A loss in the lower house would threaten the governing party's
34-year hold on power since that chamber chooses the prime minister.
   About 65 percent of Japan's 90.3 million eligible voters cast
ballots in Sunday's election, reflecting strong feelings over
issues affecting many people's everyday lives.
   Women were particularly unhappy over the new sales tax,
bulldozed through by the governing party despite an opposition
boycott.
   ``I really believe that this was a people's revolution coming
from the kitchen,'' said Kazuo Shinsaka, a Rengo candidate who won
election in Nara.
   A record 146 women candidates ran for office Sunday, and a
record 22 were elected, more than doubling female representation in
the chamber.
   ``One result of the election is that Japanese politicians from
now on will have to pay more attention to women,'' said Seisaburo
Sato, professor of political science at Tokyo University.
   Though Ms. Doi is immensely popular, her party has been widely
accused of lacking a realistic and constructive platform.
   In the past, it has called for Japan to disband its Self-Defense
Forces and scrap the U.S.-Japan Security Treaty, under which 64,000
U.S. troops are stationed in Japan.
   Socialist leaders now say they would not immediately do away
with the armed forces and seek only to revise the treaty.
   Uno became prime minister June 2 after former Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita resigned to take responsibility for a scandal in
which the Recruit Co., a publishing conglomerate, allegedly
distributed millions of dollars in underpriced stocks and political
donations to obtain favors.
   The governing party spent weeks finding an unsullied successor
for Takeshita. But shortly after taking office, Uno was linked to
the sex scandal.
   Asked how he felt after announcing his resignation, Uno, a poet,
said, ``My state of mind is `meikyo shisui''' _ meaning tranquil as
unrippled water.
</TEXT>
