<SECOND>PM-Ringo Returns, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0481,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Beatle Kicks Off First Solo Tour With `All-Starr' Backing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to insert time element, DELETES erroneous reference
to Starr as composer of ``Yellow Submarine.''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICIA SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kids got in free on the first night of Ringo
Starr's Tour for All Generations but their parents were doing the
screaming for the former Beatle, a grandfather backed by a graying
constellation of rock stars.
   They included former Beatles collaborator Billy Preston, who
played the organ on ``Let it Be;'' spooky Bayou singer Dr. John;
saxman Clarence Clemons and guitarist-keyboardist Nils Lofgren, on
loan from Bruce Springsteen's E-Street Band; and volume-cranking
guitarist Joe Walsh, a former Eagle.
   Ringo opened the first show of his 30-city tour stage front and
center Sunday night, singing ``It Don't Come Easy.'' After his
third vocal on ``Yellow Submarine,'' the 49-year-old retired to the
rhythm section.
   Banging the drums rapidly along with Ringo were Jim Keltner, who
played for John Lennon and George Harrison on their solo efforts,
and Levon Helm, drummer for The Band. Fellow Band member Rick Danko
provided the bass line.
   The audience for Ringo's first-ever solo concert was dominated
by thirty- and forty-somethings, including one woman who brought
her two young daughters to show them what the fuss was about.
   ``My kids don't even know who Ringo Starr is, but they will
after tonight,'' she said.
   The concert's promoters boosted the family theme by giving free
admission to children 12 and under accompanied by adults.
   Starr was wearing a star-trimmed jacket in his first public
appearance since a 1986 guest role with the Beach Boys in
Washington, D.C.
   Though he has released nine solo albums since 1970, Starr hasn't
toured since the Beatles split.
   A legendary drinker, he told USA Today that he and wife Barbara
Bach dried out last year at a Tucson rehabilitation center.
   Sober, he felt restless, and channeled his musical drive into a
plan he first hatched in 1978 _ assembling a cast of ``All-Starrs''
with himself in charge.
   ``I am the boss,'' Starr told the newspaper in an interview
published Friday. ``The big boss!''
   Guitarist Walsh interjected, ``The rest of us are little
bosses.''
</TEXT>
