<FIRST>r i PM-Burma     07-24 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burma,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Demand Release of Burmese Opposition Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRUNNSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 60 Burmese students waved banners
and chanted slogans outside their country's embassy in Bangkok
today to demand that Burma release two arrested leaders of the top
opposition group.
   It has been difficult to determine what is happening in Burma
because telephone and telex lines have been cut most of the time
since Wednesday, when hundreds of students defied martial law with
anti-government protests. Burma's official radio reported 44
arrests during those protests in Rangoon, the capital.
   Diplomats in Bangkok believe Burmese authorities are trying to
limit foreign reporting on their domestic strife.
   The military government of Burma placed Aung San Suu Kyi and Tin
Oo, who lead the National League for Democracy, under house arrest
on Thursday.
   The two were accused of trying to ``destroy the military and
revive anarchy,'' even though Ms. Suu Kyi had canceled a major
rally planned for Wednesday.
   In addition, British authorities have expressed concern over the
whereabouts of Michael Aris, Ms. Suu Kyi's British husband. He flew
to Burma's capital, Rangoon, on Saturday.
   A Foreign Office spokesman in London said Aris was not permitted
to see a British diplomat who had waited for him at the airport.
Aris may also be under house arrest, the spokesman said on
condition of anonymity.
   In the Bangkok protest, Burmese students carried banners
denouncing military rule and waved a ``fighting peacock'' flag
while chanting slogans of last year's thwarted popular Burmese
uprising for democracy.
   The fighting peacock was the symbol of Burma's battle for
independence from British colonial rule.
   ``We denounce the arrests and demand the immediate release of
Aung San Suu Kyi and Tin Oo,'' said 24-year-old Moe Thee Zun, who
until April headed the largest student party in Burma. He fled
after a wave of arrests of opposition activists.
   Gen. Saw Maung seized power in Burma in September and his troops
crushed dissent by killing hundreds of people. Millions of people
protested nationwide last year to demand an end to a quarter
century of military control of the government.
   ``The more oppressive the government becomes, the more turmoil
it will cause, and it may lead to a civil war in Burma,'' said Htun
Aung Gyaw, chairman of the All Burma Students Democratic Front. The
group is a Burmese dissident organization operating on the Thai
border.
</TEXT>
