<SECOND>PM-Jail Tours,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmen Can't Figure Out Why Tourists Want To Go To Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's not exactly Disneyland, but a new
jail and its robot food carts have become so popular with families
that a baffled sheriff decided to schedule more tours this week.
   ``We've had people with cameras and video cameras. It's amazing
to me,'' said Sheriff's Sgt. Harvey Lewis, who organized the tours
of the state-of-the- art facility.
   The $174 million Alameda County jail, about 25 miles east of San
Francisco, will be the sixth-largest county jail in the nation when
it opens in September. Plummer and his deputies were amazed when
more than 6,000 people showed up for free tours offered during two
weeks last month.
   About 2,500 showed up for the first Saturday tour _ more than
the number who tour the former federal prison on Alcatraz on an
average day.
   ``It may be a little like why people like to watch horror
movies. It's the unknown,'' said Sheriff Charles Plummer.
   Most of the visitors are families with children, senior groups
and scout troops.
   The new jail's biggest draw is its high-tech robot carts, which
will deliver food and linens throughout the compound.
   ``That's what we wanted to see, the little robots running
around,'' said Jim Sparano, 17. ``What's really amazing is that the
prisoners deserve so much. I figured it would be like old jail bars
and cells. It looks like a hotel.''
