<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Denmark     07-24 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Denmark,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Danish Tourist Suspected of Planning Attacks in Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly released court documents show that an
expelled Danish woman was suspected of planning an attack in
Israel, but she has denied the charges and her lawyer was quoted
today as saying she would sue Israel.
   Authorities expelled 25-year-old Ulla Lyngsby on July 14. She
had been questioned for 90 minutes upon her arrival in Israel on
July 6 and arrested two days later in the northern city of Haifa.
   Details of the case were censorsed until Sunday, when a Haifa
court released a document from her bail hearing on July 10 in
response to a request from Israeli journalists.
   The document included charges she was linked to Force 17, a
military arm of Yasser Arafat's Fatah faction of the Palestine
Liberation Organization. It said she planned to carry out attacks
on Israeli nationals.
   The document said the accusation was contained in material
provided by Israeli agents who investigated her. Her boyfriend,
Jihad Mishlawi, a Palestinian refugee from Lebanon, was identified
as the deputy chief of Force 17 in the documents.
   The Maariv daily newspaper said Ms. Lyngsby was sent by Force 17
to carry out a massacre at the closing ceremony of the Maccabiah
Games for Jewish athletes on July 13.
   The story said she also intended to assassinate the chief rabbi
of Denmark. He was to attend the ceremony at Jerusalem's Wailing
Wall, Judaism's holiest site.
   The charges reported by the paper did not appear in the court
documents released Sunday. Police said they could not comment
because the Shin Bet secret police had conducted the investigation.
   In the confession, Ms. Lyngsby admitted helping to obtain travel
itineraries of the chief rabbi and newspaper editor Herbert Pundik
for suspected attacks when they visited Israel.
   In Copenhagen, Denmark, the daily Berlingske Tidende quoted Ms.
Lyngsby's lawyer, Joergen Jacobsen, as saying she will sue Israeli
authorities for a ``symbolic'' sum of $4,730.
   Following her expulsion, she claimed she signed the confession
under duress in an effort to win her release. She said it was
written in Hebrew, a language she does not understand.
   The newspaper quoted her lawyer as saying she was never informed
of the charges against her.
   Prime Minister Poul Schlueter of Denmark said Friday that
authorities ``knew with certainty'' that a group of people in that
country were involved in assassination plans against Danish
citizens connected with Israel. He gave no specifics.
   He said no Danish charges would be pressed against Ms. Lyngsby.
But Denmark's foreign minister said it found no reason to protest
her arrest or expulsion.
   The daily Politiken in Copenhagen quoted the PLO Information
Office in that city as saying Force 17 had never been involved in
terrorism. The group said it had no knowledge of any plot to kill
the chief rabbi or other Danish Jews.
</TEXT>
