<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1137EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Madagascar     07-24 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Madagascar,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Station Seized in Coup Claim, But Government Asserts Control</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANTANANARIVO, Madagascar (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six armed men took over a
state-run radio station today and announced the government's
overthrow, but authorities quickly denied that a coup had occurred
and asserted they were in control.
   Apart from the seizure of the radio station, there were no
reports of violence. No injuries were reported at the station.
   In Antananarivo, the capital of this island off East Africa,
people went about their business as usual. The nation has about 10
million people.
   The armed men took over the station of Madagascar national radio
early today and broadcast a statement claiming the government of
President Didier Ratsiraka had been replaced. It said the country
was now being ruled by a group of opposition political leaders.
   Ratsiraka was in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, attending a summit of
the Organization of African Unity. It was not immediately possible
to determine if he intended to remain there.
   Two hours after the men seized the station, Information Minister
Simon Pierre broadcast a government message on national radio. He
denied that a coup had taken place and called for calm.
   That message, which was broadcast several times during the
morning, said an investigation was under way but provided no other
details.
   A later newscast said one of the armed men had been identified,
but that the other men had worn masks. It was not immediately known
if the men had been arrested.
   In April, three people died and about 73 were injured in clashes
with police after Ratsiraka's re-election.
   Opposition leaders said the elections were riddled with fraud
and called for the formation of a provisional government. They said
it should include representatives of the military, students and
churches and should yield power after new elections.
   Ratsiraka, initially chosen to rule by the military in 1975, was
re-elected to a third seven-year term on March 12 with about 62
percent of the vote.
</TEXT>
