<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Unrest     07-24 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abkhazia Unrest Spills into Soviet Georgian Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethnic unrest in Soviet Georgia spilled into the
republic's capital today, with hundreds of protesters marching
through the streets and bus traffic disrupted, according to
witnesses and official reports.
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev told the national legislature the unrest in
the Black Sea enclave of Abkhazia spread to Tbilisi, causing ``the
disorganization of transportation'' this morning, apparently
because of a strike.
   The Soviet president said ``the situation became acute'' in the
city in the Caucusus mountains, about 1,050 miles south of Moscow.
   The protest follows clashes between Georgians and Abkhazians in
the Georgia-ruled enclave of Abkhazia, a popular seaside vacation
area about 170 miles west of Tbilisi. Since the violence began July
15, 19 people have been reported killed and more than 400 injured.
   An editorial assistant at the Georgian news agency Gruzinform
said buses failed to appear in some areas of Tbilisi this morning
but were running by midday.
   The interruption of bus service appeared linked to a railway
strike that began over the weekend and ended today, the official
Tass news agency reported. The walkout stranded thousands of
tourists.
   Besides the transit strike, several hundred people demonstrated
throughout the day in central Tbilisi ``against what happened in
Abkhazia,'' the editor, Nana Gelashvili, said in a telephone
interview.
   ``When those Abkhazians started to knife Georgians, it just
drove us out of our minds,'' she said.
   No armed clashes have been reported in the area for the past two
days, Tass reported, although internal security troops and police
continued to confiscate weapons from extremists.
   Activists in Tbilisi proposed a general strike for today to
protest what they called a failure by authorities to protect
Georgians in Abkhazia.
   As a result of the violence, two regional party secretaries were
fired and two government leaders in Abkhazia lost their jobs
Saturday.
   Abkhazians and Georgians blame each other for the ethnic unrest.
Abkhazians, who are a minority in their own region, want greater
economic independence and cultural rights, while Georgians want the
fertile enclave retained as part of their Caucasus republic.
   Georgian leaders want to develop a dialogue over problems in the
region, but Abkhazians want the Kremlin to establish an outside
body to take control, news reports say.
   Protesters today called for resolution of the question of
Abkhazia's status and an end to the violence, Gelashvili said.
   At least 132 people have died in ethnic unrest during the past
month in the southern Soviet republics of Georgia, Azerbaijan,
Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan and Tadzhikistan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
