<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Who'saJew 1stLd-Writethru   07-24 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Who's a Jew, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0518,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Court Says Government Must Recognize Jewish Conversions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 4 grafs of comment from U.S. groups.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARIEH O'SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's Supreme Court ruled today that the
government must recognize Jewish conversions conducted abroad by
Reform and Conservative rabbis, deciding an issue that has put many
U.S. Jews at odds with Israel.
   The 4-1 decision immediately caused friction in Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir's Cabinet, where religious parties protested and one
faction threatened to resign.
   In a second decision, the court unanimously rejected an appeal
to allow Reform rabbis to perform marriages in Israel. That
decision upheld an Orthodox monopoly on conducting religious
weddings.
   Both of today's rulings were linked to the issue of ``Who is a
Jew?'' Israeli Orthodox Jews have sought to narrow that definition
under the Law of Return.
   The law now permits granting Israeli citizenship to anyone born
of a Jewish mother or who has converted to Judaism and does not
belong to another faith.
   The Orthodox want the definition to include only Jews born to
Jewish mothers or converted according to Jewish law known as
Halacha, which would effectively mean by Orthodox rabbis.
   The change has been fought by Conservative and Reform rabbis,
whose followers constitute a majority of more than 5 million U.S.
Jews but who have few adherents in Israel.
   The Reform and Conservative Jews contend the Orthodox proposal
would symbolically excommunicate them from Judaism and alienate
U.S. Jews from Israel.
   Rabbis estimate there are more than 10,000 conversions a year in
the United States, nearly all non-Orthodox.
   The Supreme Court, headed by Chief Justice Meir Shamgar, made
today's decision in a ruling on appeals by 12 U.S. immigrants and
one from Brazil. They were denied Israeli citizenship papers by the
Interior Ministry, which is controlled by the ultra-Orthodox Shas
Party.
   The court's 17-page ruling said a 1965 Israeli law did not
entitle the government to decide the validity of conversions by
different Jewish groups.
   Religious Affairs Minister Zevulun Hammer reacted to the ruling
by pledging to renew a political campaign for a narrower definition
of who is a Jew, Israel radio reported.
   Menachem Porush, a legislator of the ultra-Orthodox Agudat
Israel faction, said his party may withdraw its support from
Shamir's Cabinet. Such a move could sway other religious parties to
take similar actions.
   ``We have a secular court interfering in a religious subject. We
must view this very seriously,'' Porush told The Associated Press.
   Agudat is participating in the government for the first time. It
has traditionally refused to do so to avoid dealing in secular
affairs.
   The party holds five seats in the 120-seat Parliament. Its
executive council scheduled a meeting for later today to discuss
the issue.
   Gail Moskowitz, one of the U.S. immigrants in the court case,
said: ``I have been waiting for this for 2{ years. That's a long
time to not know where you stand. Now I know where I stand: on my
own feet and I'm Jewish.''
   ``I believe it is important to separate the issue of church and
state,'' said Elissa Ben-Rafael, a plaintiff from Chicago. She
joined the suit even though she was converted by an Orthodox rabbi.
   The marriage ruling came on appeals made seven years ago by the
Israeli Reform Judaism Movement; Israeli rabbi Mordechai Rotem; and
a rabbi from Baltimore, Moshe Zemer.
   In the 97-page decision, the justices upheld three laws which
effectively give Israel's Orthodox rabbis exclusive rights to
decide who may preside at marriages.
   Spokesman for several U.S. groups said they were pleased by the
decision on conversions.
   ``We believe that the court's action helps to preserve the unity
of the Jewish people so essential to Israel at the present critical
time,'' said George Gruen, director of Israeli and Middle Eastern
affairs for the American Jewish Committee in New York.
   ``I say hallelujah,'' said Carmela Kalmanson, president of
Hadassah, a women's Zionist organization in America with 385,000
members.
   Ms. Kalmanson said that though the numbers of people affected
``may be small, it was the perception that was very hurtful.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
