<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Korea-Soviet     07-24 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Korea-Soviet,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korea's First Economic Mission Leaves For Soviet Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea's first economic mission
to the Soviet Union left Monday to meet with Kremlin officials on a
proposed joint development of Siberian resources and other economic
cooperation.
   The 37-member private mission, representing construction,
fishery, coal and other industries, was led by Chung Ju-yung,
founder and honorary chairman of the Hyundai Group conglomerate.
   During their week-long visit, the South Koreans are to tour
Khabarovsk, Vladivostok, Nakhodka and Moscow.
   The Soviet Chamber of Commerce and the state-run Korea Trade
Promotion Corp. this year exchanged trade offices seeking direct
trade and other economic dealings.
   The Soviet Union, which has no diplomatic relations with Seoul,
is interested in using South Korean capital and expertise in
developing natural resources such as natural gas, coal and timber.
   Seoul officials hope economic exchanges between the two
countries will lead to formal relations. Moscow has diplomatic ties
with North Korea.
</TEXT>
