<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1241EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines     07-24 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aquino Admits Filipinos Still Poor; Teachers Demand Pay Rises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino told
legislators Monday that most Filipinos remain poor despite economic
gains during her three-year rule.
   In an address to a joint session of the House of Representatives
and Senate, Mrs. Aquino repeated promises to rid her government of
tax cheaters and grafters, and to purge the police and military of
criminals who made the crime situation ``nothing less than
terrible.''
   As she spoke, about 3,000 members of left-wing organizations
marched to protest corruption and alleged foreign control of Mrs.
Aquino's government and economic policies.
   Another group of about 3,000 public school teachers demonstrated
separately to demand salary increases.
   Mrs. Aquino said that despite a 20-year communist insurgency and
at least six coup attempts, her government succeeded in the past
three years in reviving the economy, increasing investment,
reducing unemployment and nibbling away at mass poverty.
   But the recovery ``has restored old fortunes far more
significantly than it has touched the lives of the vast majority''
of more than 55 million Filipinos, Mrs. Aquino said.
   ``Poverty has lessened but 5.3 million households, or 29 million
people, remain poor,'' she said. ``Unemployment has been reduced,
but try telling that to the 2.9 million still jobless and the 7.2
million underemployed.''
   Even the 500,000 families which statistically have crossed the
poverty line _ a monthly income of $119 for a family of six _ feel
nothing has changed, she said. ``I can't blame them: liberty is a
poor substitute for food.''
   She announced measures to help develop the countryside, where
most Filipinos live.
   Mrs. Aquino said she is ``tired of being taken to task'' for
continuing corruption and wants to leave clean and honest
government as her legacy.
   ``To my fellow workers in government specifically involved in
this area and in all other areas as well, let me say that unless
the public sees results soon, it will be good-bye for you,'' she
said. ``The compassion that marked my administration in the past
may generate doubts about my resolve in this matter, but the
actions that will be taken by me in the next weeks and months will
dispel them all.''
</TEXT>
