<HEAD>Army Investigating Fatal Helicopter Crash in Caifornia Desert</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs last 3 grafs pvs with 2 grafs to provide ages and hometowns
of victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army's Safety Center said today it is
investigating the cause of a helicopter crash that killed six
soldiers in the California desert during training exercises.
   ``It will take three to four months for the investigation,''
Col. Herbert Blanks, a spokesman for the safety center at Fort
Rucker, Ala., said in a telephone interview.
   The UH-60 Blackhawk helicopter went down about 4 a.m. Saturday
during a mission 14 miles northeast of Fort Irwin, Calif. Three
officers and three non-commissioned officers died in the crash. A
corporal suffered a broken leg, the Pentagon said.
   All the soldiers involved were from the 1st Cavalry Division
based in Fort Hood, Texas. They were at the 1,000-square-mile base
120 miles northeast of Los Angeles for a three-week training
exercise that ended Saturday.
   Blanks said the crash was the fourth by a UH-60 since October.
There were five such accidents last fiscal year, he said, adding:
``There is no abnormal trend, not when you consider the amount of
hours they fly.''
   The colonel said no repeated structural flaws have been found.
   ``The majority of our accidents are human error,'' he said.
   At the Pentagon, those killed in the crash were identified as
Lt. Col. William C. Whittingstall, 40, Iowa Park, Texas; Capt.
Marlon D. Joseph, 33, Houston; 1st Lt. Robert B. Wilson, 26,
Dumfries, Va.; Chief Warrant Officer 4 Roy A. Westbrook, 42,
Poteet, Texas; Chief Warrant Officer 3 Adelbert L. Morrow, 41,
Hemat, Calif.; and Staff Sgt. Stephen P. Thompson, 28, Sacramento,
Calif.
   The wounded soldier was identified as Scott A. Matthews, 24, of
Corpus Christi, Texas.
</TEXT>
