<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Beaches     07-24 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Italy-Beaches,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adriatic Region Approves Emergency Funds for Slimy Coast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOLOGNA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Emilia-Romagna region on Monday
approved $17 million in emergency funds to help clean up its
algae-infested coastal waters.
   The money will be used to aid the region's tourism and fishing
industries, devastated by the algae which first appeared in early
July.
   The government recently approved $100 million in emergency aid
for the Adriatic but has yet to implement any measures.
   The algae that has spread along beaches in the Friuli, Veneto,
Marche and Emilia-Romagna regions is moving to the south, news
reports said Monday.
   Officials in the Abruzzo region said the algae spoiled several
beaches over the weekend and hotel operators fear the same tourist
flight that has hurt the resort industry in the north.
   On Sunday, 300 fishing boats tried to increase the Adriatic's
oxygen supply by cruising back and forth to churn up the water.
Despite this effort, fish, crustaceans and mollusks have died from
lack of oxygen caused by the algae.
   Affected are areas of the northern Adriatic from Venice to
Pescara.
