<FIRST>r w PM-US-Japan     07-24 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Japan,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Expects Close Ties with Japan to Continue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration expects close ties
with Japan to continue regardless of who is chosen to succeed the
fallen government of Prime Minister Sousuke Uno, the White House
said today.
   Marlin Fitzwater, President Bush's spokesman, said he had no
direct comment on the election results in Japan ``simply because
it's an internal matter.''
   ``However, the United States has long and strong relationships
with Japan. We certainly would expect those to continue under any
successor government,'' said Fitzwater.
   ``We don't have any idea who that successor will be. But whoever
it is we look forward to working with them, to establishing
friendly and productive ties of a kind that we have had in the
past,'' he said.
   Uno and his ruling Liberal Democratic Party lost its majority in
the upper house of the Diet for the first time in 34 years. Uno
announced today he would resign, saying he accepted ``the
responsibility for this defeat wholly upon myself.''
   Fitzwater said the United States and Japan are bound by their
trading ties and militarily. ``We would expect to maintain all of
those ties in a solid fashion,'' he said.
   But he said the U.S. government would continue to ``press rather
vigorously'' with the new government on trade problems. ``That can
be done in a positive fashion, and that's the way we expect to do
it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
