<FIRST>u i PM-PuertoRico-Bombings 1stLd-Writethru a0540 07-24 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Puerto Rico-Bombings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0540,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explosions Damage Army Recruiting Station, Post Office, Supermarket</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs with claim of responsibility; picks up 3rd
pvs, `Police said...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pipe bombs exploded at a U.S. Army
recruiting station, a post office and other offices in a shopping
center early today, police reported.
   Police reported no injuries in the bombings, the latest in a
series of attacks on U.S. government facilities.
   An anonymous caller told radio station WKAQ that the two bombs
had been placed by the Puerto Rican Revolutionary Forces, a
little-known pro-independence group. Police could not confirm the
authencity of the claim.
   The anonymous male caller said the bombing was to protest the
presence of military bases in Puerto Rico and the present
commonwealth status.
   Police said the explosive devices went off at 2 a.m. at the
shopping center about 10 miles east of San Juan, causing
``considerable'' damage to the recruiting office, the post office
and a supermarket.
   The FBI and local police were investigating.
   Two explosive devices went off last week at post offices in the
towns of Coamo and Guayama.
   In June, the Borinquen Popular Army, also known as the Los
Macheteros, or machete wielders, claimed responsibility for a bomb
that caused heavy damage to a U.S. Army recruiting station and a
branch of the Bank of Boston in Bayamon, about 15 miles northwest
of San Juan. Borinquen was Puerto Rico's name before the Spanish
conquest of the island.
   Similar explosions, with no injuries and minor damage, occurred
in June at a U.S. Customs office in the southern city of Ponce and
at a Chase Manhattan Bank branch in Caguas, about 20 miles south of
San Juan. No group claimed responsibility for those blasts.
   Los Macheteros is a militant pro-independence group that has
been relatively inactive in recent years. During the 1970s, the
organization blew up five National Guard fighter jets valued at $47
million and ambushed a U.S. Navy vehicle, killing two sailors and
injuring 10 others.
   Sixteen alleged members were charged in the $7 million robbery
of a Wells Fargo depot in Hartford, Conn., in 1983. The FBI alleged
that the Macheteros intended to use the stolen money to finance
their campaign to gain independence for Puerto Rico.
   Ojeda Rios, 55, still faces trial in Hartford and is currently
being tried in San Juan's U.S. District Court on separate charges
stemming from the wounding of an FBI agent during his 1985 arrest
in Puerto Rico.
   The explosions came one day before Puerto Rico Constitution Day,
which is an island holiday. The Constitution, approved 37 years
ago, established the island's commonwealth relationship with the
United States.
   In a referendum scheduled for 1991, voters on the island
territory will have the choice of statehood, independence or
continued commonwealth status.
   Puerto Rico, with 3.3 million mostly Spanish-speaking people,
became a U.S. territory in 1898 and has been a commonwealth since
1952.
</TEXT>
