<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1345EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India-Storms     07-24 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Storms,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Downpours in Western India Kill at Least 100</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOMBAY, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Torrential downpours in western India on
Monday triggered flash floods and landslides that collapsed houses,
and one report said at least 100 people had died.
   The deaths were reported by the United News of India news agency
in coastal Maharashtra state after the rain flooded rivers and high
winds knocked down houses and trees.
   At least 13 people died in Bombay, the state capital, according
to police.
   An official at Bombay's meterological office said 11 inches of
rain was recorded in 24 hours. It is the highest figure recorded in
one day since July 2, 1984, when 22 inches of rain fell.
   The rain was accompanied by winds gusting up to 52 mph, the
official said.
   Bus and train services in the city were suspended and roads were
inundated with waist-deep water. Trucks were stranded in swirling
waters and several villages were cut off, police said.
   Transactions at the stock exchange, India's largest, were
suspended, said M.R. Mayya, an exchange official.
   The army was called out in the districts of Beed, Deglur and
Biloli to rescue the residents of 46 villages that had been
surrounded by floodwaters.
   At least 2,400 fishermen were reported missing after they were
caught on the seas during the storm, the news agency said.
</TEXT>
