<FIRST>r i AM-China-Floods     07-24 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Floods,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Floods Batter China, 117 More Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain in northern China touched off floods
and landslides that killed at least 117 people, destroyed thousands
of buildings, and ravaged crops, official reports said Monday.
   Some of the deaths were caused by Typhoon Hope, which struck
China on Thursday. Up to 14 inches of rain has fallen in some
places, the English-language China Daily said.
   At least 1,400 flood-related deaths already have been reported
in China this summer.
   The China Daily said 41 people were killed and 381 people
injured in landslides caused by torrential rains last week in
Dandong, in the northeastern province of Liaoning.
   The rail line between Dandong, a coastal city on the North
Korean border, and the provincial capital of Shenyang was washed
out in 65 places, the report said. More than 16,000 buildings were
destroyed.
   In neighboring Jilin province, 43 people have died since
Saturday in floods and mudslides, the China Youth News said. It
also reported 22 people missing.
   Typhoon Hope killed 21 people in Zhejiang province and 36 in
Fujian province, the China Daily said.
   In Fujian's Zhanghe county, 4,000 homes were destroyed,
authorities said. At least 8,151 acres of crops, 12,500 tons of
grain, and 1,000 pigs were washed away since Saturday, they said.
   The storm also cut telecommunications and transport in that area.
   Heavy rains and mudslides in northern China have killed four
people in Beijing, according to previous reports. China Daily said
12 people still were missing in Fengjiayuan, near Beijing, after a
mudslide Saturday.
   Flooding has been severe in southern and central China since the
beginning of June.
   Yang Zhenhuai, deputy director of the State Flood Control
Headquarters, said about 2,700 people die annually in floods.
</TEXT>
