<FIRST>u a PM-Iran-Contra 3rdLd-Writethru a0579-a0532 07-24 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0579-a0532,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Temporarily Delays Iran-Contra Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs, with minor editing.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court today temporarily
delayed the Iran-Contra trial of the CIA's former station chief in
Costa Rica.
   The appeals court in Richmond issued an emergency stay at the
request of the Justice Department, putting off the trial of Joseph
Fernandez in order to address national security issues that are
threatening to kill the case.
   U.S. District Court Judge Claude Hilton told a pool of
prospective jurors to go home, saying he would call them back after
the appeals court has an opportunity to rule on the national
security questions.
   Earlier today, Hilton rejected motions by the prosecutors in the
case which would have allowed the CIA to protect details of some of
its programs and the names of three of its stations and facilities
in Latin America from disclosure in the courtroom during the
Fernandez trial.
   Fernandez was to go on trial today on four criminal charges of
obstructing and making false statements to the CIA inspector
general's office and the Tower Commission.
   Fernandez allegedly tried to cover up his assistance to Oliver
North's secret supply effort to the Nicaraguan Contras.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Richmond will consider
the Justice Department's request to intervene in the Fernandez case
and Hilton's refusal to bar disclosure of the specifics about the
CIA stations and programs.
   In court, Hilton rejected proposals by the government that would
have limited disclosures about CIA stations and programs at the
trial of Fernandez.
   Fernandez says he needs to present the information about the
agency's stations and programs in his defense.
   One proposal presented by Laurence Shtasel, who is prosecuting
Fernandez, would have referred to CIA stations and facilities in
Latin American countries by a series of numbers rather than by
name. Hilton rejected that proposal.
   The judge also rejected a proposal Shtasel made Friday in which
the government offered to drop a portion of the case in exchange
for not allowing disclosure of three highly sensitive CIA programs
in Costa Rica. Hilton said it was important to Fernandez's defense
that he be allowed to refer in open court to the programs.
   The Justice Department's seeking of an appeals court delay was a
last-ditch attempt to avoid filing an unprecedented national
security affidavit that would kill the case.
   Fernandez is charged with lying and giving misleading statements
to the CIA inspector general's office and to Congress in an alleged
coverup of assistance to Oliver North's secret Contra resupply
network.
   U.S. intelligence experts spent the weekend with Justice
Department officials drafting an affidavit detailing national
secrets that they will not alow to emerge in the trial.
   Independent counsel Lawrence Walsh's office said Friday the
Fernandez case would be untriable if the Justice Department's
affidavit barred disclosure of too a wide range of material.
   ``If the CIA's request for a broader ... affidavit is granted,
the case will be untriable,'' prosecutors said in court papers.
   With a Justice Department affidavit in hand, Hilton would have
no choice under federal law but to prohibit the ex-CIA operative
from using in his defense the classified information detailed in
the affidavit.
   That could lead to the judge dismissing some or all the criminal
charges, depending on the scope of the affidavit.
   Fernandez was charged with two counts each of making false
statements and obstruction of an inquiry by the congressional Tower
Commission and the CIA's office of inspector general.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
