<FIRST>r i AM-China-Movie     07-24 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Movie,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Movie About Deng Opens, But Audience Seems Unimpressed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The major summer film, a period piece about
senior leader Deng Xiaoping, opened Monday in Beijing and added to
the clamor of praise for the man blamed by many Chinese for the
recent military crackdown.
   ``The Baise Uprising'' has as its hero a 25-year-old Deng
leading the peasants of remote Baise in southern China to victory
over Nationalist troops in 1929. The Nationalists ultimately lost a
bloody civil war to the communists and retreated to the island
province of Taiwan in 1949.
   The movie's opening comes less than two months after the
government called in troops to put down a student-led pro-democracy
movement, killing hundreds and perhaps thousands of people. Many
Chinese say they have lost confidence in the government as a
result, and many hold Deng responsible for the killings.
   ``The Baise Uprising'' fits neatly into the ideological
education all Chinese are required to undergo.
   Most of those who attended the opening day showings at two
Beijing theaters were organized by their work units, and the movie
could be required viewing for many Chinese. It opens nationwide on
Aug. 1, the anniversary of the founding of the People's Liberation
Army.
   Unless Chinese are told to see the movie, many doubtless would
not pay the steep admission fee of about 67 cents _ five times the
price of most films.
   In the one-hour, 45-minute film, Deng is portrayed as a
confident, level-headed and charismatic leader with all the
answers. But the film also shows a human side that one rarely sees
in revolutionary-style movies.
   There are scenes of Deng, an avid bridge player, playing cards
and telling a young girl that the strategies involved in playing
bridge and chess are much like fighting a war.
   He also is depicted as a music lover who carries a record player
with him on his campaign to Baise. When townspeople ask him to sing
a song from his native Sichuan province, he brings out the record
player and puts on music from ``Carmen.''
   The media has given enormous publicity to the movie, which was
made to mark the 60th anniversary of the Baise uprising and the
40th anniversary of communist rule.
   The People's Daily, the party newspaper, on Saturday devoted
half a page to the film, with articles writen by Lu Qi, who played
Deng, and Chen Jialin, the director.
   State-run TV last week broadcast a story on the movie's
premiere, showing Vice President Wang Zhen shaking hands with
actors. Wang and other top leaders supervised the movie's
production, according to the People's Daily.
   Despite the build-up, the audience at one afternoon showing at
Beijing's Capital Theater seemed unimpressed. There was very little
audience reaction, with only laughter during the two times Deng
tells his followers to ``seek truth from facts,'' a slogan he has
made famous in the past decade.
   Comments after the movie also lacked enthusiasm. A few people
said, ``It was OK.'' Others just shrugged their shoulders and
walked away. One young woman said it was worth watching, but didn't
say why.
   The audience reaction was in stark contrast to another movie
that opened a month ago in Beijing.
   During the opening of ``The Towering Kunlun,'' about Mao
Tse-tung's battles with the Nationalists in central China,
audiences applauded scenes of students demonstrating. They also
clapped when U.S. Ambassador Leighton Stuart promised money for
weapons to the Nationalists, but only if Nationalist leader Chiang
Kai-shek did not to use the weapons against the students. Stuart's
comment since has been cut from the movie and the demonstration
scene has been shortened.
   Theater employees reportedly informed on those who cheered. That
could explain the muted audience reaction to scenes in ``Baise
Uprising,'' including an incident in which Nationalist troops shot
at student demonstrators.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
