<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1413EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     07-24 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seoul Says it Will Arrest Student Coming Home From North Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea said Monday it will arrest
a radical student who plans to return from North Korea via the
border at Panmunjom as a symbol of national unification.
   Prime Minister Kang Young-hoon called an emergency meeting of
key Cabinet ministers and the government later said it asked the
U.S.-led United Nations Command to warn communist North Korea it
will deny entry to radical student Im Su-kyong if she tries to
cross the sensitive border area.
   A spokesman for the command, which polices the armistice in the
southern half of the demilitarized zone, said it will not interfere
in inter-Korean politics.
   The border is guarded by heavily armed troops and passage from
one side to the other without mutual agreement is considered a
violation of the truce that ended the 1950-53 Korean War.
   South Korea, already angry at unauthorized visits to North Korea
by a dissident clergyman, a lawmaker and Ms. Im, said she will be
arrested and charged with violating the national security law.
   Ms. Im, 20, has said she will cross the border Thursday, the
anniversary of the cease-fire, to dramatize radical and dissident
demands for unification of the divided peninsula. She flew to North
Korea via third countries this month to attend an international
youth festival.
   A Seoul newspaper said if Ms. Im crosses the border, Korean
soldiers attached to the U.N. command have been ordered to arrest
her.
   There are no physical boundaries in the truce village of
Panmunjom. A person allowed access into the joint security area
from either side would find it relatively easy to walk across.
   South Korean President Roh Tae-woo said Monday that Ms. Im's
plan is an example of extreme leftist thinking and he warned
college students not to take their freedom for granted.
   Also on Monday, six students armed with firebombs, pipes, tear
gas shells and leaflets demanding the withdrawal of American troops
tried to break into the U.S. Information Center in Seoul.
   The students fled as police arrived. Two were arrested.
   Radical students said they will rally in Seoul to welcome home
Ms. Im and protest plans to arrest her. The radical National
Council of Student Representatives said it also will demonstrate to
denounce the armistice agreement and the presence of 43,000 U.S.
troops in South Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   Also Monday, the national intelligence agency issued its third
summons to Kim Dae-jung, head of the leading opposition Party for
Peace and Democracy, asking he make himself available for
questioning about a party lawmaker charged with espionage and
making an unauthorized visit to North Korea.
   Kim said he knows nothing about the case of legislator Suh
Kyung-won and accuses the government of trying to make him appear
pro-communist. The intelligence agency said it will get a court to
order Kim's cooperation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
