<FIRST>r w AM-US-Japan     07-24 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Japan,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Expects Close Ties With Japan to Continue</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Japan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House said Monday it expects to
maintain close ties with Japan regardless of who succeeds the
fallen Sousuke Uno as prime minister.
   Marlin Fitzwater, President Bush's spokesman, said Sunday's
elections, in which Uno's Liberal Democrats lost control of the
upper house of parliament, were ``an internal matter.''
   ``The United States has long and strong relationships with
Japan,'' Fitzwater said. ``We certainly would expect those to
continue under any successor government.''
   Uno announced Monday he would resign as prime minister. His
resignation will open the way to dissolving Uno's Cabinet and
restructuring the governing party's leadership.
   ``We don't have any idea who that successor will be,'' Bush's
spokesman said. ``But, whoever it is, we look forward to working
with them, to establishing friendly and productive ties of a kind
that we have had in the past.''
   Fitzwater said the United States and Japan are bound
economically and militarily, and ``we would expect to maintain all
of those ties in a solid fashion.''
   But he said the U.S. government would continue to ``press rather
vigorously'' on trade problems with the new government.
   Fitzwater also said that a non-binding congressional resolution
calling for restrictions on the FSX jet fighter deal with Japan
``faces a very heavy veto threat'' from the president.
   Several senior advisers have urged Bush to reject the measure as
an intrusion on executive branch deliberations and because it
``compromises the president's ability'' to manage foreign affairs,
Fitzwater said.
   Bush has until July 31 to act on the FSX resolution, but will
probably make his decision before then, Fitzwater said.
   Regardless of what course Bush takes, the joint development deal
will go through because the congressional resolution is
non-binding, Fitzwater said. Congress never passed a binding
resolution disapproving the joint venture.
   Under the FSX deal, General Dynamics Corp. and Mitsubishi Heavy
Industries Ltd. will jointly develop the new fighter for Japan
based on an improved F-16 design. Japan had been set to develop a
jet fighter by itself until then-Defense Secrtary Caspar Weinberger
talked the Japanese into the joint development, which ensures U.S.
companies 40 percent of the revenues from the project.
   Critics in the Senate and elsewhere have charged the deal will
give the Japanese access to U.S. technology they could use to
develop a domestic airplane industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890724-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1415EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Baker-Cambodia     07-24 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baker-Cambodia,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secretary of State To Attend Weekend Talks in Paris</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III will
attend a conference on Cambodia's future next weekend in Paris,
working for a settlement that rules out a return to power of the
Khmer Rouge, the State Department announced today.
   A U.S. official said Baker probably will meet there with Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze. That session could begin
preliminary planning for a summit meeting between President Bush
and Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The month-long conference, involving the five permanent members
of the U.N. Security Council _ the United States, the Soviet Union,
China, Britain and France _ is designed to map out Cambodia's
future after the last Vietnamese troops leave the country at the
end of September.
   ``We hope our collective efforts can become another example of
how we, the Soviets and others can work together to resolve
regional conflicts,'' State Department spokeswoman Margaret
Tutwiler said in making the announcement.
   Baker and the other foreign ministers plan to attend the opening
session. The conference will then proceed through the month of
August in the form of working-level groups.
   The departure of Vietnamese troops, which backed up a pro-Hanoi
and pro-Moscow government in Phnom Penh, was long a U.S. foreign
policy goal.
   ``With an international, verified Vietnamese withdrawal, we hope
to see a beginning of an end to the tragedy that has beset the
Cambodian people for years, and a beginning of a transition to
genuine Cambodian self-determination,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   Her statement said a settlement had to ensure peace in Cambodia
by containing three key elements:
   _A verified withdrawal of Vietnamese forces.
   _Prevention of a return to power by the Khmer Rouge, who have
been implicated in the killings of as many as 1 million Cambodians
during the 1970s.
   _Self-determination for the Cambodian people.
   ``Given the legacy of warfare in Cambodia and the tragedies of
the past it will be difficult to achieve peace,'' Ms. Tutwiler
said. ``But it is necessary to try. It is time to at least try to
end the suffering of the Cambodian people. We hope the day is near
when the Cambodian people will be able to live in peace and achieve
true self-determination.''
</TEXT>
