<FIRST>u a PM-Honeywell 1stLd-Writethru a0539 07-24 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honeywell, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0539,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honeywell Announces Sweeping Plan To Enhance Shareholder Value</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT to annual dividend, sted fourth-quarter;
A version moved on the business wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honeywell Inc., subject of intense takeover
speculation for the past several weeks, said today it will cut
4,000 jobs, reduce its weapons business, repurchase shares and
increase dividends.
   The sweeping restructuring will result in a 65-cent increase in
the company's annual dividend, to $2.75 a share, and possibly
include a special cash dividend, said James Renier, chairman of the
controls maker and defense contractor.
   The news prompted a sharp increase in Honeywell stock on the New
York Stock Exchange. In early morning trading, the stock was up
$3.75 a share to $89.25.
   The program will include the sale of a ``substantial portion''
of Honeywell's 50 percent stake in Yamatake-Honeywell, a Japanese
controls maker, Renier said. Analysts have valued the holding at
about $1 billion.
   Honeywell also will reduce its weapons business, which accounts
for about 20 percent of its revenues. Honeywell spokeswoman Kathy
Tunheim would not say if a sale of the business is one of the
options being considered.
   The program will include elimination of 4,000 jobs worldwide
over the next 18 months, including 300 corporate staff positions
targeted in a previous announcement. Tunheim said the company is
not ready to announce specific locations for the job cuts.
   Honeywell employs about 78,000 workers worldwide. Many of the
job losses will come through attrition, but layoffs will be
necessary, Tunheim said.
   Honeywell's board of directors also has broadened a company
stock repurchase plan from about 3.5 million shares to 10 million
shares. The stock will be bought on the open market, Renier said.
   The program should improve operating profits by about $150
million over the next 18 months, Renier said.
   Negotiations to sell the company's stake in Yamatake-Honeywell,
which is listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange, will begin within a
few days, Tunheim said. She would not identify potential buyers.
Japanese investors currently own half of the company, she said.
   Renier said the reduction of Honeywell's weapons business is
part of a strategy begun in 1988 to ``concentrate on core controls
businesses that principally serve commercial markets as well as the
market for military and space controls.''
   Honeywell is the leading manufacturer of torpedoes for the Navy
and also supplies small, medium and large ammunition to the Army,
Tunheim said.
   John McManus of Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York
said the action could deter a takeover attempt, but not guarantee
independence for Honeywell.
   ``They are trying to basically boost the stock price to make it
more difficult for someone to take them over,'' McManus said. ``It
will also alleviate some of the large shareholders who have been
pounding on the door.''
   Honeywell's stock price has risen sharply in the last two weeks
following published reports that General Electric Co. was
considering acquiring the company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
