<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1431EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SexOffenders     07-24 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sex Offenders,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sex Offenders Waive Chance at Parole to Seek Treatment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY REEVES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNION SPRINGS, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Alabama inmates have temporarily
waived their chances at parole so they can participate in an
18-month prison treatment program for sex offenders.
   Convicted rapist Robert Mosley said in an interview last week
that agreeing to give up a May 1990 parole review, his first, was
not difficult.
   ``I need the treatment more than I need my freedom,'' said
Mosley, 28, serving a 10-year sentence imposed in 1986.
   Because of his commitment to the program he and the four others
are next due for parole consideration in January 1991.
   Samuel Gardner, in prison for 16 years since being convicted of
rape, said waiving his chance to escape a 99-year term was the only
way he had to help himself. He was to have had a February 1990
parole hearing.
   ``I came to the conclusion that if they let me out on the day I
was thinking about, I would be back here in a month,'' said
Gardner, 38, previously denied release in 1986 and 1988. ``I don't
want no more victims.''
   Mosley, Gardner and the other three who waived parole hearing
dates are among 26 inmates participating in the state's sexual
offender treatment program at the Bullock County Correctional
Facility, said director Pamela Van Wyk. The five are the first to
give up a chance at release to seek treatment.
   The five were required to sign away their chance at parole
during the 18-month period to ensure they would be able to finish
therapy, said Merle Frieson, director of mental health treatment
for the state prison system.
   The program includes group sessions and exercises to enable
inmates to overcome sexual arousal that leads to acts like rape and
child molestation, Frieson said.
   ``The treatment is rugged enough ... that you have to have to be
highly motivated to complete it,'' he said.
   Ms. Van Wyk said only inmates who admit to their crimes and to
having a sex-related problem are admitted to the program.
   For inmate Raymond McLoyd, confessing that he was the only one
responsible for his 1978 rape conviction was the hardest part.
   ``I did what I wanted to do. My thinking was just so twisted,
distorted,'' a weeping McLoyd said last week. He has been denied
parole three times and put off his next hearing for nine months to
enter the program.
   Ms. Van Wyk said the treatment is intended to teach inmates how
to control their perverse desires when confronted with situations
they find sexually exciting.
   While the men might always be excited by certain images or
sounds, Ms. Van Wyk said, they can learn to quell their dangerous
impulses.
   ``We're not curing anything. We're teaching people to control
their arousal,'' she said.
   Ms. Van Wyk said officials do not know if the program is a
success. Of 26 inmates who have completed the 18-month program,
none has gone before the parole board and only one has completed
his sentence.
   ``And the real test is when they get back on the street,'' she
said.
   A similar program in Canada has had a 50 percent to 60 percent
success rate in steering sex offenders away from more assaults, Ms.
Van Wyk said, and Alabama officials would be pleased with similar
results.
   Warren Gaston, executive director of the State Board of Pardons
and Paroles, said he was unsure how the board would look upon sex
offenders who have completed the program.
   But while the board is reluctant to release rapists and child
molesters, he said, the inmates' willingness to stay in prison for
treatment is ``rather remarkable.''
</TEXT>
