<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--SurfDrownings     07-24 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Surf Drownings,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>3 Drown in Treacherous Ocean Conditions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SURFSIDE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High wind created treacherous currents in
which three tourists drowned off unguarded southern Florida
beaches, and Miami Beach lifeguards made at least 15 successful
rescues, officials said.
   Beach Patrol Chief Ray Sforza said the rip-tide remained
dangerous Monday. ``It's insidious,'' he said.
   While the patrol didn't close the beaches Sunday, swimmers were
warned to avoid the currents after the first two drownings. But
many stayed in the ocean _ some within sight of the blanket-covered
corpses on the beach.
   The National Weather Service said strong easterly wind caused
rip currents, which develop when strong waves bring a lot of water
close to the shore. The water then opens up gaps in sandbars and
rushes back out to the ocean through channels.
   ``With each days you have same conditions, it exacerbates the
rip currents,'' Sforza said. ``You get more and more sandbar breaks
up and down the coast, so you have more rip currents.''
</TEXT>
