<HEAD>`Beauty and the Beast' Will Return To CBS With Two-Hour Movie</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fans of ``Beauty and the Beast'' howled when
CBS left it off its fall schedule, but now the network has
announced the weekly saga will return with a surprising two-hour
movie.
   ``It is going to be a real corker, and I don't want it to get
out,'' CBS Entertainment President Kim LeMasters said of the movie
plot Saturday during a speech at a TV critics convention.
   LeMasters said the series, about the love between a beautiful
woman and a man-beast who lives in a subterranean world beneath New
York City, would veer away from the love story and that star Linda
Hamilton would have a ``reduced presence.''
   Miss Hamilton is expecting a baby, but LeMasters would not say
if she would return full-time after her baby is born. Ron Perlman
plays the leonine, Shakespeare-quoting beast, Vincent.
   LeMasters said CBS kept the show in production, because ``it's
one of the better-done shows we have on the network.'' He said it
was initially dropped because executives thought the series had
begun to ``implode on itself.''
   ``Those stories between Vincent and Catherine just got more and
more narrow and we were unable to explore issues that we want to
explore. We think that we have corrected the problem, and what
we're going to do, we're going to re-launch it as a two-hour movie
that will have some rather stunning details attendant to it.''
