<FIRST>r a AM-Posey-Contras     07-24 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Posey-Contras,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Posey's Contra Mission Back on Track After Court Victory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLINT CITY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A self-described freedom fighter says
his mission to aid the Contra rebels fighting the Nicaraguan
government is back on track since a federal judge dismissed treaty
violation charges against him.
   The criminal indictment charging Tom Posey and five others with
violating the Neutrality Act by supporting the Contras was
dismissed July 13 by a federal judge in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
   The Neutrality Act allows prosecution of anyone making war from
U.S. soil against a nation with which the United States is at peace.
   But U.S. District Judge Norman Roettger agreed with the defense
that the Reagan administration waged war against the Sandinistas in
1984-85 despite congressional votes to cut off funds.
   Posey, 44, a co-founder of Civilian Materiel Assistance, said in
an interview in Sunday's editions of The Birmingham News that his
legal battles have ruined his produce business and cost him
$100,000 in legal fees.
   But he said he's not bitter and hasn't abandoned the goal he and
a few conservatives set for themselves when they created CMA in
1984 _ fighting communism when, where and how they can, with
Central America first on the list.
   Although professing no bitterness, Posey does express some
disillusionment with Washington after all of his problems.
   ``I look at the White House people as more worried about their
retirement and reputation than truth and justice,'' he said.
   ``He (President Reagan) is the one who said the buck stops here,
but when it got hot, he let it pass on through,'' Posey said.
   Posey is preparing for the annual CMA convention in Madison Aug.
3-6, where Contra leader Adolfo Calero and at least two top Contra
field commanders will speak. He is sending more than 1,000
invitations.
   His budget comes primarily from the sale of CMA caps, shirts,
belt buckles and a recently completed videotape of the Contras in
action.
   The tape features a Soviet-made Hind-24 ``flying tank''
helicopter being shot down by Contras armed with U.S. Redeye
missiles.
   Posey said it's ``the only known footage'' of the
top-of-the-line Soviet chopper going down. CMA literature promises
that it will ``get your blood boiling.''
   Posey said CMA's activities will remain in the field of of
supplying non-lethal support to the Contra soldiers, away from the
field of battle.
</TEXT>
