<DOCNO> AP890724-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1458EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Vienna-Spies Bjt   07-24 0892</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vienna-Spies, Bjt,0915</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vienna _ Traditional Center for East-West Spying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investigation of senior diplomat
Felix S. Bloch on suspicion he spied for the Soviets has again
turned the spotlight on Vienna as a hotbed of East-West espionage
and intrigue.
   Orson Welles' depiction of Harry Lime in the 1949 film ``The
Third Man'' stamped on the minds of millions an image of devious
dealings in the Austrian capital, which, like Berlin, was divided
into British, French, American and Soviet sectors after World War
II.
   Former Nazis and refugees from Eastern Europe struggled to
survive in the postwar turmoil, selling knowledge to any side that
would pay and helping to weave a net of intrigue.
   The Soviets withdrew their forces from Austria in 1955, but they
left behind a large embassy and many other offices that Western
intelligence agencies always have viewed as potential helpers of
the KGB and the GRU, Soviet military intelligence.
   Intelligence sources in Washington say nearly every American
taken to court on charges of spying for the Soviets in the past
five years had come to Vienna to meet KGB officers.
   The Soviets are as aware as the Americans that these trips often
are part of the evidence used by the FBI. Some intelligence sources
believe, therefore, that one purpose of the trip to Vienna is to
get a blackmail hold over the American, threatening exposure of a
hard-to-explain journey if he wants to wriggle out of his deal with
the KGB.
   Americans who have made Vienna trips include Ronald Pelton, the
National Security Agency officer who tipped Moscow to a system that
hid U.S. submarines from Soviet radar, and John Walker, head of the
family spy ring in the U.S. Navy.
   Court documents in the Walker case included written instructions
from the KGB about how to ``drop'' information, including a
detailed description of doing a walking ``pass'' on a Vienna street.
   It was also in Vienna that Marine Clayton Lonetree confessed to
a security breach in the U.S. Embassy in Moscow.
   A Soviet defector who worked for the GRU in Vienna in the 1970s
described Moscow's elaborate intelligence network in the Austrian
capital in a 1985 memoir, ``Aquarium,'' published in Britain.
Viktor Suvorov (not his real name) said detailed procedures were
worked out to avoid immediate identification by Austrian and other
security services in Vienna of agents in the embassy.
   He estimated about 80 percent of all Soviets in Vienna _ where
Moscow has an Aeroflot office, trade representations, and a large
diplomatic presence at the United Nations _ engaged in ``other
work'' outside their official duties.
   Part of the elaborate coverup of Soviet intelligence work,
according to Suvorov, was to assign active agents, such as himself,
mostly to work outside Austria.
   But most of the work, he said, focused on acquiring Western
technology and contingency plans for military or economic crises.
   It is not known what information, if any, Bloch handed to the
Soviets during his seven years in Vienna, where he arrived in 1980
as head of the U.S. Embassy's economics section. He became deputy
chief of mission, a post he held for years before returning to
Washington in 1987.
   However, his position would have put Bloch, a native Austrian
who left the country at age 3 with his Jewish parents, at the
center of sensitive U.S.-Austrian negotiations over the illegal
transfer of Western technology through Vienna to the East bloc.
   Several Viennese shipping agents and firms have come under
scrutiny in the past decade amid U.S. allegations they helped the
Soviets and their allies to acquire technology that was banned for
export to the East.
   Austrian intelligence sources say they do keep a careful watch
for illegal activities. Austrian Foreign Minister Alois Mock, a
close friend of Bloch, bristled Monday when reporters suggested
Vienna was a hotbed of spying.
   ``These regrettable events are not more numerous than
elsewhere,'' Mock said, allowing however that Vienna is perhaps
exposed because of its ``geographical position'' just an hour's
ride from the Czechoslovak and Hungarian borders.
   There are tens of thousands of Soviet and East European
scientists, emigres, diplomats and other officials in Vienna,
making blanket surveillance tough.
   In 1981, Soviet researcher Arkady Belozerov denied reports he
had spied but caused a stir when he resigned from a post at the
prestigious Institute for Applied Systems Analysis, a 17-nation
project south of Vienna that has attracted hundreds of Soviet
researchers since it was set up in 1972.
   A neighboring institute in the same town of Laxenburg was in the
news the same year when Josef Hodic, a Czechoslovak historian who
had been granted asylum in Austria as a signatory of the Charter 77
human rights appeal, suddenly disappeared.
   Hodic turned up in Prague, where state-run media said he had
been working all along as a Czechoslovak agent.
   One of the most mysterious cases centered on Vienna was that of
Nikolai Shadrin, said to have been a Russian defector turned double
agent for FBI and KGB.
   Shadrin disappeared when he went to Vienna to meet two KGB
agents in December 1975. The disappearance did not become public
until July 1977, when Shadrin's Polish-born wife said he had been
kidnapped and appealed for help to get him back.
   The U.S. government pledged its assistance but has never
disclosed Shadrin's fate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890724-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1501EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest Bjt   07-24 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest, Bjt,0518</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Hundreds March in Tbilisi; Strike Disrupts Factories ^By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TBILISI, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of protesters marched in the
capital of Soviet Georgia on Monday after 10 days of ethnic
violence in the republic's western region, and organizers of a
strike said it had affected 33 factories.
   A day of marches in Tbilisi culminated in an evening rally
attended by 2,000 people shouting ``Freedom from the U.S.S.R.!''
and slogans protesting the alleged failure of authorities to
protect Georgians from armed attacks in the Black Sea region of
Abkhazia.
   In Moscow, President Mikhail S. Gorbachev told the national
legislature ethnic unrest in Abkhazia had spread to Tbilisi,
causing ``the disorganization of transportation'' on Monday,
adding: ``The situation became acute.''
   Most stores and other businesses appeared to be open, but Irakli
Tseretel, a leader of the Georgian Party of National Independence
and a rally organizer, claimed 33 factories were closed, including
two military plants.
   Tseretel's report could not be confirmed and three other
informal groups that favor Georgian independence were boycotting
the strike, fearing a repeat of April 9, when 20 demonstrators died
at the hands of soldiers.
   Another speaker at the rally, Zviad Gamsachurdia, demanded the
arrests of those responsible for attacks on ethnic Georgians in
Abkhazia, a separate administrative area within the republic.
   An editor at the Georgian news agency Gruzinform said buses did
not appear Monday morning in some regions of Tbilisi, but that
service was normal by midday.
   The interrupted bus service appeared linked to a transit strike,
including a railway walkout that began over the weekend and ended
Monday. Tass, the official news agency, said the rail strike
stranded thousands of people.
   Several hundred people demonstrated throughout the day in
central Tbilisi, protesting the violence in Abkhazia.
   ``When those Abkhazians started to knife Georgians, it just
drove us out of our minds,'' said the news agency editor, Nana
Gelashvili.
   Tass said no armed clashes had been reported in Georgia or
Abkhazia for two days, but it reported more confiscations of
weapons from extremists by internal security troops and police.
   Authorities seized 104 rifles and more than 500 pounds of
explosives in the previous 24 hours and found a cache of 130 pounds
of explosives and 6,500 feet of detonating cable near the Abkhazian
village of Gvandra, Tass said.
   Residents of Abkhazia voluntarily turned in 744 firearms, the
agency reported.
   Nineteen people have been reported killed and more than 400
injured since July 15 in clashes between warring Georgians and
Abkhazians in the seaside resort area 880 miles south of Moscow.
   Two regional Communist Party secretaries and two government
leaders in Abkhazia were dismissed Saturday.
   Each ethnic group blames the other for the trouble. Abkhazians,
a minority in their own region, want more economic independence and
cultural rights. Georgians insist the enclave remain part of their
Caucasus republic.
   During the past month, at least 132 people have been killed in
ethnic unrest in the southern Soviet republics of Georgia,
Azerbaijan, Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan and Tadzhikistan.
</TEXT>
