<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Barthelme     07-24 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Barthelme,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Award-Winning Writer Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private memorial service will be held for
Donald Barthelme, an award-winning modern fiction writer who died
of cancer at the age of 58.
   Barthelme was known best for his wry humor and innovative
techniques in short stories, many of which were published in The
New Yorker, Atlantic and the Paris Review.
   Barthelme underwent successful surgery for throat cancer 17
months ago. But he became ill with a form of blood cancer while
living in Rome this summer and was admitted to M.D. Anderson Cancer
Center in Houston three weeks ago. He died Sunday.
   Barthelme also was an English professor at the University of
Houston.
   ``He was a reigning presence in the program,'' said Edward
Hirsch, poet and professor of English at the University of Houston.
``Donald was the kindest man I've known. He had a deep-bred
Southern courtesy and a kind attitude towards life, personally and
professionally.
   ``I've looked to him often as a mentor, teacher and friend.''
   A former newspaperman, Barthelme wrote 15 books, including
several novels and collections of short stories. His awards include
a Guggenheim Fellowship in 1967, National Institutes of Arts and
Letters Award in 1972, National Book Award in 1972 and the Rea
Award for the Short Story in 1988.
   ``His short stories were witty, funny and in an odd way deeply
emotional,'' Hirsch said. ``He was one of the few writers who make
one proud to be an American and part of this culture. His work is a
lasting American glory.''
   Born in Philadelphia, he grew up in Houston and attended the
University of Houston, but never obtained his degree. He served in
Korea and Japan during his U.S. Army service in 1953-54. He began
work at The Houston Post in February 1955 as an entertainment
reporter and critic.
   He later directed the Contemporary Arts Museum then moved to New
York in 1962. He returned to Houston in the early 1980s to teach.
   Among his works are the prize winning children's book, ``The
Slightly Irregular Fire Engine or the Hithering Thithering Djinn,''
and the novels ``Snow White,'' ``Unspeakable Practices,'' ``The
Dead Father,'' and a collection of stories, ``Come Back Dr.
Caligari.''
   Barthelme's novel ``The King'' is scheduled for publication next
spring by Harper and Row.
   He is survived by his wife, Marion Knox Barthelme; two
daughters; his parents, and a sister and three brothers. Plans for
a private service were not complete Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
