<FIRST>r a AM-InjuredChief     07-24 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Injured Chief,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Townspeople Hold Raffle to Pay Part-Time Cop's Hospital Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto AB1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HANCOCK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Townspeople are collecting money to help
their part-time police chief, who was hurt in the line of duty but
checked out of the hospital because the town doesn't have insurance.
   Chief Alfred H. Rodda, whose jaw was fractured in three places
when he was slugged by a man he arrested for refusing to pay a $24
restaurant tab, said Monday he's having trouble making ends meet.
   ``Things are kind of tough right now, because I support the
family during the summer driving a truck and I can't work,'' Rodda
said in a telephone interview.
   Rodda, 52, was hospitalized for two weeks with a broken jaw,
brain swelling and other head injuries. But he checked out July 14
when he learned the town of 600 in the Berkshire Hills doesn't have
insurance to cover officers hurt in the line of duty.
   Selectmen declined to discuss the chief's claim at a meeting
Thursday. Board Chairman Eleanor Patterson instead read a statement
which said, in part: ``Certainly the town is grateful for the 30
years of service Mr. Rodda has devoted to the town.''
   Officials declined to comment on the case on advice of town
attorney Sarah Bell. Ms. Bell did not return telephone calls to her
office Friday and Monday.
   Residents are pitching in to help the chief.
   A can for donations has been set out at Town Hall. And the
Jiminy Peak ski resort is organizing a raffle to raise money for
his medical bills, said marketing director Larry Dubin.
   ``It's a small town and we all know that if it was someone else
in trouble, that he'd be in the front of the line helping out,''
Dubin said.
   Organizers don't know how much money has been raised.
   Rodda keeps the peace on an on-call basis, and for most of 30
years hasn't charged the town for his services. The town's two
other part-time officers have refused to work since the chief's
injury.
   ``The townspeople are all for me,'' Rodda said. ``They'll
eventually get after the selectmen and I'll sue if I have to.''
   Rodda's attorney, Francis X. Spina, said Monday that state law
provides little protection for volunteer firefighters or part-time
police.
   ``People who serve as police and firefighters in small towns are
at a tremendous disadvantage if they get hurt in the line of
duty,'' Spina said. ``I'm not sure if they or the towns really
understand how much of a disadvantage.''
   If selectmen reject his claim for medical expenses, which Rodda
said now exceeds $10,000 and time lost from work, the chief can
sue, Spina said. State compensation laws appear to put a $3,000
annual limit on payments for time lost from a regular job by
volunteer firefighters and special police.
   ``You can't support a family on $3,000 a year,'' Spina said.
``It's less than welfare.''
   Rodda still needs surgery to repair his jaw.
   When the chief was hit June 30, his head slammed against the
pavement when he fell.
   Five witnesses captured the alleged assailant, William Finn, 38,
of Pittsfield. Finn, who had been at the Berkshire County jail
awaiting trial, was transferred to Northampton State Hospital for
psychiatric tests last week after allegedly attacking a guard.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
