<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     07-24 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Impasse on First Day of Cambodia Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   LA CELLE-SAINT-CLOUD, France (AP) _ Cambodian Prime Minister Hun
Sen told resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk on Monday that
there won't be any role for Khmer Rouge guerrillas in an interim
government.
   At a news conference following four hours of meetings, Hun Sen
said the discussion failed to produce any results but noted more
talks were scheduled Tuesday. Sihanouk said there was ``complete
disagreement.''
   The encounter was designed to pave way for an international
conference toward ending the 10-year-old war in Cambodia by setting
up a transition government.
   The monthlong conference begins Sunday, two months before
Vietnamese troops backing Hun Sen's pro-Moscow government are to
complete their withdrawal.
   The meeting between the two leaders at an 18th century chateau
in this Paris suburb is to be expanded Tuesday to include Hun Sen
and leaders of the three-faction resistance coalition: Sihanouk,
Son Sann of the non-Communist Khmer People's National Liberation
Front and Khieu Samphan, the nominal chief of the Chinese-backed
communist Khmer Rouge since the reported resignation of former
leader Pol Pot.
   The Khmer Rouge under Pol Pot was responsible for the deaths of
hundreds of thousands of Cambodians during a three-year reign that
ended with the Vietnamese invasion in December 1978.
   Sihanouk continues to insist on including the Khmer Rouge in an
interim government made up of the three resistance groups and Hun
Sen's government. He contends that giving the strongest of the
three guerrilla groups a place in the power structure is the price
of avoiding renewed civil war.
   Hun Sen disagrees.
   ``We think such a version simply signifies making the Cambodian
people hostage to the Khmer Rouge,'' he said. ``Our position is
that we are not hostages of Pol Pot and we will not let the
interests of the Cambodian people be bargained against the Pol
Pottists.''
   Hun Sen said he and Sihanouk took ``two steps backward'' at
Monday's meeting, but he refused to call it a failure, noting
discussions would continue Tuesday.
   Besides the future role of the Khmer Rouge, other issues on the
agenda include discussion of a cease-fire and a mechanism to
monitor the withdrawal of the remaining Vietnamese troops in
Cambodia, estimated at up to 70,000.
   The Cambodian prime minister blamed the impasse on Sihanouk's
insistance that as coalition president he was representing three
parties. In agreements reached at previous meetings, Sihanouk
represented only himself.
   Hun Sen said there should be only two Cambodian delegations to
the peace talks: his government and Sihanouk's Coalition Government
of Democratic Kampuchea.
   Sihanouk has the backing of many Western nations, including the
United States and the six-member Association of Southeast Asian
Nations, or ASEAN. There has been growing international support for
reaching a settlement that does not include the Khmer Rouge.
   In Washington, the State Department said Secretary of State
James A. Baker III will attend the opening session of the
international conference Sunday, and a spokeswoman reiterated U.S.
opposition to a Khmer Rouge role in an interim government.
   The conference is to include the Cambodian leaders plus all five
permament members of the U.N. Security Council _ the United States,
the Soviet Union, China, Britain and France _ as well as India,
Japan, Canada and Australia, and members of ASEAN: Indonesia,
Thailand, Malaysia, Philippins, Brunei and Singapore.
   As he left the chateau, Sihanouk said the resistance coalition
intended to keep fighting.
   The exiled prince, deposed in 1970, said that after the Sept. 30
Vietnamese withdrawal, 130,000 Vietnamese troops will remain in the
country ``hidden'' in the Cambodian army.
   Hun Sen's delegation distributed a copy of a cease-fire protocal
under discussion. However, as late as Friday, Sihanouk rejected a
cease-fire so long as armed Vietnamese remain in Cambodia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
