<DOCNO> AP890724-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1622EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Tranportation     07-24 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tranportation,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secretary Calls For `Revolution;' Analyst Says Car Still King</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner called
on Monday for a ``revolution in transportation,'' possibly
including high-speed rail systems, but a private analyst said the
car will remain king.
   Skinner launched a series of nationwide hearings aimed at
drawing up a national transportation policy for rail, highway, air
and water travel. Meetings are to be held in large and small cities
throughout the country through mid-September.
   The first one, in a Washington auditorium, featured the heads of
some of the country's biggest airline, railroad and automobile
companies and Nebraska Gov. Kay Orr, who said the whole system is a
``handyman's special.''
   If the nation's system of roads, rails, waterways and airports
were listed in a real estate ad, she said, it would say: ``Lots of
potential, oldstyle craftsmanship with many modern conveniences,
but needs work, a real fixer-upper.''
   Skinner, who moderated the first session and will attend some of
the other meetings, said a decision to build high-speed rail
systems is one possible result of the effort. This could include
trains that travel up to 300 mph, particularly between cities where
air travel has reached maximum levels.
   ``It is time for a new revolution in transportation, and
hopefully it will be a peaceful revolution,'' said Skinner.
   In an interview prior to the meeting, Skinner said the nation's
airports, highways, bridges, waterways and mass transit systems are
simply wearing out.
   ``We're going to have to rebuild it and replace it, or we're not
going to be able to rely on it anymore,'' he said.
   Among the most critical problems, Skinner said, are a lack of
planning for new airports and neglect of $80 billion worth of work
needed on deteriorating bridges.
   William B. Johnston, senior research fellow at the Hudson
Institute, told the opening session that no new system is in the
wings that will revolutionize transportation within the next 25
years, so old systems have to be made more efficient.
   He said the fastest growth is in suburban areas as urban density
continues to decline and automobile use increases. The Hudson
Institute is a Washington think tank that has studied several
national issues, including transportation needs.
   ``The country has become ever more tied to its personal,
on-demand, point-to-point transportation system: automobiles,''
Johnston said.
   ``Despite oil shortages and price increases, the lamentations of
many environmentalists and urban planners, and multi-billion dollar
federal investments in urban transit, nothing has dented the
dominance of the automobile,'' he said.
   General Motors President Robert C. Stempel said GM and other
companies are studying ``smart cars and smart highways'' that would
be computerized for increased safety and efficiency.
   In the meantime, he said, some simple things can be done to
improve road travel in many areas: traffic light coordination,
improved toll road payment procedures, and clearer and brighter
highway signs and markings.
   The Transportation Department is inviting citizens with ideas
about how to move Americans in the 21st Century _ and about how to
pay for the changes _ to attend the hearings around the country or
to send written proposals to the Transportation Department.
   The transportation secretary said he doesn't want the sessions
to turn into a littany of complaints.
   ``You shouldn't go if you're just going to say, `We've got
gridlock, somebody ought to do something about it,' because we know
that,'' Skinner said. ``These are needs and idea sessions.''
   The first meeting outside Washington will be held in Moscow,
Idaho, on Tuesday, with the focus on rural transportation issues.
The last meetings will be in Boston on Sept. 11-12 and will deal
with drug and alcohol use in the commercial transportation system
and federal research and development.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
