<HEAD>Bush Hasn't Forgotten Who Controls the Purse Strings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is the nation's commander in
chief these days, but on Monday it seemed as if he may be coveting
a position he used to hold: member of the House Ways and Means
Committee.
   Bush, a former Republican congressman from Texas in the early
1970s, was paying not one _ but two _ visits to the powerful
tax-writing panel, which is celebrating its 200th anniversary.
   After a busy morning schedule, Bush rode up to Capitol Hill _
about a mile away up Pennsylvania Avenue _ for a committee
luncheon. Monday night, Bush and his wife, Barbara, were attending
a committee dinner.
   The committee is working on a bill whose chief aim is to raise
$5.3 billion in new revenues for deficit reduction next year.
   Needless to say, the Democrat-controlled panel, chaired by Rep.
Dan Rostenkowski of Illinois, is ``rather important,'' said Marlin
Fitzwater, Bush's spokesman.
