<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Defense     07-24 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Defense,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says U.S. Needs Maximum Flexibility in Arms Control Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Bill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush lobbied senators Monday to
support his $295 billion defense budget, saying the United States
needs ``maximum flexibility'' in arms control negotiations.
   The president called a bipartisan group of senators to the White
House for a pep talk as lawmakers prepared for congressional floor
action on military spending measures.
   Although Bush said defense programs are ``complicated,
expensive,'' he urged full funding for the Pentagon's fiscal
program. Already, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney has made some
``important cuts'' in defense, Bush said.
   Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, praised Cheney for making tough choices in killing six
or seven programs.
   The committee has ``been willing to bite a part of that bullet,
too,'' he said, adding: ``We hope the Senate will stick with us
because we have basically backed the Cheney budget.''
   Among the potential targets of congressional budget-cutters are
the B-2 bomber, known as the stealth, the Strategic Defense
Initiative, or Star Wars, and how much money to give the
rail-mobile MX missiles or the single-warhead Midgetman.
   The expensive B-2 _ each plane is expected to cost more than
$500 million _ has been criticized by some lawmakers. But Bush
called the radar-evading plane a ``revolutionary technology'' that
is vital to the nation's defense.
   He said he could justify the B-2 expense because ``when you look
at the full defense program, I want to have maximum flexibility as
we have arms control negotiations.''
   The administration's defense outline calls for 132 bombers at a
cost of $70.2 billion. For fiscal 1990, Bush wants to spend $4.7
billion, but the House Armed Services Committee has already cut
$800 million from the program. Last week, Bush made his pitch to
members of the House panel.
   Sen. John Warner of Virginia, the ranking Republican on the
Senate Armed Services Committee, said he is hopeful the
administration will get money for three bombers in the current
round. The plane made its first flight last week in Palmdale, Calif.
   ``We put fences around the B-2,'' Nunn said. ``We want to make
sure that the plane performs as advertised, both in terms of its
flying ability and also in terms of its stealth characteristics,
which are crucial.''
   Nunn also said the Senate panel supports complete research and
development of the V-22, known as the Osprey, but it wants to
withhold advanced procurement money until it is determined the
tilt-rotor aircraft can be used commercially.
   The senators want ``to see if someone other than the taxpayer is
going to put up some money,'' Nunn said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890724-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1553EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Mexico-Debt Bjt   07-24 0786</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Debt, Bjt,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Effect of Mexican Deal on Third World Still Unclear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The general agreement between Mexico and its
creditor banks offers a glimmer of hope to the debt-strapped Third
World, but the success of the plan hinges on how far the banks are
ultimately willing to go, government officials and private bankers
said Monday.
   The Bush administration, which provided a final push over the
weekend to get the agreement, hailed the package as a landmark
success for its debt-reduction initiative, unveiled by Treasury
Secretary Nicholas Brady on March 10.
   However, the banks that will implement the plan were more
reserved in their enthusiasm, with many contending that it was too
soon to say how much debt relief they will provide to Mexico
because they were still examining the fine print of the agreement.
   ``At the moment, we're exploring our options,'' Fraser Seitel, a
spokesman for Chase Manhattan Corp., said in a typical comment.
``We're looking at the entire (Third World) debt package.''
   The Bush administration hopes to use the Mexican agreement to
set a precedent that will facilitate debt relief in other
countries, with Venezuela and the Philippines considered the two
leading candidates to follow Mexico's lead.
   The administration has made debt reduction a key component of
its foreign policy, believing that the only way to insure the
survival of emerging democracies in Latin America is to find a way
to reverse the decade-long slide in living standards caused by the
crushing $1.3 trillion Third World debt burden.
   The Brady plan for debt relief seeks to slash this debt by
establishing incentives to get commerical banks to voluntarily
forgive a portion of the loans.
   However, banking analysts said it was unclear whether the
incentives being offered in the Mexican package were sufficient to
trigger a substantial writedown of the debt.
   In the case of Mexico, the debt-reduction package provides the
commercial banks with three options.
   On the debt-relief side, the banks can cut 35 percent off the
face value of the current loans or they can agree to reduce
interest rates to 6.25 percent, down from about 10 percent
currently.
   Banks also have the option of simply providing new loans.
   The administration estimated that the various options could save
Mexico about $1.5 billion annually off the $5 billion to $5.5
billion it must pay to service its $54 billion in commercial bank
debt.
   However, the administration stressed that this was a rough
estimate and would vary depending on individual decisions made by
the 500 commercial banks in the United States, Japan and Europe
that hold the Mexican debt.
   Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., and a leading congressional expert
on Third World debt, said that the Mexican agreement appeared
seriously flawed because it did not provide enough incentives for
banks to opt for the two debt-reduction options rather than simply
piling on new debt.
   ``A lot of the banks, without the necessary carrots or sticks,
are going to stick with the familiar (approach of supplying) new
money to pay old debt,'' Schumer said.
   Schumer said that approach has proven to be a disaster over the
last seven years. Since 1982, when the debt crisis first erupted,
Third World debt has more than doubled from $600 billion to $1.3
trillion.
   Rep. John LaFalce, D-N.Y., said the Mexican agreement did not
represent any ``long-lasting breakthrough in Mexico's debt
situation.'' He said that, while the amount of debt-reduction was
likely to be small, Mexico would benefit in the next couple of
years with an infusion of money to get its economy started again.
   Cynthia Latta, an economist with DRI-McGraw Hill, said that the
administration apparently failed to get as many concessions as it
could from the commercial banks because they were so anxious to get
an agreement.
   ``It looks like they desperately wanted to do a deal and get
something signed to prove that their debt strategy could work,''
she said. ``It is a surface agreement that allows the
administration to claim a success but it leaves a lot of unanswered
questions.''
   The administration had hoped that President Bush would be able
to present a completed Mexican package during the seven-nation
economic summit last week in Paris.
   When that deadline was missed, Brady stepped up his lobbying
efforts. He brought the bankers and Mexican negotiators to
Washington over the weekend for meetings at the Treasury, which
were also attended by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
   After two days of discussions at the Treasury, final agreement
was reached late Sunday, in time for Mexican President Carlos
Salinas de Gortari to announce the breakthrough during a televised
broadcast, saying the proposal would answer the ``the cry of
Mexicans to return to growth.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890724-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1832EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     07-24 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lanka Lifts Censorship Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Monday lifted
3-week-old censorship restrictions on reporting ethnic violence but
told journalists to censor themselves.
   Also Monday, authorities halted a rally by about 600 Sinhalese
Buddhist monks who were demanding the expulsion of Indian
peacekeeping troops. No violence was reported.
   The monks' organization, which claims to represent 25,000
members, said it is prepared to join an armed struggle to oust the
Indian forces. Monk are an important political force in Sri Lanka.
   The government's announcement that censorship was being lifted
came 26 hours after the slaying of its chief censor, Themis Guruge.
He was shot to death Sunday while walking near his home.
   Government officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, blamed
the slaying of Guruge, who also headed state-run radio, on
Sinhalese extremists. Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne informed
local newspaper editors that censorship had been lifted, but he
also warned them: ``Be more responsible and maintain
self-censorship, especially on subversive activities and the Indian
issue.''
   The censorship had taken heavy criticism from both government
and opposition lawmakers.
   The July 6 announcement of censorship on domestic and foreign
press coincided with worsening ethnic violence and a deepening
dispute with India. Sri Lanka has demanded that India pull out
40,000 soldiers deployed as a peacekeeping force.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa has denounced the Indian military
presence in his nation as a threat to Sri Lanka's sovereignty and
demanded a pullout by the end of July.
   Indian peacekeepers arrived in Sri Lanka two years ago at the
invitation of Premadasa's predecessor, President Junius R.
Jayewardene.
   India has long said it does not intend to keep its force here
indefinitely, but Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi has said a premature
withdrawal would lead to even more bloodshed.
   More than 15,000 people have been killed in ethnic violence that
started with a separatist revolt by ethnic Tamil guerrillas in 1983.
   About 11,000 people have died in the Tamil insurrection,
including 1,000 Indian soldiers. According to the government,
Sinhalese extremists killed 4,000 people _ mostly Sinhalese
government officials and supporters _ in a backlash against what
they perceived as excessive concessions to the Tamils.
   The militant Sinhalese have been led by the People's Liberation
Front.
   During censorship, most references to the front or to Sinhalese
radicals were removed from news stories.
   Tamils, who make up about 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million
people, say they are discriminated against by Sinhalese. The
majority Sinhalese comprise 75 percent of the population,
dominating the government and military.
   During their rally, the saffron-robed monks were defying a ban
on such protests. They pushed past a line of police and sat on the
narrow lane outside the Sri Mahabodhi Temple in the capital,
Colombo.
   Earlier, their Sri Lanka National Bhikkhu Federation issued a
statement saying thousands of monks were prepared to join an armed
struggle to preserve Sri Lankan sovereignty from what it called
``the Indian army of invasion.''
   Before the rally, a 25-year old monk who declined to give his
name told a news conference in the temple compound that the monks'
federation had decided to join militant Sinhalese extremists and
student groups in opposing the government and the presence of
Indian peacekeepers.
   ``We do not believe the Indian army would go back on just a
request,'' the monk said. ``We believe that we have to take further
action, and we are prepared to do it.''
   Asked if the monks condoned violence, he said: ``If an armed
struggle is demanded to gain the freedom of the people, the Bhikku
Federation does approve and will participate in it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890724-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1916EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-AntitrustFines     07-24 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Antitrust Fines,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Backs Higher Fines for Corporate Crimes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department said Monday it
supported a ten-fold increase in the maximum fine for criminal
antitrust violations by corporations to $10 million.
   The department, noting it is conducting more than 150 grand jury
investigations of alleged criminal antitrust violations, said an
increase was needed to deter price fixing, bid rigging and unlawful
attempts by corporations to control the market on certain products.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said in a statement that he
supported legislation pending in Congress that would increase the
maximum fine from $1 million to $10 million for corporate antitrust
violations.
   ``This increase in penalties will send a strong signal to those
who intend to defraud American consumers or the federal government
through criminal antitrust conspiracies that the Justice Department
takes their criminal conduct most seriously and will see that they
are appropriately punished,'' Thornburgh said.
   He issued the statement on the eve of a Senate Judiciary
Committee hearing on antitrust issues.
   The proposal to increase the maximum corporate fine was
contained in legislation sponsored by Sens. Howard Metzenbaum,
D-Ohio, and Strom Thurmond, R-S.C.
   James F. Rill, the new assistant attorney general in charge of
the Justice Department'santitrust division, is scheduled to testify
at Tuesday's hearing.
   Rill noted in a statement that ``it has been 15 years since
criminal fines for coprorate antitrust offenders were raised, and a
sizeable increase in fines now is a good way to underscore that
this criminal activity will not be tolerated.''
   The fines apply to criminal antitrust violations such as price
fixing and bid rigging, which Rill noted is ``undertaken purely to
defraud its victims and has no possible economic justification.''
   Rill, noting that the antitrust division is conducting more than
150 grand jury investigations of suspected criminal violations,
said current fines ``do not appear to be adequately deterring this
unlawful conduct.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890724-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1812EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-PuertoRico-Tremor     07-24 0137</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Puerto Rico-Tremor,0141</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slight Tremor Shakes Virgin Islands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A slight tremor shook the U.S.
Virgin Islands Monday and was felt in neighboring Puerto Rico, the
Geophysical Institute said. No damage or casualties were reported.
   The quake had a 4.9 magnitude on the Richter scale and was
centered 25 miles northwest of the island of St. Thomas, said
William McCan of the institute.
   McCan said the institute received calls from Puerto Rico
residents saying they also felt the tremor.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
   An earthquake of 4 on the Richter scale can cause moderate
damage in the local area and an earthquake measuring 5 on the scale
can cause considerable damage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
