<DOCNO> AP890724-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1801EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     07-24 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Airs Official Version of Democracy Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State-run TV on Monday broadcast the government's
first documentary account of the events leading up to its bloody
suppression of pro-democracy protests in early June.
   The first hour of the four-part series, ``A Test of Blood and
Fire,'' was as remarkable for what it left out as for what it
included.
   It didn't show the students singing the national anthem, which
they did constantly.
   It also didn't show posters attacking corruption and nepotism,
or banners proclaiming the protesters' love for China.
   Footage shown in the program, unlike earlier official reports,
did show Premier Li Peng hanging in effigy and banners mocking
senior leader Deng Xiaoping.
   In the first two weeks after the crackdown on pro-democracy
demonstrators June 3-4 that left hundreds or perhaps thousands
dead, state-run TV repeatedly showed angry crowds stoning troops
and setting army vehicles on fire. Monday's was the first official
documentary account of the events leading up to June 3 that
purported to put the student movement into perspective.
   Some events in the documentary were shown out of sequence,
apparently to strengthen the government's argument that the student
marches were instigated by anti-communist intellectuals.
   Dissident intellectuals, who remained on the sidelines until the
last stages of the protests, were portrayed as speaking to students
much earlier than they did.
   Apparently to support government claims that the student-led
protests were orchestrated many months in advance by dissidents
such as Fang Lizhi, the program began by showing students
discussing democratic reforms at forums last winter.
   Fang and his wife, physics professor Li Shuxian, were shown at
that time speaking to the students. Fang and Li did not appear in
public support of the later protests sparked by the death of former
Communist Party head Hu Yaobang in mid-April.
   After the crackdown, however, they sought refuge in the U.S.
Embassy in Beijing. The Chinese government has demanded they be
handed over for arrest.
   Monday's TV program repeatedly accused Hu's successor as
Communist Party head, Zhao Ziyang, of contributing to the
``turmoil'' of the widespread demonstrations.
   Zhao, who was ousted following the crackdown on dissent, has
been accused of supporting the student protests and opposing other
party leaders who wanted to quash them.
   Public criticism of Zhao has mounted steadily since his June 24
ouster from his party posts. Several reports of comments Zhao
allegedly made at closed meetings have been cited to prove his
softness on Western-style liberalism, which the government blames
for the student movement.
   An editorial Monday in the newspaper Liberation Army Daily
accused Zhao of supporting ``words and deeds that vilified
Marxism'' and spreading non-Marxist theories. It did not give any
specifics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
