<DOCNO> AP890724-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1803EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-OAU     07-24 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OAU,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egypt's President Heads Organization Of African Unity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt
became chairman of the Organization of African Unity on Monday and
said his top priority is to seek an end to regional conflicts.
   In a speech to the opening session of the three-day summit,
Mubarak also urged the 50-nation group to work together to confront
``racist aggression'' by South Africa and ease Africa's debt
problem.
   Mubarak called for the ``enhancement of solidarity for the
settlement of the current disputes between various states.''
   He mentioned no specific conflicts, but he clearly was referring
to the border dispute between Chad and Libya, the war between
Morocco and the Polisario Front over control of the Western Sahara
and recent ethnic clashes among residents of Senegal and Mauritania.
   Mubarak did not make any reference to the civil wars in Sudan,
Ethiopia, Somalia and Mozambique that have taken hundreds of
thousands of lives.
   The OAU traditionally does not meddle in what are considered the
internal affairs of its members, although many African nations take
the view that the rebels battling the government in Mozambique are
inspired and backed by South Africa.
   Mubarak was elected by acclamation to lead the OAU for the
coming year, succeeding President Moussa Traore of Mali. The
chairmanship alternates each year between Arab and black African
states.
   The Egyptian president pledged to ``confront firmly and
tenaciously the racist aggression'' of South Africa, which he
accused of trying to undermine Namibia's transition toward
independence and enslaving its own black people through apartheid,
its policy of racial segregation.
   Mubarak listed Africa's economic problems as his third priority,
saying they ``constitute a serious danger which not only threatens
to stifle development'' but ``also threatens our very existence and
survival.''
   As he has before, he urged a resumption of talks between the
impoverished nations of Africa and South America and the northern
industrialized countries.
   Mubarak also said he would seek greater cooperation between the
Arab states of the Middle East and Africa, saying they share the
same principles, values and goals.
   Earlier, U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar told the
session that he was encouraged by progress toward ending South
African rule of Namibia.
   But he said some provisions of the independence plan ``have not
been fully respected'' by South Africa. He specifically cited the
incorporation of some members of a disbanded South African
counterinsurgency force known as Koevoet into the legitimate
South-West Africa police force.
   He said the U.N. peacekeeping force in the region ``has clearly
established'' that former Koevoet members were intimidating
civilians in an apparent attempt to influence scheduled elections
this fall.
   Perez de Cuellar said there ``had been a reduction of
intimidation in recent days, but this is not enough. ... There must
be full compliance'' with the independence plan.
   He made no reference to an earlier OAU call for an increase in
the U.N. peacekeeping force, a call repeated in another speech
Monday by Sam Njuma, the leader of the South-West Africa People's
Organization. SWAPO has been battling South Africa for Namibia's
independence for 25 years.
   Perez de Cuellar reportedly rejected any increase in the
peacekeeping force after talks with Njuma in Lusaka, Zambia, late
last week.
   Former President Jimmy Carter was scheduled to arrive in Addis
Ababa at the end of the week to mediate between the Ethiopian
government and Eritrean rebels, who have engaged in one of the
world's longest wars. Both sides have accepted Carter as a
go-between, and the Ethiopian conflict also was expected to be the
subject of a series of private talks at the OAU meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
