<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Outdoors     07-24 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Outdoors,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Honors `Take Pride in America' Volunteers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush honored 104 people and
organizations with ``Take Pride in America'' awards Monday for
helping preserve the great outdoors.
   ``America can only be as beautiful as her people are vigilant,''
Bush said during an outdoor ceremony at the White House.
   Borrowing a line from the poet Walt Whitman, Bush said ``Today
each of you is helping America sing, through your caring and your
sacrifice, and through deeds that are making America a more
pristine and glorious place.''
   The winners included businesses, civic groups, schools and
individuals, as well as government projects.
   He singled out volunteers in Page, Ariz., who ``rally every year
to clean up the nearby Glen Canyon Recreation Area and Navajo
Reservation,'' and a 4-H Club called the High Country Cactus
Kickers that help preserve archaeological sites in Craig, Colo.
   The awards program is a public-private partnership, with the
federal effort spearheaded by the Interior Department. The number
of winners has tripled since it began two years ago.
   Addressing a crowd of several hundred people on the South Lawn,
Bush said his wife, Barbara, the campaign's honorary chairwoman,
shares his love for the outdoors, although ``she might feel that
she's a fishing widow at times.''
   Actually, Bush said, ``she, too, loves to fish. In fact, she's
the only person I know who can read and fish at the same time.''
   He added, to groans, ``You might call it reading between the
lines.''
   Bush also quipped, ``Only in Washington could they call the
office that manages the great outdoors the Department of the
Interior.''
   Country singer Lee Greenwood, who was master of ceremonies for
the event, got to sing ``God Bless the USA'' on the White House
lawn for the second time in four days. He also performed at Bush's
picnic for astronauts last Thursday.
   Perhaps preaching to the choir, Greenwood told the crowd at the
end: ``Remember, the White House grounds belong to us all. Put your
trash in designated containers.''
</TEXT>
