<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Talvela     07-24 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Talvela,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Finland's Leading Opera Star Dies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATTI HUUHTANEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials and supporters of the new
National Opera were reeling Monday from the death of Martti
Talvela, the country's leading opera star, who had agreed to take
over as director.
   The 54-year-old singer, whose bass voice had boomed through
opera houses from La Scala to the Metropolitan, died Saturday. One
colleague on Monday called him ``the father figure of Finnish
opera.''
   News reports said Talvela died during the wedding dance of his
youngest daughter on his farm in Juva, near Savonlinna in eastern
Finland. They indicated he died of a heart attack.
   His family refused to discuss the cause of death or funeral
arrangements.
   Two months before his death, Talvela agreed to become director
of the National Opera in 1992 after the opera house is finished.
   Talvela said his aim would be to make the Finnish opera ``on a
par with the best in Europe.''
   Alfons Almi, a leading figure behind the plan to build a new
opera, said Talvela was the only real candidate for director.
   ``The directorship was tailor-made for Talvela. He is
irreplaceable,'' Almi said in a newspaper interview Monday.
   Roger Lindberg, a member of the committee to select a new
director, described Talvela's death as a ``catastrophe'' for the
National Opera. ``It will be very difficult to find a suitable new
director,'' Lindberg said.
   Talvela, born Feb. 4, 1935, began his international singing
career after winning a contest in Vaasa, west Finland, in 1960. He
had trained to be a school teacher and singing was just a hobby.
   He then studied singing in Stockholm. After a breakthrough at
the Bayreuth Wagner festival, he was signed by the West Berlin
Deutsche Opera.
   During his career, Talvela performed more abroad than in
Finland. In addition to the Metropolitan Opera of New York and
Milan's La Scala, his stages have included the Moscow Bolshoi and
the Vienna National Opera.
   He was said to have sung all the major opera roles for bass
voices. He was particularly acclaimed for his interpretation of the
title role of Mussorgsky's opera ``Boris Godunov.''
   Talvela was artistic director of the annual Savonlinna Opera
Festival from 1972 to 1979. He elevated the festival to a major
international opera event.
   Walton Gronroos, current artistic director of the festival, said
Talvela's ``uncompromising nature was precisely the reason why he
was able to create such great art.''
   ``In Talvela, we have lost a visionary, the father figure of
Finnish opera,'' Gronroos said.
   Not long before he died, Talvela was asked about his reputed
stubborn streak. ``Nobody can ever force me to do anything, but I
am always prepared to negotiate,'' he said.
   When not working, Talvela spent much of his time at his summer
retreat in Juva, where he tended a flock of 100 sheep.
   Talvela is survived by his wife of 32 years, Annukka, and by
three adult children.
</TEXT>
