<FIRST>r i AM-PuertoRico-Blasts     07-24 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Puerto Rico-Blasts,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blasts Damage Army Recruiting Station, Post Office in Puerto Rico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pipe bombs blasted an Army
recruiting station and a U.S. post office Monday, authorities said.
A telephone caller claimed the two bombs were planted by a
pro-independence group.
   There were no reports of injuries from the blasts, which came on
the eve of Puerto Rico Constitution Day. The holiday celebrates the
37-year-old Constitution that made the island a U.S. commonwealth.
   A series of similar bomb attacks have struck the island in
recent months.
   Monday's caller told a radio station the bombs were placed by
the Puerto Rican Revolutionary Forces, a little-known group. Police
could not confirm the authenticity of the call.
   The male caller, who did not give his name, said the bombing was
to protest military bases in Puerto Rico and its Commonwealth
status.
   The United States provides defense for Puerto Rico, and its only
military bases are American. The Pentagon has 3,350 active
servicemen on the island, including 2,000 at the Roosevelt Roads
Naval Base on the west coast.
   Police said the Monday's bombs went off at 2 a.m. at the Plaza
Carolina Shopping Center about 10 miles east of metropolitan San
Juan.
   They caused ``considerable'' damage to the Army recruiting
office, the post office and several public telephones, all on the
interior of the shopping center, police said. They also damaged the
administrative offices of the Pueblo Supermarket, which faces the
parking lot.
   Police and FBI agents were investigating.
   Two bombs went off last week at the U.S. post offices in Coamo
and Guayama, municipalities in the island's interior. No injuries
were reported.
   In June, the Borinquen Popular Army, also known as the Los
Macheteros or machete-wielders, claimed responsibility for a bomb
that caused heavy damage but no injuries at an Army recruiting
station and a branch of the Bank of Boston in Bayamon. The town is
about 15 miles northwest of San Juan.
   Borinquen was Puerto Rico's name before the Spanish conquest of
the island in the 16th century. Spain ceded the island to the
United States in 1898.
   Similar explosions, with no injuries and only minor damage,
occurred in June at a U.S. Customs office in the southern city of
Ponce and at a Chase Manhattan Bank branch in Caguas, about 20
miles south of San Juan. No group claimed responsibility for those
blasts.
   Los Macheteros is a militant pro-independence group that has
been relatively inactive in recent years. During the 1970s, it blew
up five National Guard fighter jets worth $47 million and ambushed
a U.S. Navy vehicle, killing two sailors and injuring 10.
   Sixteen suspected members were charged in the $7 million robbery
of a Wells Fargo depot in Hartford, Conn., in 1983. The FBI charges
that the Macheteros intended to use the money to pay for their
campaign to gain independence for Puerto Rico.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890724-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1930EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-24 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Forces Raid Guerrilla Hideouts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops Monday launched an
offensive on suspected guerrilla hideouts on the outskirts of the
capital and seized large amounts of weaponry, a spokesman said.
   In Pakistan, U.S.-backed guerrillas said government fighter jets
blasted villages north of Kabul after residents refused to pressure
guerrillas to open a key stretch of highway used to carry in
supplies from the Soviet Union.
   Afghan Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammed Nabi Amani said
soldiers conducted search operations at four areas to the west,
east and southwest of Kabul.
   ``The operation is still continuing and our brave soldiers are
successfully recovering arms and ammunition,'' he said. Mortar
shells, anti-tank and anti-personnel mines, rockets and ammunition
were recovered, he said.
   Amani did not mention any fighting during the operation.
   The offensive comes after the Moslem guerrillas launched 19
rockets into the city over the weekend, killing 46 people and
wounding 121 others.
   At least 43 people were killed Saturday when the guerrillas
launched eight rockets. The barrage resumed Sunday when 11 rockets
landed in the city, killing three people.
   Also Monday, a bomb exploded in a restaurant in the city center,
injuring at least seven people.
   Mohammad Faizullah, a restaurant employee said the bomb made a
deep crater on the floor, shattered window panes and destroyed
furniture.
   ``Had the bomb exploded during lunch or dinner time, many people
would have died,'' he said. The blast took place in the afternoon,
he said, when few people were in the restaurant.
   The guerrillas were believed responsible for the explosion, but
no arrests were reported.
   Fazle Akbar, of the pro-rebel Afghan Information and
Documentation Centre in Pakistan, said that since Friday,
government planes blasted the villages of Shakardara, Mir Bacha Kot
and Qara Bagh, along a 35 mile stretch of the Salang Highway north
of the Afghan capital.
   There was no estimate of damage or casualty figures and the
report could not be independently confirmed.
   Akbar said the attacks came after Afghan President Najib, in a
meeting Friday, was unable to persuade elders from villages north
of Kabul to put pressure on the guerrillas to stop attacking supply
convoys.
   The guerrillas, also based in neighboring Iran, have been
fighting the Soviet-backed government for the past 11 years.
   They control most of the countryside and the government's army
has maintained control of the cities after a Soviet troop pullout
was completed in February.
   At least 1 million Afghans have been killed in the war.
</TEXT>
