<HEAD>Daley Meets Bush, Vows Cooperation on Federal Issues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago Mayor Richard Daley paid a brief
social call on President Bush on Monday and pledged to work with
the federal government in tackling problems in his city and
elsewhere.
   Daley, who was accompanied by his wife, Maggie, and his three
children on the visit to the Oval Office, said he told Bush ``I
will be working with him on many problems, whether it's housing or
narcotics.''
   Daley, a Democrat who took office in April, said he does not
want political differences to stand in the way of achieving his
goal of building a better Chicago.
   Although Daley said Bush did not promise Chicago any special
favors, he said the meeting helped solidify a personal relationship.
   Bush, according to Daley, talked about his family and mentioned
that Daley's father, the legendary former mayor of Chicago, was a
``great political leader.''
   Last week, Daley said he met in Washington with a number of
Cabinet secretaries, including those for housing, transportation
and education.
