<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0569 07-24 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0569,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede BUDAPEST</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nyers, Grosz Arrive in Moscow</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Hungarian leaders arriving in Moscow;
no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary's top Communist Party leaders arrived
Monday to inform Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev about plans
for multiparty elections, according to official reports.
   Rezsoe Nyers and Karoly Grosz were invited by the Soviet
Communist Party after a change in the Hungarian party leadership
last month. The party set up a four-man presidium dominated by
reformers and elevated Nyers to the newly influential post of party
chairman. Grosz maintained his position as party general secretary.
   Grosz is responsible for internal party matters, and Nyers is
responsible for the party's foreign relations.
   Nyers met with Gorbachev this month in Bucharest at a meeting of
the seven Warsaw Pact countries.
   The Soviet Foreign Ministry's deputy spokesman, Vadim Perfilyev,
said the talks were part of an increasingly frequent discussion of
reforms in the two countries.
   In Moscow, the Hungarians will inform Gorbachev about Hungary's
decision to allow a pluralistic system, according to a foreign
policy aide to Grosz, Gyula Thurmer.
   The party is negotiating with the opposition on the first
multiparty elections since the Communists consolidated power in
1948. Elections are due by June 1990.
   In Budapest, Thurmer told the party newspaper Nepszabadsag the
visit was aimed at exchanging information on recent developments in
the Soviet Union and Hungary.
   ``It is worth examining how the processes taking place in the
two countries strengthen each other,'' Thurmer said. ``The Soviet
party shows understanding toward the introduction of a multiparty
system in Hungary.''
   On Saturday, the first opposition candidate in more than 41
years was elected in a local by-election to Hungary's
Communist-dominated Parliament.
   Grosz and Hungarian Premier Miklos Nemeth _ also elevated to the
party four-man presidium along with reformer Imre Pozsgay _ visited
Moscow in March and returned with assurances of Kremlin support for
Hungary's reforms.
   Reforms began earlier in Hungary and have progressed further
than in the Soviet Union, making it both a laboratory for economic
and social experiments in the Soviet bloc and an occasional source
of worry for Moscow over whether they are going too far.
   Visiting Budapest this month, President Bush also expressed
support for Hungary's reforms but emphasized that he did not wish
to interfere.
   Thurmer said Bush's Budapest visit would also be discussed in
Moscow.
</TEXT>
