<FIRST>u w AM-ArmySecretary     07-24 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Army Secretary,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Will Nominate Service's No. 2 to Top Job</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush said Monday he will nominate
Michael P.W. Stone, the undersecretary of the Army, to assume the
top job as secretary of the service.
   Stone, 64, a member like Bush of the Yale University class of
1948, would succeed John O. Marsh Jr., if confirmed by the Senate.
   Since 1988, Stone has served as the undersecretary of the Army,
and for two years before that was the assistant secretary of the
Army for financial management.
   Stone had a long career as a businessman, primarily in
California, before he joined the Agency for International
Development in 1982 as the head of its mission in Cairo, Egypt. He
also directed AID's Caribbean Basin Initiative Affairs in 1984.
   From 1964 until 1982, Stone was president and director of
Sterling Vineyards in Napa Valley, Calif. From 1960 until 1977, he
was president of Sterling International.
   He also served as assistant to the president of Utah
International Co. in San Francisco, 1957-1959; as associate with
McKinsey and Co., 1954-1957 and president of Howard Rotavator Co.
in Arlington Heights, Ill., 1950-1954.
   Stone, who is married with two children, served in the U.S. Navy
from 1943 to 1946.
