<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-CivilRights 1stLd-Writethru a0608 07-24 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Civil Rights, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0608,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Stands Firm on Lucas Nomination</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 7th graf pvs, bgng: `But supporters,' with 11 grafs to
UPDATE with comment from Jesse Jackson, Bob Dole, Joseph Lowery. Picks
up 8th graf pvs, `We still'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush still stands behind William
Lucas, his embattled nominee to be the Justice Department's top
civil rights enforcer, the White House said Monday.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Bush chose the Detroit lawyer as
``someone who would be a fighter for civil rights; a black person
who understood the black experience.''
   He said Lucas also was ``someone who knew urban problems,
someone who was willing to take charge in that job and do it with
aggressiveness and forcefulness. We think Bill Lucas will do that.''
   The former sheriff of Wayne County, Mich., is opposed by many
civil rights groups who claim he lacks experience to be assistant
attorney general for civil rights. They also have criticized his
defense of recent Supreme Court decisions on civil rights.
   Several members of the Senate Judiciary Committee, which could
vote on the nomination as early as Thursday, expressed doubts about
Lucas following his testimony at confirmation hearings last week.
   A prominent black in the House, Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich.,
withdrew his support for the nominee following the hearing.
   And Jesse Jackson on Monday urged Judiciary Committee Chairman
Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., to reject Lucas as being ``unsuitable''
for the post.
   Jackson, in a letter to Biden, said he considered Lucas an
``outstanding person and family man,'' but without qualifications
to run a major legal operation.
   ``Today, racial discrimination is defended, not by dogs and
hoses, but by onerous burdens of proof, severe statutes of
limitations, discovery restrictions and procedural trickery. ... We
don't need someone who has never performed surgery operating on the
civil rights of the American people.''
   Jackson said Lucas, ``could, despite the best of intentions,
seriously harm the cause of civil rights. ... We need an aggressive
response to the cutbacks in civil rights. In my judgment, Mr. Lucas
cannot provide that response.''
   But supporters countered that Lucas' stand on civil rights is
the same as that of Bush and Attorney General Dick Thornburgh.
   Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas said criticisms that
Lucas does not have a civil rights background or legal expertise
are ``unjustified'' and ``miss the point.''
   He said the head of the civil rights division has a battery of
lawyers to assist him in court and to free him for the task of
setting civil rights policy.
   ``Ninety percent of the complaints filed with the civil rights
division's criminal section involve police misconduct. Who in this
country is better equipped than Bill Lucas _ the former policeman,
FBI agent and county sheriff _ to deal with these tough issues with
real experience,'' Dole said.
   The Rev. Joseph Lowrey, head of the Southern Christian
Leadership Conference, called the opposition to Lucas ``partisan
and picayune.''
   ``I think he is qualified,'' Lowrey said as he left a meeting
Monday with Thornburgh. ``He has as much courtroom experience as
Bobby Kennedy had when he was nominated to be attorney general over
the whole Department of Justice.''
   Lowrey said he expected Lucas to ``work to alter and influence
the administration's position'' on civil rights once confirmed as
assistant attorney general.
   ``We still think Lucas is a good candidate, an excellent
candidate and should be confirmed, on the basis of his experience,
his ability, the work that he's done, the fact that he has labored
in the vineyards of law enforcement and civil rights, that he knows
these problems from the inside of a big city,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``We stand behind the candidate,'' he said.
   Asked about a comment by a Justice Department spokesman, David
Runkel, that civil rights groups opposing the Lucas nomination
``have the most to lose'' from their stance, Fitzwater said Bush
did not plan to hold this against them.
   ``The president made this appointment in good faith. He thinks
it's a good appointment. He expects to maintain good relations with
the civil rights groups no matter what,'' Fitzwater said.
   Lucas has been nominated to the job that William Bradford
Reynolds held in the Reagan administration. Reynolds was Reagan's
point man in implementing Reagan's conservative legal agenda at the
Justice Department. Civil rights groups complained Reynolds
undermined affirmative action.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
