<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1726EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0629 07-24 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,0765</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Defying Gov't Policy by Meeting PLO Supporters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 8th pvs, `Arda was...' to UPDATE casualties;
pickup 9th pvs, `The mass-circulation...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir has held meetings
with PLO supporters from the occupied territories despite a
government ban on contacts with the outlawed group, Palestinian and
Israeli sources said Monday.
   The reports were denied by Shamir's spokesman, Avi Pazner, and
by Palestinians identified as meeting with Shamir.
   Pazner told The Associated Press the premier ``does not meet
with PLO members and does not conduct negotiations directly or
indirectly with the PLO.''
   He confirmed Shamir has met ``non-PLO Palestinians'' from the
West Bank and Gaza Strip in recent weeks, but said, ``I don't know
what they believe in their hearts.'' He declined to identify the
participants.
   Also on Monday, an Arab attacker shot to death one Palestinian
and wounded another in front of City Hall in Gaza City, Arab
witnesses said. Both victims were suspected of collaborating with
Israel. The army confirmed the shootings but said it was checking
the circumstances.
   In the West Bank, soldiers shot and killed Mohammed Yusef Arda,
22, in a clash between troops and youths in Araba village, Arab
reports said.
   Monday's Gaza attack brings to 84 the number of Palestinians
killed as alleged collaborators during the 19-month uprising
against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Arda was the 519th Palestinian to die in confrontations with
Israeli troops and civilians. Thirty-eight Israelis also have been
killed.
   In scattered stone-throwing confrontations with troops in the
Gaza Strip, 11 Palestinians were shot and wounded by soldiers
Monday, Arab hospital officials said. The army said it was checking
the reports.
   The mass-circulation Yediot Ahronot said senior Soviet official
Gennady Terasov will visit Israel soon to discuss Shamir's peace
plan.
   An Israeli Foreign Ministry official said he could not confirm
the report, but noted Terasov would be the highest-ranking Soviet
to visit since Moscow severed ties with Israel after the 1967
Middle East war. Terasov is Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze's new adviser on Middle East affairs.
   The reports alleging Shamir is meeting pro-PLO activists came as
the premier faces a challenge from hard-liners in his Likud bloc
who fear he will make too many concessions to win approval to hold
elections in the territories to calm the uprising.
   They also surfaced as Palestine Liberation Organization leader
Yasser Arafat was quoted in the Rome daily Il Messaggero as saying
the Israeli government has opened direct contacts with his group.
   Arafat also said a PLO executive committee member met recently
in Vienna with an envoy of Shamir. He gave no details.
   The Austrian news agency APA said PLO executive Abdul Razzak
Al-Yahya and Israeli Eli Halali both attended a July 1-2 symposium
in Vienna.
   But Halali, a Likud central committee member, told The
Associated Press: ``I didn't meet with anyone at the Vienna
conference.''
   Palestinian and Israeli sources who demanded anonymity said
Shamir met with Radwan Abu Ayyash, head of the Arab Journalists
Association in the West Bank, and Mansour Al-Shawwa, son of the
late Gaza City Mayor Rashad Al-Shawwa.
   The independent Hebrew daily Maariv said Monday that another of
the Palestinians was attorney Jamil Tarifi from the West Bank town
of Ramallah.
   Haaretz daily reported Shamir met an unidentified east Jerusalem
journalist who supports Arafat's Fatah faction.
   Other reports said the fourth participant was Ramallah
pharmacist Ezziddin Al-Aryan.
   All are known supports of the PLO's mainstream Fatah, and
Al-Aryan is a member of the Palestine National Council, its
parliament-in-exile.
   Al-Shawwa and Al-Aryan both denied meeting Shamir. The others
could not be reached for comment.
   Shamir in April announced a peace plan calling for elections in
the occupied territories to select Palestinians to open talks to
negotiate an interim solution.
   The plan was seen as a vehicle around the government ban on PLO
contacts, since many elected undoubtedly would be PLO backers.
   U.S. officials are trying to persuade Arafat to approve the plan.
   Arafat told Il Messaggero that the PLO approved meetings with
Israeli officials and has been receiving reports on the contacts.
   However, underground leaders of the uprising condemned them.
   ``The unified leadership confirms its rejection of holding any
communications with any official representatives in the Israeli
government and confirms that not one of the national personalities
met with any government officials,'' they said in a leaflet Sunday.
</TEXT>
