<DOCNO> AP890724-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 2013EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CoastalPollution     07-24 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coastal Pollution,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governors Agree To Clean Oceans, But With No Specifics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governors of eight Atlantic Coast states
met with congressional environmental leaders Monday and then signed
a broadly worded agreement to work for clean oceans.
   Rep. Gerry E. Studds, D-Mass., acknowledged that the document,
which was passed from governor to governor while homestate
television cameras rolled, ``probably will not take its place
between the Magna Carta and the Mayflower Compact.''
   But he joined other participants at a news conference following
the closed meeting in saying the agreement was a symbolic
achievement that signaled the governors were determined to work
among themselves and with federal officials to solve environmental
problems.
   Standing behind Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, last year's
Democratic presidential nominee, Studds said it will take billions
of dollars just to clean up Boston Harbor alone and that the main
measure of success for the governors' ``coastal agenda'' will be
``the number of dollars we are able to put behind them.''
   The bipartisan meeting, attended by about a dozen members of
Congress, was arranged by Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of
Maine and Maryland Gov. William Donald Schaefer, also a Democrat.
   The governors of Connecticut, Rhode Island, Delaware, Virginia,
North Carolina and South Carolina also attended the ceremony.
   The document specifically did not endorse any of the many pieces
of federal legislation pending on environmental issues and
purposely was worded vaguely enough to ensure unanimous support.
   For example, the first section of the five-part plan _ ``Create
an Environmental Ethic'' _ says ``Federal and state policies must
reflect the need for strengthened environmental protection'' and
``Education and public participation must be strenghtened to show
how everyone can participate in the solution to coastal pollution
problems.''
   The document also called for strengthening research and
monitoring of coastal waters; reducing coastal nutrient and toxic
pollution; protection of marine and coastal sediment quality; and
expansion of government authority for oil spill prevention and
response.
   ``This is the beginning,'' Schaefer of the meeting.
   Sen. John F. Kerry, D-Mass., said the most important aspect of
the agreement was its call for creation of an environmental ethic
because significant progress will not be made ``until the ethic
becomes strong enough for force funding.''
   Pressed to estimate how much money would be needed to accomplish
the goals of the group, Mitchell said, ``There is no single overall
figure and I think it is a mistake to view it in the context of
those kind of questions.''
   He emphasized that there was no attempt to get the group to
agree on specific legislation and added: ``I think it is very
significant that we got started and got the agreement that we did.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
