<FIRST>u w AM-HUD-Demery     07-24 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Demery,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Declines Prosecution of Former HUD Official for Charity Ties</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-HUD Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department has declined to
prosecute a former Department of Housing and Urban Development
official in connection with his activities for a charity whose
donors included many developers who did business with HUD.
   The decision was made last week but not disclosed until Monday
when a copy of a Justice Department letter informing HUD's
inspector general of the decision was released by a congressman.
   In the letter, the department said it has declined to prosecute
Thomas T. Demery for any actions detailed in the inspector
general's April report on the agency's Section 8 Moderate
Rehabilitation Program.
   The report detailed numerous instances in which former HUD
officials have reaped benefits from the program either as
developers or consultants and said many other developers who won
lucrative subsidies under the program were donors to FOOD for
Africa, a Michigan-based charity Demery helped found.
   HUD Inspector General Paul A. Adams told Congress recently that
he found no evidence of criminal activity during his office's
review of the program.
   But the inspector general referred the report to the Justice
Department's Public Integrity Section for a review of whether
Demery violated HUD's conduct standards by associating himself with
the charity, including occasional references to his official
position on invitations to FOOD for Africa events.
   Demery has repeatedly denied any connection between his HUD
decisions and donations to the charity. Attempts to reach him
Monday for comment were not immediately successful.
   In releasing the July 19 letter, Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass.,
said he was not criticizing the department for declining to
prosecute Demery but took issue with a passage in the letter he
said indicated the department would not independently investigate
abuses at HUD during the Reagan administration.
   ``Should you come to obtain information not contained in your
report implicating Mr. Demery or other HUD officials in possible
criminal violations we would be happy to review that information,''
Public Integrity Section Chief Gerald E. McDowell said in the
passage Frank referred to.
   ``Call me if you find anything wrong,'' Frank said was the
attitude the Justice Department was adopting.
   He praised new HUD Secretary Jack Kemp for seeking to reform the
agency but added: ``Elsewhere in the Bush administration we are not
getting the same kind of commitment to clean this mess up.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
