<FIRST>u w AM-DC-10-CrashSurvival     07-24 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-10-Crash Survival,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigative Team Interviews Passengers To Find How They Survived</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special team of investigators is looking
into how so many passengers survived the DC-10 crash in Iowa, with
an eye to increasing the chances of both adults and children of
living through a crash.
   The ``survival factors team'' led by National Transportation
Safety board investigators has interviewed 26 of United Airlines
Flight 232's passengers so far, NTSB spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz
said Monday.
   Most were among those still hospitalized after Wednesday's crash
landing in Sioux City that killed 111 people, Lopatkiewicz said.
   Questionnaires will be sent to all adults among the 185
survivors, the investigation spokesman said in a telephone
interview from Sioux City.
   Lopatkiewicz said the team will ``document the survivability of
the accident'' and try to find out what precautions were most
effective in preventing injury and death when the jetliner burst
into flames, flipped over, landed on its back and split apart in a
cornfield near the Sioux City airport.
   The team will try to interview all adults traveling with
children to see what happened to the youngsters after the pilot
told passengers to prepare for a crash landing.
   Among concerns to be addressed, he said, is the fact that
several infants were traveling free in their parents' arms without
assigned seats _ a common practice on domestic flights.
   At least one infant was among the dead, United said.
   Lopatkiewicz said investigators have not determined exactly how
many of the passengers on Flight 232 from Denver to Chicago were
children or infants or how many children were among the dead.
   A list compiled by The Associated Press shows 24 children under
10 years old, including seven under 5, among the survivors.
   The safety board in 1983 recommended that standards be adopted
for infants' seats on airliners. In 1984 the Federal Aviation
Administration and the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration drew up standards for seats that can be used in both
airliners and cars, but they are not required.
   In addition to board employees, the survival factors team
includes members from the Federal Aviation Administration, the
airline, the engine manufacturer, General Electric Co., the
aircraft manufacturer, McDonnell Douglas Corp., and others
participating in the overall inquiry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
