<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1820EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HUDProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0686 07-24 0870</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0686,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former HUD Official Denies Friendship With Top Aide Gave Her Access</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 3rd graf pvs, bgng: `But when,' to UPDATE
with criticism of Murphy for hiring Dean. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `Ms. Murphy.'
SUBS 7th graf pvs, bgng: `I found,' to remove first reference to Shays</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former federal housing official said Monday
that after joining a private law firm she was shown a HUD internal
document affecting one a client but she denied receiving special
treatment because of her friendship with a top aide to then-HUD
Secretary Samuel Pierce.
   Deborah Gore Dean asked someone ``to show it to me,'' Lynda
Murphy told a congressional subcommittee when asked how she was
able to read a sensitive Department of Housing and Urban
Development document before it was signed by Pierce.
   But when asked whether it would be fair to say her close
friendship with Ms. Dean helped her receive access to internal HUD
information, Ms. Murphy angrily replied: ``I don't think that's a
fair characterization.''
   A Republican member of the subcommittee, Rep. Christopher Shays,
R-Conn., criticized Ms. Murphy for hiring Ms. Dean as a consultant
not long after Ms. Dean left the housing agency.
   ``I'm beginning to feel there is a quid pro quo,'' Shays said.
Ms. Murphy said she did not believe there was anything improper
about hiring Ms. Dean. ``She was a good friend,'' she said later
when asked about their personal relationship.
   Ms. Murphy was one of two witnesses appearing before the House
Government Operations Subcommittee on Employment and Housing, which
is investigating allegations of fraud, abuse, mismanagement and
influence peddling at HUD during the Reagan administration.
   Influence was the central topic Monday, with panel members, Ms.
Murphy and a second witness, Republican National Committeeman
William Taylor, sparring in combative verbal exchanges often laced
with sarcasm and cynicism.
   Taylor, former chairman of the Florida Republican Party,
detailed at length his lobbying on behalf of the city of
Jacksonville and a variety of developers, and he defended his use
of national party stationery to write letters to HUD officials
seeking funding for his clients.
   ``I found nothing wrong with letting people know who I am,''
said Taylor. When Shays said the panel's goal was to rid Washington
of such influence peddling, Taylor retorted: ``Good luck'' and
added ``I didn't invent it.''
   ``I wish you were a Democrat,'' Republican Shays said. ``I am
embarrassed. ... You cashed in on your party.''
   Among those Taylor wrote to were Pierce and Ms. Dean, Pierce's
executive assistant who, according to testimony to Congress and
former HUD officials, was considered by many as ``de facto
secretary'' as far as many funding decisions were concerned in her
more than three years in the post.
   Notes from Ms. Dean that have been obtained by the subcommittee
show that a Georgia project for which Taylor had lobbied was on her
list for funding under the agency's Section 8 Moderate
Rehabilitation program.
   Also on Ms. Dean's approval list for the date April 7, 1987,
according to the notes released by the subcommittee, were 200 units
for ``Boston _ Ed Brooke.'' Brooke is a former Republican senator
who as an attorney has lobbied HUD on behalf of developers.
   Ms. Murphy is a Washington attorney who since leaving HUD in
1982 has had extensive dealings with the agency.
   She said that in the summer of 1985 while her law firm was
representing a client in HUD-related matters, she was shown a draft
of a letter Pierce was preparing to send to DRG Funding Corp., a
major lender in a HUD coinsurance program that had been placed on
probation because of numerous problems with its loan-approval
practices. Pierce criticized the firm for most of a nine-page
letter but in the next-to-last paragraph announced he was lifting
restrictions HUD had placed on the company.
   At the time, DRG was on HUD probation and had to have all its
loans approved in advance. Ms. Murphy's client was applying to DRG
for financing and its project was stalled because DRG had to get
HUD approval of the loan.
   Ms. Murphy said she made comments about the draft letter but
that it was not changed to reflect her position. And she disputed
contentions that she should not have been shown the document before
it was made public, saying there frequently was such ``give and
take about the language'' between HUD officials and representatives
of major firms doing business with the agency.
   Subcommittee member, however, did not accept her justification.
   ``I think you are being evasive,'' Shays said after Ms. Murphy
said she could not respond in detail to his question about Ms.
Dean's role in a later decision involving DRG, this one an
ultimately unsuccessful attempt to help a Houston development on
which HUD coinsured a mortgage that was issued at several times the
property's value.
   The exchanges with Taylor were at times humorous.
   When Taylor told Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., that he had great
respect for the congressman and his ``knack'' for crafting catchy
phrases, Frank responded: ``Why do I feel I should hold on to my
wallet at this moment, Mr. Taylor?''
</TEXT>
