<FIRST>r i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0556 07-24 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0556,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Will Confer with Jaruzelski</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with official announcement of meeting,
Jaruzelski consulting with other parties. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa will meet
with new President Wojciech Jaruzelski to discuss how the new
government should be formed, the state-run news agency said Monday.
   The meeting in Warsaw on Tuesday will be the first since the
army general and Communist Party first secretary was narrowly
elected president by the National Assembly on July 19.
   Jaruzelski began consultations with leaders of the nation's
political and social forces Monday, meeting the chairmen of two
parties allied with his own Communist Party, the PAP news agency
said.
   Jaruzelski is in the process of deciding who to nominate as
Poland's next prime minister and has urged Solidarity to join the
Communist Party in a coalition government.
   Solidarity lawmakers, who as the result of partly democratic
elections in June control the Senate and account for 35 percent of
the parliament's lower house, are deeply divided over whether to
enter into such a coalition.
   On Thursday, Solidarity lawmakers discussed whether to share the
Cabinet with party ministers or whether to demand all the Cabinet
seats including the prime minister's post but excluding control of
the army and police. They also considered whether to stay entirely
out of the government and function solely as a parliamentary
opposition.
   The debate was to resume this week.
   The Walesa-Jaruzelski meeting, confirmed by Walesa aide
Krzysztof Pusz in Gdansk, was expected to give both leaders a
chance to exchange views on how the next government should be
formed.
   On Monday, Jaruzelski met with chairmen of the Peasant's Party
and the Democratic Party, the two allied parties that form the
Communist coalition in the National Assembly, PAP said.
   The new president also will meet with chairmen of the official
OPZZ union, other government-sanctioned groups and the independent
farmers union, Rural Solidarity, the agency said.
   The state news agency announced that Communist Party deputies in
the lower house would confer Tuesday. Solidarity lawmakers will
hold their caucus Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
