<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-24 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms In The Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms gathered Monday over parts of the
southeastern quarter of the nation and into the Midwest, with
locally heavy rain over parts of Florida.
   The wet weather clustered over the Texas coastal region,
Florida, Mississippi, western Alabama, Arkansas, Missouri, and
southern and western Illinois.
   Heavier rain during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included 1.88
inches at Pensacola, Fla., and 1.51 inches at Key West, Fla.
   Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms developed along a
cold front over eastern North Carolina and the middle Atlantic
Coast region.
   West of the major rain activity, widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms developed ahead of an upper-level weather disturbance
over eastern New Mexico and western Texas. A thunderstorm in
south-central Texas spawned several small, short-lived tornadoes
near Corpus Christi, the National Weather Service said.
   Waco, Texas, tied its record overnight low of 65 and Marquette,
Mich., tied its record high of 87.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 106 at Palm Springs, Calif. Monday
morning's low for the Lower 48 states was 39 at Yellowstone
National Park, Wyo.
   For Tuesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the Atlantic Coast states to the Mississippi Valley, and
across the southern Plains, and the southern and central Rockies.
   High in the 60s and 70s were predicted along the Pacific Coast;
in the lower 90s from Florida to the middle Atlantic Coast states
and southern and eastern sections of the Ohio Valley and over
Louisiana and southern Texas, and across most of the nation west of
the Rockies; and above 100 in the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
