<FIRST>u a AM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0624 07-24 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0624,588</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Wins Delay in Case Against Ex-CIA Operative</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 15th graf, bgng ``Independent counsel,'' to update with
letter from Walsh; picks up 16th graf, bgng ``With a.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department, citing national
security concerns, won a delay Monday in the Iran-Contra criminal
case against the CIA's former station chief in Costa Rica.
   A 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals judge in Richmond, Va.,
issued an emergency stay to temporarily block the trial of Joseph
Fernandez.
   The ex-CIA operative's trial was to have started Monday, but the
CIA wanted to stop Fernandez's lawyers from identifying as part of
his defense three CIA programs in Costa Rica and locations of three
CIA stations and facilities in Latin America.
   The Justice Department sought the emergency stay after U.S.
District Court Judge Claude Hilton rejected prosecutors' proposals
to substitute numbers for the three CIA locations and to drop
portions of one criminal charge against Fernandez to avoid
mentioning the CIA programs.
   Hilton said Fernandez must be allowed to mention the names of
the CIA programs and that substituting numbers for names of the
three CIA locations was not acceptable.
   Ron Noble, a deputy assistant attorney general, told the judge
the department would seek a delay of the trial.
   With a pool of prospective jurors waiting in a room adjacent to
the court, the judge, obviously irritated, asked Noble why the
Justice Department didn't take action a week ago.
   ``This is a very difficult thing for the department to do,''
replied Noble. He said the proposals from the prosecutors ``would
allow this trial to go forward. We have no alternative.''
   At the appeals court, the Justice Department is seeking to
formally intervene in the case and wants the court to reconsider
Hilton's denial of the prosecutors' proposals.
   Fernandez is charged with lying about his involvement with
Oliver North's Contra resupply network. He faces two counts of
obstruction and two counts of making false statements in his
responses to the CIA inspector general's office and the Tower
Commission in 1987.
   The Justice Department went to the appeals court instead of
taking an unprecedented step of filing a national security
affidavit with the court. Such a document would categorically bar
disclosure of certain classified information and could kill the
case.
   Fernandez's lawyer, Thomas Wilson, called the Justice
Department's trip to the appeals court unconscionable.
   ``We don't even know what case we're trying,'' complained
Wilson. He said the government has known since charges were first
brought against Fernandez last year that his defense would involve
significant disclosures of classified information.
   Saying that ``enough is enough,'' Wilson called on the Justice
Department to file a national security affidavit.
   In a letter to the Justice Department that was filed in court
Monday, Independent Counsel Lawrence Walsh said that the CIA was
trying to ``protect a fictional secret`' by objecting to the
release of certain classified documents. The Fernandez case, he
said, would be untriable if the department blocks disclosure of the
names of CIA stations as well as of the three CIA Costa Rican
programs.
   Walsh added that if the CIA action to protect documents prevents
the trial from going forward, ``I believe that there must be a
broad re-evaluation of the standards'' under which such power is
exercised.
   With a Justice Department affidavit in hand, Hilton would have
no choice under federal law but to prohibit the ex-CIA operative
from using in his defense the classified information detailed in
the affidavit.
   That could lead to the judge dismissing some or all the criminal
charges, on grounds that the prohibited information was vital to
giving him a fair trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
