<FIRST>r w AM-Honoraria     07-24 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honoraria,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sunny Climates Popular with Members of Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Congress preferred to earn their
speaking fees in sunny climates last year, when 60 lawmakers
traveled to the Caribbean, Florida, California and Hawaii, Common
Cause said Monday.
   The congressional watchdog group also discovered that several
House members received honoraria from their constituents, some
racked up piles of money quickly in what the group called an
``honoraria blitz'' and others earned outside income from private
businesses.
   Members of Congress reported earning more than $9 million in
honoraria last year, usually from special interest groups trying to
influence legislation.
   House and Senate rules allow a member to keep only $2,000 per
appearance. The Senate allows its rank-and-file members to keep
$35,800 in outside income and the House permits retention of
$26,850. Amounts over those figures go to charity.
</TEXT>
