<FIRST>r a AM-HelmsleyTrial     07-24 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helmsley Trial,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Art Dealer Says Hotels Paid for Jade Art Objects for Mansion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harry and Leona Helmsley billed their hotels a
half-million dollars for antique jade figures for their Connecticut
mansion in February 1984, an art dealer testified Monday.
   Mrs. Helmsley returned one of the art objects a year and a half
later and personally cashed a $71,000 refund, witness Sydney
Sahkenazie testified at Mrs. Helmsley's federal tax-evasion trial.
   Ashkenazie said he went along with a scheme to bill the hotels
for the jade by submitting fake invoices for furniture purchases
because the Helmsleys were weeks late in payment and he was having
cash flow problems.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney James DeVita admitted into evidence
invoices that gave detailed descriptions of antique furniture that
didn't change hands.
   In other testimony, the executive vice president of Helmsley
Hotels, Geoffrey Lerigo, said the Park Lane Hotel paid a $10,685
bill for uniforms for the servants at the Greenwich, Conn.,
mansion, Dunnellen Hall.
   The uniforms included suits, clip ties, black trousers and
swallowtail jackets for the butlers; four kinds of aprons, pink
checked and black cotton dresses and matching headpieces for the
maids; and cotton jackets and trousers for the cook.
   Lerigo and Ashkenazie, whose business Ashkenazie &amp; Co. is
located in San Francisco, testified with immunity in U.S. District
Court in Manhattan. Mrs. Helmsley and two former aides, Frank Turco
and Joseph Licari, are charged with tax evasion. Helmsley's case
was severed from his wife's because a series of strokes affected
his memory and he was declared icompetent to stand trial.
   Mrs. Helmsley is accused of evading taxes by disguising $4
million in renovations at Dunnellen Hall and other personal items
as business expenses.
   Ashkenazie said the Helmsleys, who head a $5 billion hotel and
real estate empire, agreed to buy a $210,000 jade water buffalo, a
$150,000 jade mountain, a $80,000 jade incense burner and a $60,000
pair of lavender jade buffalo.
   Five weeks later, after he pressed for payment, Licari
telephoned and told him to send new invoices that indicated the
Helmsleys had bought furniture, Ashkenazie testified.
   ``I don't see how I can do that. We don't deal in furniture,''
Ashkenazie said he told Licari.
   Licari then told him to send blank invoices that he would fill
out in New York and Ashkenazie could keep his own records, he said.
   A year and a half later, Mrs. Helmsley called him and said she
was unhappy with the jade mountain and asked for a refund.
   The Helmsleys decided to take two additional jade objects in
exchange, leaving a $71,000 balance, Ashkenazie testified. He said
he sent the amount in two checks made out to Mrs. Helmsley, who
endorsed and cashed each check.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
