<FIRST>u w AM-Foley-Flag     07-24 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foley-Flag,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley Speaks Against Lightly Amending the Constitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley spoke Monday
against lightly and frivolously amending the Constitution to ban
flag burning.
   ``I cannot imagine why anyone in this country, the president or
anybody else, should favor amending the Constitution unnecessarily
without reason if a statute can accomplish all the objectives that
the president or others seek,'' the Washington Democrat said in his
first appearance as House speaker before the National Press Club.
   Foley and other Democratic leaders contend it is possible to
draft a statute banning flag burning that will meet the standards
of the Supreme Court, which ruled last month in a Texas case that
flag burning was a protected form of free expression.
   President Bush and House and Senate Republican leaders are
backing a constitutional amendment, arguing that a statute can't
work.
   The issue has raised political tensions in Congress, with
Democratic lawmakers opposed to the amendment worried that the GOP
campaign organization will flog them as less patriotic unless they
vote for it.
   ``I think to lightly, frivolously almost, rush forward and amend
the Constitution out of political or partisan or legalistic reasons
when there is an opportunity to consider a statute ... achieving
the objectives is something that we should all be concerned
about,'' Foley said.
   ``The Congress would be wise to draft a statute and see what the
courts do with it,'' he said.
   Congress can include with the statute a provision that would
speed court review, he said.
   The House Judiciary Committee is expected to meet on flag
legislation later this week and Foley said he still intends to
bring a statute to the full House before the August recess.
   Foley said he might not be able to block a House vote on the
constitutional amemdment, but indicated he'd at least like to let
the Senate act first, which it is now scheduled to do in October.
   ``The danger is not only amending the Constitution without
necessity, it's lowering the level of resistance in the Congress
and the country to amendments to the Constitution and most
particularly to the First Amendment, which is the basis as we all
know of speech, religious and press liberty,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
