<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia-Prince,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exiled Prince Calls for Restoration of Monarchy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The heir to Yugoslavia's abolished
throne has called for the restoration of the monarchy as a way to
overcome the economic and political problems in this
Communist-ruled country.
   ``I hope that my country will reform politically so that the
ruling party competes in elections with the full freedom of the
people to decide,'' said Crown Prince Aleksandar Karadjordjevic in
an interview published in the current issue of Start magazine in
Zagreb.
   ``If I ever go to Yugoslavia it will be to live there and to
contribute to its development,'' said Aleksandar who has never been
in Yugoslavia. The interview was held in London where Aleksandar
lives.
   His father, King Peter II, fled Yugoslavia in 1941 during the
Nazi invasion and spent the war years in England where Aleksandar
was born in 1945.
   The king and other members of the royal family were barred from
returning when the monarchy was abolished and a single-party
republic proclaimed in 1945.
   Aleksandar served as an officer in the British army and is now a
succesful businessman.
   Yugoslavia is struggling with soaring inflation, unemployment,
ethnic strife between its various nationalities and divisions
within the Communist Party leadership.
