<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0574 07-24 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0574,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cemeteries Full after 14 Years of Civil War</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs to UPDATE with report Lebanese Shiite factions
pledge to end feud.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of residents fled from
artillery duels in Beirut Monday, some taking their dead with them
amid reports that 14 years of civil war have filled Beirut's
cemeteries to capacity.
   The ghost-town atmosphere also spawned the first major bank
robbery in two years.
   ``I have never seen Beirut in such sadness,'' said one resident.
``It is as if the whole of Lebanon is preparing for a funeral.''
   Syrian gunners killed an elderly Greek Orthodox priest and
wounded three other civilians in a bombardment of Christian east
Beirut and the shore north of the capital, said a police spokesman.
   Christian artillery blasted Syrian batteries along west Beirut's
seafront, but all shells landed offshore and there were no
casualties, said the spokesman.
   He also said six people drowned this weekend trying to get water
from wells in Moslem districts of Beirut, which has been without
water for a week.
   The latest casualties raised the toll to 453 dead and 1,859
injured since the confrontation erupted March 8 between Lebanese
army commander Gen. Michel Aoun's mostly Christian troops and
Moslem Syrian army soldiers.
   The shelling went on sporadically through the night but was less
intense than the weekend bombardment, which underscored Aoun's
attempt to break Syria's naval and land blockades imposed March 14
against the 310-square-mile Christian enclave. Aoun has blockaded
illegal ports operated by Moslem militias.
   Police said 700,000 of the city's 1.5 million residents have
fled since March, with a quarter-million streaming out in recent
days.
   In west Beirut's Mar Elias district, masked gunmen stormed into
the Bank of Beirut for Commerce, locked employees and clients in
one room and escaped with an estimated $40,000, said the police
spokesman.
   Bank robberies proliferated during the lawless period between
1984 and 1987 when feuding Moslem militias fought for control of
west Beirut. Robberies declined after Syria sent troops to restore
order. Syria keeps 40,000 troops in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab
League peacekeeping mandate.
   Lately, caskets have been piling up around the city's
cemeteries, and ambulances and hearses were seen leaving Beirut on
Monday taking the dead to other parts of Lebanon for burial.
   ``Cemeteries in Beirut, the city of death, have no room left for
new graves,'' East Beirut's conservative Ad-Diyar newspaper said
Monday.
   It quoted an unidentified cemetery caretaker as saying:``Graves
are full. The new fatalities will have to remain out in the open
because there is no burial space left.''
   More than 150,000 people have been killed since the civil war
broke out in 1975, mostly in and around Beirut.
   ``We're packed to the brim,'' said a Greek Orthodox priest at
west Beirut's Saint Mary's church, whose courtyard houses the
biggest Christian cemetery in the Moslem sector. ``We have to work
out a system to cope, but I don't know how.''
   Beirut's vast public beaches were deserted Monday and the only
people on the streets searched for water.
   ``Water vendors are making a killing,'' according to Zuheir
Mullah, a janitor who said he had just invested his savings of $750
buying 200 gallons of water, half of which he plans to sell.
Vendors are selling water for about $10 a gallon.
   In Iran, Lebanon's rival Shiite Moslem factions pledged in a
joint communique issued in Tehran to end their 15-month-old feud,
Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
   An estimated 560 people have been killed in fighting between the
Syrian-backed Amal militia and pro-Iranian Hezbollah that erupted
in early July following a five-month lull.
   The communique was published Monday, one day after leaders of
both Shiite factions ended a two-week visit to Iran, according to
the IRNA report monitored in Cyprus.
   Amal and Hezbollah have been fighting to dominate Lebanon's 1.2
million Shiites.
</TEXT>
