<FIRST>r i AM-Mozambique     07-24 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mozambique,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ruling Party Opens National Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frelimo, Mozambique's ruling party,
opened its national congress Monday with strong hints of moving
away from Marxist ideology toward a market-oriented economy.
   The eight-day party congress also is expected to debate a plan
by President Joaquim Chissano calling for negotiation between the
government and rebels of the Mozambique National Resistance,
commonly called Renamo.
   Frelimo, the Front for the Liberation of Mozambique, has ruled
the nation in southeastern Africa since independence from Portugal
in 1975. The rebel war, combined with mismanagement and a weak
infrastructure left by the Portuguese, has made Mozambique one of
the world's poorest countries.
   In his opening address, Chissano appeared to hint at better
relations with businessmen and others who have had little influence
in the past.
   ``Since our essential task is to combat the destabilization of
which the country is a target, all Mozambican classes and social
strata are equally involved in the project'' of rebuilding the
country, he declared.
   Among changes to be considered are admission of property owners,
businessmen, shop owners and the religious faithful to Frelimo
membership.
   Chissano said, however, that religious believers would have to
``accept that the implementation of the party program is no less
important'' than their beliefs. The country has a mixture of
Christians, Moslems and animists.
   Another proposed change would lift restrictions on the number of
workers who can be employed by farmers belonging to Frelimo, which
the official news agency AIM said ``is justified by the need to
increase food production and for party members to lead this drive.''
   It added, however, that a party Central Committee report to be
discussed at the congress ``makes clear its preference for party
members to work in cooperatives.''
   Vigorous debate is expected on economic policy and government
efforts to end the war, which has cost hundreds of thousands of
lives and half the country's 14.7 million people wholly or partly
dependent on food aid.
   The government has been moving to end central control of the
economy since 1983. It has met conditions set by the International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank and has experienced modest growth
in recent years after a decade of decline.
</TEXT>
