<FIRST>r a AM-ExxonValdez     07-24 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon Valdez,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ship Bottom Buckling Concerns Raised Over Impact On Salvageability</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Exxon Pullout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Underwater sections of the hull of the tanker
Exxon Valdez, ripped open on a reef that caused the nation's worst
oil spill, have increasingly buckled and loosened, officials said
Monday.
   ``I want to stress and emphasize we are not yet in a critical
situation,'' Coast Guard Lt. Larry Solberg said. ``We're still
optimistic the ship will be able to come in (for repairs).''
   Solberg said the ship remains seaworthy, but its fate
increasingly is at the mercy of weather and ocean conditions as it
waits off San Diego to be declared free of environmental and
navigational hazards.
   The Valdez spilled nearly 11 million gallons of crude into
Alaska's wildlife-rich Prince William Sound on March 24 after it
went off course and rammed its hull across Bligh Reef.
   Preliminary repairs were made before the ship was towed 2,500
miles to San Diego for repairs in drydock, but during the voyage
huge sections of underwater hull plating pulled away and dangled
beneath the hull.
   Working four to six miles off San Clemente Island, divers
through Monday had cut away five of seven jagged steel plates. They
began the interim repairs Friday and expect to take three to four
more days to finish.
   The dangling plates must be removed so the Valdez can navigate
San Diego Harbor shallows en route to the National Steel and
Shipbuilding Co. yard for a nine-month, $25 million repair job.
   Signs of further hull buckling have been spotted, however.
   ``As these plates loosen, and there are signs more are
loosening, it eventually could reach a point where the
salvageability of the vessel could be in doubt,'' Solberg said.
``The reason being, it might not have enough bottom for adequate
support while the ship is in dry dock.''
   Exxon Shipping Co. spokeswoman Jan Cool said the company was
confident the ship will make it to the NASSCO shipyard.
   ``We feel pretty confident that we're going to arrest any
further deterioration of the hull by cutting the plates which are
hanging down ... and cutting small pieces of plate before they pull
away any further,'' Cool said.
   Cool acknowledged a worsening of ocean conditions could
exacerbate the buckling of the ship's hull.
   ``Obviously, at some point, I don't know where that point is,
the ship would have difficulty in dry docking because you need a
bottom to support her,'' said Fred Hallet, NASSCO's vice president
of finance and public relations.
   Cool said no one has calculated just how much of the damaged
hull needs to be removed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
