<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1938EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ExxonPullout     07-24 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon Pullout,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Says Fall Pullout Non-Negotiable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State environmental officials said Monday
they are unhappy with Exxon's plan to withdraw its oil spill
cleanup forces from Prince William Sound by mid-September, but the
company says the pullout is not negotiable.
   ``We've been saying all along we would operate until about Sept.
15 when we have to shut down because of the weather,'' said Exxon
spokesman Henry Beathard. ``None of that has changed.
   ``Generally Sept. 15 is an average date. Sometimes bad weather
starts before that; sometimes after that.''
   A July 19 memo from Otto Harrison, Exxon's general manager in
Valdez, to company officials indicates Exxon is adamant about a
mid-September pullout.
   He said Exxon will conduct no winter cleanup operations because
of safety and operational reasons and the company's only commitment
for next spring is to survey the shorelines.
   ``These are not negotiable points,'' he wrote in the memo, a
copy of which was provided to The Associated Press.
   The memo was dated the day before Exxon President Bill Stevens'
testimony to the National Ocean Policy Study Subcommittee of the
Senate Commerce, Science and Transportion Committee. He reluctantly
committed the company to resuming operations next year if more work
needs to be done.
   But Steve Provant, on-scene oil spill coordinator for the Alaska
Department of Environmental Conservation, said his agency wants
Exxon to leave a contingency force behind to deal with oil that may
wash off beaches and cause problems during the winter.
   ``We're not asking them to do any beach cleaning or anything
like that in the winter,'' he said.
   An army of 11,000 people, 1,000 vessels and more than 70
aircraft has been trying to clean beaches stained by the nation's
largest oil spill. The Exxon Valdez rammed Bligh Reef on March 24,
spilling about 11 million gallons of crude oil into the sound's
pristine waters.
   ``You can't work up to the last day and pull them all out,''
Beathard said. ``We're working on a plan that gets them out by
Sept. 15. That's the average date of when the winter storms set in
and you can no longer operate out there.''
   He said studies to determine the exact day the last Exxon
workers would be withdrawn should be completed in about two weeks.
   Exxon on Monday announced that the cleanup costs stemming from
the spill had reduced its second-quarter profit by $850 million.
   Provant said his agency believes the Sept. 15 date is
``arbitrary,'' and that it might be possible to have some crews
continue working in the sound until Oct. 1.
   ``We would like to see that they still maintain come capability
to continue working as long as the weather is nice. Plans to have
everything out of here by Sept. 15 just seems too rigid to us,''
Provant said. ``The DEC plans winter activities such as
overflights, mapping, beach monitoring and collection of water
quality data.
   But Beathard said that was out of the question. ``We have no
intention of doing that. We think it's a safety factor. We've never
talked about operating in the winter on the cleanup,'' he said.
   The memo also said Exxon's ``discussions with federal or state
agencies is for the purpose of keeping them informed, and is not
requesting approval. In discussions on these matters you should
stress the safety and operational factors. We are willing to
discuss these factors. We are not willing to discuss the
decisions.''
   Beathard said a shoreline assessment would be undertaken in the
spring.
   ``We're saying we do not think that any cleanup operations will
be needed because we plan to work on all the shorelines before we
pull out,'' he said. ``There will be some oil that remains on some
shorelines or down in the gravel.
   ``But we believe six months of winter storms and tidal action
will remove most, if not all, of what's remaining,'' Beathard said.
``If there is remaining oil next spring it will be asphaltic in
nature and it would be more environmentally damaging to remove it
than to leave it there. It poses no environmental threat.''
</TEXT>
