<DOCNO> AP890724-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 2112EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LiteratureTests     07-24 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Literature Tests,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expert: Literature Tests So Poorly Written They Encourage Shortcuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Standardized literature tests are so poorly
written they encourage students to read condensed versions of
classics, a study released Monday concluded.
   Multiple-choice exams are more apt to test students on memorized
facts than on ideas, said the study by researchers at the State
University of New York at Albany.
   ``The reading of a poem is treated like reading an encyclopedia.
What are the facts? It's the Joe Friday approach to education,''
said Alan Purves, co-director of the university's Center for the
Learning and Teaching of Literature.
   Purves recommended that standardized tests, like the Scholastic
Aptitude Test for college-bound students, also use essay questions
to make students think about what they've read. He said students
can easily get by reading commercial plot summaries.
   Multiple choice tests satisfy school districts' needs for
accountability without truly measuring competence, Purves said.
   ``They aren't particularly interested in how good the
measurements of accountability are, just so they can have a number
they can throw in front of their school board,'' he said.
   Educational Testing Service, which produces the Scholastic
Aptitude Test, has written multiple-choice test questions that
measure analysis and interpretive abilities, spokeswoman Janet
Waanders said.
   ``It is true that there can be good multiple-choice questions
about interpretation,'' Purves said. ``What we found was that there
were very few of them on these tests.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
