<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Jews     07-24 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Jews,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules Government Must Recognize Jewish Conversions Abroad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARIEH O'SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court decided Monday that the
government must recognize conversions to Judaism by Reform and
Conservative rabbis abroad, starting a new round in a controversy
that has angered many American Jews.
   In another decision, a five-judge panel of the court upheld an
Orthodox monopoly by rejecting an appeal that Reform rabbis be
allowed to perform marriages in Israel.
   The 4-1 ruling on the ``Who is a Jew'' question prompted leaders
of the ultra-Orthodox Agudat Israel party to meet Monday night and
discuss whether to to withdraw support from Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir's coalition government. ``We have a secular court
interfering in a religious subject,'' said Agudat legislator
Menachem Porush. The party has five seats of the 120 seats in
Parliament.
   Orthodox rabbis echoed Religious Affairs Minister Zevulun
Hammer's pledge to renew the campaign for a narrower definition of
who is a Jew, Israel radio reported.
   ``The problem remains as an open wound and will not be solved
until it is solved at its roots: that a Jew is a Jew only according
to Halacha,'' Chief Rabbi Avraham Shapira of Israel's European
Jewish Community said on Israel radio. Halacha is orthodox Jewish
law.
   Interior Minister Arye Deri of Shas, an ultra-Orthodox party,
said he would stop signing identity cards issued by his ministry.
``My signature means that information in the identity card is
true,'' he said. ``If the court says I cannot decide about that, I
shall not sign.''
   Israel radio said identity cards would carry a sticker saying
data contained in the ``nationality'' and ``religion'' sections
could not be verified.
   In Washington, Rabbi Eric Yoffie of the Association of Reform
Zionists of America said: ``We're very pleased. What it means is
that the law that currently exists ... will now be enforced.''
   Phil Baum, associate executive director of the American Jewish
Congress, said: ``At a time when there appears to be dissension and
division, this is a welcome affirmation that the common bonds of
Jewish history and fate have endured and continue to bind us into
one people.''
   The court ruling revives an argument over Orthodox efforts to
amend Israel's Law of Return to limit those automatically entitled
to Israeli citizenship.
   Orthodox Jews want to include only Jews born to Jewish mothers
or converted according to Halacha, which in effect would mean by
Orthodox rabbis.
   Current Israeli law also grants automatic citizenship to anyone
who has converted to Judaism and is not a member of another faith.
   The change has been fought by Conservative and Reform rabbis,
whose followers constitute a majority of more than 5 million U.S.
Jews but who have few adherents in Israel. They say the Orthodox
proposal would symbolically excommunicate them from Judaism and
alienate U.S. Jews from Israel.
   Rabbis in the United States make about 11,000 conversions a
year, while Orthodox rabbis perform about 1,000.
   The Supreme Court favored appeals from eight American immigrants
and one from Brazil who were denied Israeli citizenship by the
Interior Ministry.
   The court's ruling said an Israeli Population Register Law of
1965 did not entitle the government to decide the validity of
conversions outside the country.
   ``On this matter, it has no bearing on whether the community
(conducting the conversion) is Orthodox, Conservative or Reform,''
the court said.
   The marriage ruling came on appeals made seven years ago by
Rabbi Moshe Zemer of Baltimore and an Israeli rabbi, Mordechai
Rotem.
   The judges upheld three laws that give Israel's Orthodox rabbis
exclusive rights to decide eligibility for presiding at marriages.
</TEXT>
