<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 2050EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-ShrimperProtest 3rdLd-Writethru a0720 07-24 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shrimper Protest, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0720,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mosbacher Temporarily Suspends Enforcement On Turtle Devices</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 7-10: ``In Galveston,'' with reaction of shrimpers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher on Monday
temporarily suspended regulations requiring shrimpers to use new
devices intended to protect endangered sea turtles from getting
entangled and dying in their nets.
   Mosbacher's decision came on the heels of weekend protests by
angry shrimpers who blocked ship channels along the Texas Gulf
Coast and threatened violence if the regulations were not changed
or reversed on use of so-called turtle excluders.
   ``We have worked out what I think is a good compromise that
indicates sympathy to the shrimpers and their families as well as
caring about the endangered species in general and the Kemp's
Ridley turtles in particular,'' Mosbacher said after meeting with
gulf state lawmakers.
   Mosbacher said enforcement of the turtle excluder regulations
would be suspended for 45 days. At the end of the period, shrimpers
would be required to pull their nets every 90 minutes but would not
have to use the turtle excluders.
   According to lawmakers, turtles can live for 90 minutes
underwater if trapped in a net.
   After the 45-day period is up, however, the Commerce Department
enforcement staff would issue warnings to shrimpers caught not
pulling their nets after 90 minutes. The agency would re-evaluate
the regulations next year. A study by the National Academy of
Sciences is expected to be completed in February.
   In Galveston, Texas, hundreds of shrimpers awaiting word of
Mosbacher's action at the Galveston Coast Guard station broke into
cheers when they heard the news.
   ``This is a lot more than we though we'd get,'' said Richard
Santini of Galveston, who estimated he lost $6,000 to $7,000 during
the ship channel blockade. ``We can make a living now.''
   In Cameron, La., boat owner Ashful Authement said: ``If they go
for 90 minutes, I can relate to that. But there are some times
(when) it might take you that long to find a good fishing spot and
then you have to stop and pick up.''
   ``At the end of 45 days, it seems like we're facing the same
thing again,'' said Cameron deck hand Paul Miller.
   ``We got a good deal,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas. ``I think
it is a reasonable compromise. It represents a sound way to
approach the problem.''
   But one environmental group planned to organize a national
boycott of shrimp as a result of Mosbacher's action.
   ``The radical action of the secretary of commerce has convinced
us that we need to take some radical action,'' said Mike Weber,
vice president of programs for the Center for Marine Conservation.
   Weber's organization also planned to seek a temporary
restraining order against Mosbacher.
   The shrimpers had contended their business would be ruined by
the turtle excluder regulations.
   In Galveston, Texas, on Monday, shrimpers met with
representatives of the Coast Guard, the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration and the National Marine Fisheries
Service about the rule, which was issued under the federal
Endangered Species Act.
   About 200 shrimp boats on Saturday crowded the deep-water
Houston ship channel and about 300 shrimpers jammed Port Aransas,
gateway to the Port of Corpus Christi, Texas. Those blockades, as
well as similar actions at smaller Texas and Louisiana ports, ended
Sunday pending the outcome of the meetings Monday.
   Ship traffic was reported normal Monday, Coast Guard officials
said.
   The turtle devices are intended to save many of the 11,000
turtles that conservationists estimate are killed each year in
shrimp nets. The devices, which cost from $60 to several hundred
dollars each, are made of wire mesh and have hinged doors to allow
turtles to swim out before the net is pulled aboard a boat.
   Shrimpers say the devices allow valuable shrimp to escape as
well. The shrimpers also complain that the hinged devices are
bulky, dangerous and expensive to operate.
   The rule requiring the devices was to take effect May 1, but its
enforcement has been sporadic.
   Failure to use the devices, which federal officials say cost
shrimpers 6 to 7 percent of their catch, could result in fines of
up to $25,000 and six months in jail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
