<DOCNO> AP890724-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 2103EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Strike 3rdLd-Writethru a0702 07-24 0928</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strike, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0702,0955</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says Strikes Highlight Need to Overhaul Councils</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Speaking to...' with two grafs to move up reference
to Gorbachev saying republics should decide when to hold elections. Pick
up 5th pvs, `The Kremlin...' Minor editing thereafter.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev said Monday the
strikes in Soviet coalfields were the biggest test of his four-year
economic reforms _ worse than the Chernobyl disaster _ and he
called for a shake-up of local councils often blamed for blocking
progress.
   Gorbachev appealed last week for a ``renewal'' of Communist
Party ranks from top to bottom, and his suggestion that local
governing bodies also be transformed could mean sweeping leadership
changes.
   Local elections scheduled in the spring throughout the Soviet
Union involve multiple candidates and for the first time offer
serious challenges to entrenched officials.
   Some members of the national legislature, the Supreme Soviet,
said Monday the elections should be held earlier. Gorbachev said
each Soviet republic should decide when and how to hold the
elections.
   He said party and government bodies as well as official trade
unions should meet urgently to analyze the two-week strike that at
its peak idled half the Soviet Union's 1 million coal industry
workers and deprived vital factories of fuel.
   The Kremlin chief told legislators almost all the miners have
returned to work.
   ``We are coming out of a very serious crisis, the biggest test
during the four years of perestroika,'' Gorbachev said.
   He said the test was even more severe than the April 1986
explosion and fire at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant that killed
31 people, cost millions of dollars to clean up and sparked a
nationwide environmental protection movement.
   The strikes dealt a serious blow to the economy, Gorbachev said,
but he reassured his countrymen that ``our perestroika will give
results despite the tests we are undergoing.''
   He blamed Coal Ministry and local officials rather than the
miners, but warned, ``deciding such questions by striking will ruin
our work.''
   Communist maverick Boris N. Yeltsin told the Supreme Soviet that
local party and government leaders have been inactive and
insensitive to people's needs because ``they know they won't be
re-elected.''
   Gorbachev said that because of the strike, governing councils
should not wait for elections to make changes.
   ``Ripe questions require sessions without delay to discuss
reports of regional executive committees, and where it is necessary
to take personnel decisions, they must be taken without waiting for
elections,'' he said.
   Several heads already have rolled, Tass official news agency
reported. It said the party chief and mayor of Stakhanov in the
Donetsk Basin ``were forced to leave their posts,'' apparently
under pressure from strikers.
   One legislator suggested strike committees be absorbed into
local governing councils because they proved they can get things
done.
   In a meeting last Tuesday with party officials, Gorbachev said
the party also needs ``a flow of fresh blood, and ... to be renewed
at the level of the work place, the locality, the city, the region,
the republic, the central committee and the Politburo.''
   He said Monday that party bodies should analyze reasons for the
strikes, which miners started to press for better supplies of food,
consumer goods and housing as well as higher pay and better working
conditions.
   He balked at calls for independent unions, suggesting instead
the official unions ``think over what happened and what to do to
make sure unions carry out their role.''
   Deputies speaking at Monday's nationally broadcast session said
the country needs better unions.
   ``We have to admit the trade unions don't have the workers'
faith,'' said Lithuanian deputy Kazimeras Uoka. ``We have to give
them the right to establish independent trade unions.''
   Soviet unions act as djuncts of the government, handling
distribution of benefits rather than fighting for workers' rights.
   Several deputies from mining regions also called for moving up
local elections to this fall to give voters a chance to oust
insensitive officials.
   Gorbachev said such decisions should be taken in the 15 Soviet
republics, not in Moscow, even if it means election laws and
schedules will vary.
   ``Shall we torpedo and limit this?'' he asked. ``We will hardly
succeed, commanding from here.''
   The Soviet president said at least half the 300,000 striking
miners in the Donetsk Basin, the country's biggest coal-producing
area, have returned to work. Tass said about 50 of the region's 121
mines remain idle.
   Donetsk strikers were among the last holdouts from a nationwide
coal strike that started July 11 in western Siberia and spread from
the Arctic to Central Asia. Last week, the government granted
concessions and Siberian miners returned to work.
   A strike leader in Donetsk, in the Ukraine 550 miles south of
Moscow, said by telephone that workers are awaiting ``decisive
guarantees'' from the Supreme Soviet that the government will keep
promises made to miners Saturday. The Supreme Soviet took no action
Monday to guarantee the pact, instead juggling legislation to give
priority to strike issues.
   A deputy from the Pechora coal basin in the Arctic told the
Supreme Soviet that miners around the city of Vorkuta remain on
strike, partly because of media ``disinformation.'' Miner Vladimir
P. Lushnikov said state media reported erroneously that the Vorkuta
strike had ended.
   Reports said miners remained on strike at 11 of 13 Vorkuta mines
and all 12 mines in Chervonograd in the western Ukraine.
   Viktor G. Kucherenko, head of the Supreme Soviet's Planning and
Budget Commission, said the strike settlements probably will cost
between $4.6 billion and $8.6 billion.
</TEXT>
