<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-Fires 1stLd-Writethru a0672 07-24 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Fires, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0672,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forest Fires in Manitoba Force Evacuation of 18,000</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE and add details. No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forest fires raging through northern
Manitoba have forced the evacuation of more than 18,000 people, and
smoke and flames threatened to block some escape routes.
   The airport in Thompson was reopened Monday after radar
equipment was flown in to help guide airplanes. Pilots were unable
to locate the runways because of the dense smoke.
   Convoys of trucks loaded with food and fuel and escorted by
police drove north from Winnipeg to reach Thompson about 470 miles
away. Some 4,000 evacuees were being sheltered in Thompson, a
mining town with a normal population of 15,000. The fires were
several miles away from Thompson and there was no immediate threat
to the town.
   Just east of Thompson firefighters sprayed water on a wooden
bridge of a railroad used to move evacuees.
   ``If that bridge goes out then that escape route is cut off to
Churchill,'' Manitoba Natural Resources Minister Harry Enns told a
news conference.
   Churchill is a Hudson Bay port city 260 miles northeast of
Thompson. The railroad also links Thompson to the south.
   Enns said all available equipment was being used to evacuate
people and to block flames from sweeping through communities.
   Officials said only a few houses have burned and they had no
reports of injuries or deaths.
   Scores of fires have broken out in parched northern Manitoba in
recent weeks, but winds fanned the blazes last week and they now
form a belt more than 200 miles wide beginning about 240 miles
north of Winnipeg. Evacuations started Thursday as flames
threatened communities.
   Officials said fires in northern Saskatchewan forced 1,200
residents of Sandy Bay to flee their homes Saturday. They said that
in northwestern Ontario, 400 people living at Bearskin Lake were
flown out Thursday.
   The fires have swept through at least 2 million acres of brush
and timber in a mainly flat area.
   Military transport planes, trains and private vehicles were
being used to remove people from threatened towns in Manitoba in
what is believed to be the largest evacuation in the province's
history. Officials said 13 towns have been completely evacuated
since Thursday and a number of other towns were either partly
evacuated or the residents were on standby.
   About 8,500 people were evacuated when floods ravaged Manitoba
in 1950.
   Manitoba officials estimated there are about 250 fires in the
fire belt, but they said the figures are uncertain.
   ``There is too much smoke; we can't even see the new fires,''
said Karin Batke of Manitoba's natural resources department.
   Manitoba officials said at least 1,500 firefighters, 53
helicopters, 11 waterbombers, nine fixed-wing aircraft and heavy
equipment including bulldozers have been thrown into the battle.
   A state of emergency was declared Sunday by Albert Driedger,
Manitoba's minister of emergency measures. Retired or vacationing
civil servants were asked to report for duty as exhausted relief
workers toiled around the clock.
   ``Virtually all of northern Manitoba is on fire, and we're just
hoping some of our major centers are not going to be affected,''
Driedger said. ``Once you get 15 minutes out of Winnipeg, all you
see is smoke.''
   Lightning is blamed for most of the fires, but police believe
people started at least two.
   Weather forecasts said there could be thundershowers in the
areas, but the storms could cause more lightning-set fires.
</TEXT>
