<FIRST>r a AM-FloodRescue     07-24 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flood Rescue,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Body Recovered of Boy Lost in Dramatic Rescue Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities on Monday recovered the
body of a teen-ager who had clung to a rescue rope in swift waters
in a flood-control channel but lost his grip when he was hit by
debris.
   The body of Peter Alvarado, 17, was discovered in the Alameda
Arroya, said Anthony Garcia, a member of the aquatic rescue team of
the Bernalillo County Fire Department.
   The body was recovered 10 to 12 miles away from where Alvarado
and his brother, David, 14, were skateboarding Sunday in a concrete
flood-control channel when they were hit by a 3-foot-high wall of
water.
   The National Weather Service said an inch of rain fell in the
area in less than an hour.
   David was rescued and was treated for cuts and bruises at St.
Joseph Hospital, Fire Department spokesman Ernie Watson said.
   Firefighters had tried to pull out Peter Alvarado as he clung to
a rope Sunday, but a sudden surge of water carried a floating chair
into him, forcing him to let go.
   At least 10 people, including four police officers and four
firefighters, were injured trying to rescue the brothers.
   Clayton Mitsui, 23, and Manuel Rubio, 17, who were attending a
church picnic near the channel, were pulled in as they tried to
rescue the Alvarados.
   Firefighters and police rushed to various points along the
channel and threw ropes across to try to stop the men.
   Police officer John Bode went into the channel and grabbed one
person, but lost his grip. Bode clung to a rope across the channel
as other officers and bystanders struggled to pull him out, forming
a chain along the steep, slippery walls of the channel.
   Meanwhile, firefighter Lawrence Padilla reached for Mitsui with
a long pole but got pulled in. Padilla had on a life vest and tried
to keep hold of Mitsui.
   ``There were a few times he said, `That's it. I can't go any
farther.' I said, `Hey, we're in this together.' I started talking
to him, and he relaxed. I knew someone would get us,'' Padilla said.
   The two were eventually rescued after traveling 1{ miles down
the channel.
   Rubio also was rescued, grabbing a rope thrown to him by
firefighters.
</TEXT>
