<FIRST>u a AM-RapeRecant 1stLd-Writethru a0612 07-24 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rape Recant, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0612,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects State's Move to Block New Trial for Gary Dotson</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with prosecutor's comments, genetic tests,
other details.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A circuit judge on Monday rejected efforts to
block a new trial for a convicted rapist who is on parole and whose
victim recanted her charges four years ago.
   Cook County Circuit Judge Thomas R. Fitzgerald ruled that
genetic test results obtained by Gary Dotson's attorneys constitute
important new evidence. He denied two motions by prosecutors to
dismiss a petition for a new trial.
   Defense attorney Thomas Breen said the ruling paves the way for
a trial that will finally vindicate Dotson.
   ``It's great,'' Breen said after the hearing. ``We're 90 percent
there.''
   But Assistant State's Attorney Gayle Shines said it was
speculation to talk of a new trial. She said the state will outline
its position at a hearing Aug. 14. At that point, Fitzgerald will
schedule a hearing that likely will determine whether a new trial
will take place.
   Ms. Shines said prosecutors have not decided what approach to
take regarding the evidence that Dotson's attorneys say proves he
did not rape Cathleen Crowell Webb.
   Breen said genetic-test results prove that semen found on the
underpants worn by Ms. Webb the night in July 1977 when she said
she was raped was not Dotson's.
   But Ms. Shines said the defense has failed to prove the test
results have ``a substantial probability'' of changing the outcome
of the original trial, a requirement for granting a new trial based
on new evidence.
   And under state law, evidence of semen is not required to prove
that a rape occurred, she said. ``Evidence that Gary Dotson was not
the seminal donor cannot by itself change the results of the
trial,'' Ms. Shines said.
   She also argued that the statute of limitations on a bid for a
new trial expired two years after Dotson's 1979 conviction on
charges of rape and aggravated kidnapping.
   Fitzgerald rejected the argument, noting Breen's petition
contends that some evidence in the case was fraudulently concealed,
which would override the law.
   Dotson was not present, but a sister attended the hearing.
``We're going to prove once and for all that he didn't do it,''
said Laura Dotson, 26.
   Dotson was sentenced to a 25- to 50-year prison term after his
conviction. But in 1985, Ms. Webb recanted her testimony. Now a
Jaffrey, N.H., homemaker, she said she made up the attack because
she feared she had become pregnant by her boyfriend.
   Gov. James R. Thompson granted Dotson clemency, saying his
punishment had been sufficient. But the governor said he did not
believe Ms. Webb's about-face, and has refused to pardon Dotson.
   Dotson, 32, remains in an alcoholism treatment center as a
condition of his parole last August. He had been returned to prison
in December 1987 for a parole violation.
   Since his 1985 release, Dotson has had recurring minor problems
with the law, mostly driving violations. He also had faced two
misdemeanor battery charges, one stemming from an altercation in a
bar and the other prompted by an allegation of abuse from his wife.
Both charges were dropped.
   Dotson married shortly after his release. The couple have a
daughter.
</TEXT>
