<HEAD>Bloch Leaves Daughter's Westchester Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 4-5, bgn `Chip Broshaus...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with daughter returning home alone and give background on Soviets following
Bloch.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Diplomat-Spy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man suspected of spying for the Soviets
walked through the woods behind his daughter's home Monday, jumped
into the car she was driving and headed south, followed by a parade
of federal autos.
   ``We knew he was there and that he left,'' said New Castle
Police Chief Steve Fuchila. He would not give details of the
departure, but other officers who were at the scene said Felix
Bloch left the house by the back door and went through the woods
where he was picked up by his daughter, Kathy Swenson.
   The car headed south on the Saw Mill River Parkway, the federal
cars in tow, said the officers, who declined to be identified. The
parkway leads south to New York City.
   The daughter returned alone at 6 p.m., carrying shopping bags.
She entered a next-door neighbor's house.
   When Bloch drove to his daughter's house on Saturday, FBI agents
tailed him and were followed in turn by Soviet Embassy personnel,
according to a government source familiar with the case.
   The local police chief said the FBI had notified him of a
surveillance operation in the area, but did not disclose details.
However, a police source said the Hamilton Road residence had been
under federal observation for several days before Friday, when
reports surfaced that Bloch, a 30-year veteran of the State
Department, had been filmed last spring exchanging a briefcase with
a known KGB agent.
   There are no formal charges against Bloch and U.S. officials
have declined to go beyond confirming that he is the target of an
intelligence investigation and no longer has access to the State
Department building.
   Joseph Valiquette, the New York-area FBI spokesman, would not
comment.
   Chappaqua is a quiet, affluent community in northern Westchester
County, is part of the Town of New Castle. Houses in Mrs. Swenson's
neighborhood, which is not the ritziest area of the hamlet, sell
for $400,000 and up.
   The house was dark and shuttered, except for two open windows on
the second floor. Part of the yard recently had been worked on, and
a bag of weeds and lawn clippings had been left out.
</TEXT>
