<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 2216EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BrownDesegregation     07-24 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brown Desegregation,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Reconsidering Historic Topeka Schools Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court is reconsidering Brown vs.
Topeka Board of Education after withdrawing a recent ruling in
which it revived the historic case, a court official said Monday.
   The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Denver last week
withdrew its June 2 decision in the desegregation case without
explanation.
   ``It's as if there had been no opinion ever filed,'' said Robert
Hoecker, the court's clerk. ``They will reconsider the case.''
   Hoecker said he did not know if the court would hold new
hearings or base the new decision on existing testimony and
evidence. He also said he did not know why the decision was made.
   Attorneys in the case said they found out about the withdrawal
Friday and were unsure what the action means for the Topeka, Kan.,
school system.
   ``This is purely my speculation. I think somewhere in the
dissent someone is criticizing somebody else, and the majority
wants an opportunity to respond to that criticism,'' said Rich
Jones, a Topeka lawyer who represents the plaintiffs in the
35-year-old case.
   In 1987, U.S. District Judge Richard Rogers of Topeka ruled that
Topeka's public school district no longer had any illegal or
intentional separation of races.
   In June, the appeals court overturned Rogers' ruling, saying the
Topeka school system had not done enough to overcome remnants of
the segregated school system that existed before the U.S. Supreme
Court decided the landmark Brown vs. Topeka Board of Education case
in 1954. The appeals court ordered Rogers to devise a remedy for
what it called the racially identifiable schools in Topeka.
   Topeka Superintendent Gary Livingston said he and his staff are
still unsure what the appeals court action means, and he will be
meeting with attorneys.
   The 1954 Supreme Court decision held that the ``separate but
equal'' concept for public schools was unconstitutional.
   The case was reopened in 1979 when the parents of 17 Topeka
public schoolchildren sought a decision on whether the schools had
eliminated traces of the segregated system. The parents included
Linda Brown Buckner, who as a student in 1954 gave the case its
name.
</TEXT>
