<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Painting     07-24 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Painting,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports Gaugin Painting Stolen From Heathrow Airport</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Monday they are investigating the
reported theft from London's Heathrow airport of a Paul Gaugin
painting owned by the Beadlestone Gallery of New York.
   The London Daily Mail newspaper said the painting was valued at
more than $1.9 million and was stolen from a cargo hangar at the
airport.
   It said the watercolor measuring nine inches by four inches is
titled ``Tahitienne en Pareo Rouge'' _ Tahitian woman in a red
skirt.
   Gaugin, a Frenchman born in 1848, lived and painted in Tahiti in
the South Pacific from 1895 until his death in 1903.
   Scotland Yard, in a brief statement about the reported theft,
said, ``The matter is the subject of an inquiry by the Criminal
Investigation Department at Heathrow.''
   The Daily Mail said the painting was one of four pictures that
arrived at Heathrow on a British Airways flight from New York on
June 21.
   It said the consignment remained in the British Airways cargo
hangar until the owners arrived to collect them five days later.
Each painting was in a separate box and only the one containing the
Gaugin painting was missing, according to the newspaper. It gave no
information about the three other painting.
   The Daily Mail said the theft was not reported to police until
Sunday, but it gave no reason for the delayed report.
   It quoted the Beadlestone Gallery's New York director Susan
Seidel as saying: ``It is a work of art of the very finest quality.
It was to have been part of an exhibition at our London gallery.''
</TEXT>
