<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 2306EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ChemicalDerailment 1stLd-Writethru a0742aulAllegre 07-24
0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chemical Derailment, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0742,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Nearly Out, Residents Still Away From Homes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to restore writethru designation. SUBS 3rd graf,
`Some people...,' with 6 grafs to UPDATE with brakeman entering substance
abuse program, blood and urine tests given to crew members, other details.
Picks up 4th graf pvs, ```I've always...' SUBS 13th graf pvs, `R. Lindsay...,'
to delete superfluous first reference.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF HOLYFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FREELAND, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hazardous materials experts reassured
hundreds of displaced families Monday that fumes from a chemical
fire won't hurt their homes, and one official said even garden
vegetables will be edible.
   The experts were monitoring a burning tank car that forced
officials to keep a 15 square-mile area cordoned off for a third
day Monday.
   Meanwhile, a CSX railroad spokesman reported that the brakeman
on the CSX freight train, which derailed Saturday, checked himself
into a local hospital's substance abuse program that night.
   Within hours of the derailment, the brakeman and other crew
members submitted blood and urine samples for federally required
drug and alcohol testing, said R. Lindsay Leckie, senior manager of
news and information for the railroad. The brakeman later told
railroad officials he wanted to enter the hospital's drug and
alcohol abuse program, Leckie said.
   Leckie emphasized that human error had been ruled out as a cause
of the derailment, and that brakeman's decision wasn't expected to
alter that.
   The brakeman was riding in the first of two locomotives pulling
tank cars on a run from Port Huron to Midland and was not at the
controls when the train derailed, said Leckie and William Loftus,
executive director of the Federal Railroad Administration.
   Test results on the entire crew were expected later this week,
Leckie said.
   Some people forced from their homes by the fiery derailment,
meanwhile, said they wanted to move even if everything is OK.
   ``I've always had a gut feeling something would happen. I've
always looked at those tank cars and wondered what kind of poison
was in them,'' said Stanley Siminski, 77, who lives near the
railroad tracks.
   ``My wife and I are talking about getting out. I don't know if
we'll be able to sell now.''
   Gladys Gott, who lives three-quarters of a mile from the
derailment, said she also wants to move. ``I don't think I'll feel
safe,'' she said. ``You don't know what that stuff is.''
   The tracks where the derailment occurred have been used for more
than 10 years to carry toxic chemicals between Freeport, Texas, and
nearby Midland, on a regularly scheduled run known as the Unit
Train.
   Experts decided Monday to speed up the burning of the chemical
by pumping air into the car and boosting the fire, which burst from
a gash in the car.
   The chemical, chlorosilene, emits hydrochloric acid as it burns,
but Steve Buser, director of hazardous materials for CSX, said the
amounts were low and were dissipating into the air.
   Buser said it was impossible to tell how long it would take the
chemical to burn away, but he said he believed little was left in
the tank car.
   At the car, the amount of acid in the air was within safety
limits and 150 yards away monitors detected none, he said, adding
that houses, cars, and other personal possessions wouldn't be
damaged.
   Food from gardens would be safe after it was thoroughly washed,
said Rod Jordan of the Michigan Department of Agriculture.
   Leckie said 250 to 350 people had registered with the Red Cross
to get the railroad to pay for motel rooms, meals and clothing.
   Other evacuees had gone to stay with friends and relatives,
Leckie said. The railroad also will pay businesses forced to close
by the evacuation and reimburse pay lost by those unable to go to
work, he added.
   Investigators from CSX, the National Transportation Safety
Board, and the Federal Railroad Administration said it was too
early to determine the cause of the crash.
   Calls for slower speeds for trains carrying hazardous materials
were answered by the state government Monday.
   ``Train speed is just one factor. You could have equipment
failure contributing to it also. You can't say that speed, whether
it's going 25 or 40 mph, would be a contributing factor. The track
condition is good for 40 mph,'' said Don Riel, assistant
administrator of the Rail Safety and Traffic Division of the
Michigan Department of Transportation.
   The train was traveling at 37 mph when it derailed, officials
said.
</TEXT>
