<FIRST>r a AM-NavyCrash     07-24 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy Crash,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Jet Crashes on Takeoff, Killing Two</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH ISLAND NAVAL AIR STATION, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy jet used to
jam enemy radar crashed on takeoff during a training run Monday,
killing two of its three crew members.
   A third crew member was ``in good shape'' listed in stable
condition at Balboa Naval Hospital in San Diego, said a Navy
spokesman, Lt. Jack Papp.
   The twin-engine EA-6B Prowler went down at 5:27 p.m. at this
base on the Coronado Peninsula near San Diego, Papp said.
   ``It was just at the end of its takeoff. ... It crashed just as
it reached the end of the runway,'' he said. ``There was nothing
left. The plane's a complete loss.''
   ``The air station has ceased all flights right now,'' he added.
   The plane was from the VAQ 129 training squadron based at
Whidbey Island Naval Air Station in Washington state, Papp said.
   The Prowler is designed to be launched from a carrier and to jam
land-based enemy radar during long-range bombing missions, Papp
said. The crash was being investigated.
</TEXT>
