<FIRST>u i AM-Cyprus-Protest     07-24 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cyprus-Protest,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turkish Cypriots Release 82 Imprisoned Greek-Cypriot Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, CYPRUS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Turkish Cypriot government released
early Tuesday all 82 Greek Cypriot women who were jailed six days
ago for staging an anti-Turkish demonstration.
   Hundreds of Greek Cypriots, including President George
Vassiliou, welcomed the women at the police academy in the Greek
Cypriot sector of the divided capital.
   Sobbing with relief the freed women sang the Greek national
anthem to the cheers of the welcoming crowd.
   The women were driven to the academy in a convoy of United
Nations peace-force buses following their release from a prison in
the Turkish-occupied zone of Nicosia.
   A total of 108 Greek Cypriots _ 98 women and 10 men _ were
arrested Wednesday on the 15th anniversary of the Turkish invasion
while demonstrating in the U.N.-buffer zone dividing the east
Mediterranean island.
   They were charged with violating the border of the Turkish
Cypriot state, which is recognized only by Turkey.
   Sixteen girls, all under the age of 18, were released Sunday and
Monday. The 10 men, including Bishop Chrysostomos, another Greek
Orthodox priest, a doctor and two journalists, are still held.
   The release of the women followed mass demonstrations by Greek
Cypriots and a 5-day sit-in blocking the main entrance to the U.N.
headquarters by hundreds of women.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar on Thursday
called for the release of all of the prisoners.
   He also cricized both the Greek Cypriot demonstrators and the
Turkish Cypriot police for entering the U.N. buffer zone.
   Eleni Vrahimi, a lawyer and one of the organizers of Wednesday's
demonstration, said she and all of the other prisoners had been
``severely beaten'' by Turkish Cypriot police.
   ``The trial before a Turkish Cypriot court was a mockery and a
parody of justice,'' she said. ``There are no borders in Cyprus and
we were protesting the Turkish occupation in the yards of a Greek
Cypriot school and a church when the Turkish forces seized us.''
   Vassilou told the crowd, ``The release of the women shows that
humanity is not prepared to accept the violation of human rights.''
He expressed hope the 10 men would be freed soon.
   The conflict caused by the demonstration and arrests threatened
to wreck the 11-month-old U.N.-sponsored peace talks between
Vassiliou and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash on reunification
of the island.
   Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops invaded
and seized 40 percent of its territory. Turkey said the troops were
sent to protect the Turkish Cypriots who comprise 17 percent of the
island's population.
   Turkey launched the invasion after a short-lived coup by Greek
Cypriots seeking a union with Greece.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
