<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 2324EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Economy     07-24 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Economy,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Approves Program to Create New Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cabinet on Monday approved a proposal by
Finance Minister Shimon Peres to allocate $137.5 million for a
public works program designed to reduce the country's high
unemployment.
   The decision came a day after about 1 million civil servants,
bank employees and airport and factory workers walked off their
jobs for two hours to protest the worsening job situation.
   Labor Ministry officials said Israel's unemployment rate was 9.7
percent in May, the highest since a 1965-67 recession when the rate
reached 12.4 percent.
   Peres said funds for the public works program would come from
other areas and overall budget spending would not increase. He said
he planned to cut $30 million from the budget of the state-run
Electric Company and would trim other programs.
   ``I'm afraid of an increase in inflation and, therefore, we will
see to it that the budget will not grow,'' Peres said on Israel
television.
   He said the plan would target ``development towns'' most
affected by unemployment.
   Israel began creating development towns in the 1950s to house
Jewish immigrants, mostly from North African and Middle East
countries.
   ``The whole program stresses the development towns problems in
at least three fields: Infrastructure of roads, water systems and
schools,'' Peres said.
   Moshe Nissim, former finance minister, said the plan ``would not
really help to ease unemployment,'' and he called for a more
comprehensive economic plan.
</TEXT>
