<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   :Home Video Reviews
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Mississippi Burning'' (Orion Home Video. VHS-Beta, $79.98.
Rated R)
   
   In the summer of 1964, young men and women from around the
nation poured into Mississippi to take part in ``Freedom Summer,''
a concerted effort to register black voters in the segregated
state. One was 20-year-old Andrew Goodman, a student at Queens
College. On June 21, Goodman and two members of CORE (Congress of
Racial Equality), Michael Schwerner and James Chaney, drove to the
town of Lawndale where a black church had been burned. They never
returned.
   They were stopped for speeding near Philadelphia and jailed for
several hours on bogus charges. After being released that night,
the workers failed to call in. After an extensive search, involving
the FBI and 200 sailors, and a tip from a ``Mr. X,'' the bodies
were discovered Aug. 4 on a farm outside of Philadelphia.
   A fictionalized account of the murder of those three young
volunteers is unraveled in Alan Parker's ``Mississippi Burning.''
The movie is by no means an accurate or riveting account of that
strange and horrendous period in American history. Rather, it is a
detective story that boils down to the
   typical Hollywood good cop-bad cop treatment. It is male bonding
redux.
   Parker focuses on two FBI agents sent to Mississippi to
investigate the disappearance of the civil rights workers. Ward
(Willem Dafoe) is the upstanding, neatly suited partner who plays
things by the book. Anderson (Gene Hackman) is a redneck and a
maverick. He does things his way and has a short fuse.
   
   Their search, and Anderson's seething tensions are relentless.
Through plot twists that suspend disbelief, they discover the
bodies and peel away the facade of white Southern virtue, exposing
it as an ugly, oozing canker sore. In the meantime, Parker almost
has his audience cheering for the wonderful FBI. But the reality is
that the FBI was more a harassment to blacks and sympathetic whites
during the civil rights struggle than heroic knight. The movie also
overlooks those who were at the very helm of the movement and who
led and suffered through that summer. Blacks are mere pimples on
the landscape in Parker's thinking; they stand by and do nothing.
They have no passions, no aggressions, no thoughts.
   The strength of ``Mississippi Burning'' is not its shallow look
at segregation, but its performances, especially by Hackman. His
portrayal of Anderson is one of the best in his career. He
steamrolls through the movie with volcanic force, filling the
theater with a crackling tension and good ole boy charm. Dafoe is,
by necessity, the antithesis, and he delivers well. Taken as a
detective film, ``Mississippi Burning'' (the FBI file name for the
case), is a fine piece of entertainment, and works well on the home
screen. But don't expect a credible history lesson.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Witchery'' (Vidmark Entertainment. VHS, $79.95. No rating.)
   
   ``Witchery'' is a simply terrible film with absolutely no
redeeming virtues.
   Linda Blair, who first horrified audiences as the possessed
youngster in ``The Exorcist,'' and David Hasselhoff (TV's ``Night
Rider'') fail to save this piece of junk. Their lackluster acting,
coupled with an impossibly bad script, should cause this video to
gather dust on the store shelf.
   There is graphic violence and gore, including garroting,
crucifixion, rape and other bits of murderous mayhem. But the story
is so incredibly weak that even these excesses can't boost it to
any interesting level.
   It has the look and feel of a made-for-TV movie, and is as dull
as the worst sitcom.
   Blair plays an investigator of paranormal phenomena. She's
appears half asleep most of the time, mumbling her way through her
lines. Hasselhoff, a photographer and Blair's fiance, tries to make
the best of it with dialogue about as snappy as a grapefruit
commercial. The two have come to a New England island to take
pictures of an old hotel that resembles a witch during certain
times of the day.
   As the witch, Hildegard Knef is about the best thing going in
the movie. Michael Manches plays the most credible role as Tommy, a
child who communicates with the witch.
   _ By Chris French, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Twins'' ( MCA Home Video. VHS-Beta, $89.95. Rated PG)
   
   Not since Laurel and Hardy has such a physically contrasting
comedy team come along: Arnold Schwarzenegger and Danny DeVito.
   ``Twins'' is simply wonderful entertainment. It's silly,
improbable, irreverent.
   Schwarzenegger and DeVito play twin brothers who were separated
at birth. No joke. Seems mom was this ``exceptional'' woman who
gave her body to a secret biological experiment in creating a
superman. Something went wrong, the egg split and a runt turned up
as well.
   As they reunite, search for their mom, dodge a hitman, uncover
the truth of their origins and otherwise scheme and hustle their
way through the movie, the duo provide enough laughs to fill a
Sunday afternoon family viewing.
   DeVito continues to impress with good comedic work, both in
direction and acting. Schwarzenegger, usually a heavy (in more ways
than one), is a giggle in a lighter mood. Ivan Reitman directed
``Twins.''
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Who's Harry Crumb?'' (RCA-Columbia Home Video. VHS-Beta,
$89.95. Rated PG)
   
   ``Who's Harry Crumb?'' Don't bother to find out. You'll only
hate yourself in the morning.
   And a personal to John Candy: Fire the person who keeps giving
you all those bad scripts.
   _ By Dolores Barclay, AP Arts Editor.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
