<DOCNO> AP890724-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 2219EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Serious Adv04-06   07-24 0883</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Serious, Adv 04-06,0901</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, July 4-6 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: Get Serious</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Young Einstein'' opens Aug. 4</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You've got to take Yahoo seriously, after he
has written, directed, produced and starred in a movie being
released by a major film company.
   First of all, about his name.
   ``It's on my passport; it's been like that since I was at art
school: Yahoo Serious,'' explains the 35-year-old Australian
virtuoso who stars in ``Young Einstein.''
   ``I changed it to have an art work of a name but also make it a
laugh. It kind of fit in with the rest of the stuff I did _ the
weird hair, and weirder clothes and stuff. I had this really
ordinary name (Greg Pead) and I thought, `I can do better than
this.'
   ```Yahoo' is almost impossible to say unless you're having a
good time. `Serious,' I guess, is the director's side of me. I
dunno. It's kind of a parody on names, I suppose.''
   The other remarkable thing about Serious is the hair. It's a
brown mass that rises from his head like a bramble bush. He calls
it ``an Australian surfing haircut'' and claims it's the reason he
chose to portray Einstein _ ``he's the only historical character
with the same haircut.''
   Serious came here for his first exposure to the American media.
He may well be the biggest Australian import since Paul Hogan. His
film, ``Young Einstein,'' has broken records of ``Rambo,'' ``Star
Wars'' and the like in his home country. Warner Bros. is hoping,
not without some nervousness, that Serious will catch on here.
   It's hard to describe ``Young Einstein.'' You might call it a
combination of rock music, silent-screen slapstick and bogus
history. Yahoo plays Albert Einstein at the age of 26, when he
discovered both relativity and rock 'n' roll. All this happens in
Australia, you see.
   The inspiration for ``Young Einstein'' came during a trip down
the Amazon River. He relates it with such sincerity that you want
to believe him.
   ``I crossed the Andes with a mate, and we ended up on the border
of Peru and Brazil and I think Colombia. We were going to take a
boat down the Amazon. I don't think they had Australians aboard
before because we drank them out of beer in two days.
   ``We put in at a little village. The Brazilian native who was
carrying the beer on board wore a T-shirt with a picture of Albert
Einstein sticking his tongue out. Where he got the T-shirt in the
middle of the Amazon jungle, I don't know. That was the
inspiration: The greatest mind of the 20th Century doing something
so irreverent and childlike at the age of 72. I thought, wow, we've
got the basis for a film here.''
   Serious had dabbled in film before, making documentaries that
somehow came out as comedies. How to sell a feature? He decided to
do it by degrees. He sold his car, bought some film, borrowed a
camera, gathered a cast and crew and began shooting. When he ran
out of money, he borrowed an editing machine, put together what he
had filmed and sought financing.
   Amazingly, he found backing from some investors, the Australian
Film Commission, an Australian distributor _ and Warner Bros. He
was able to finish ``Young Einstein'' the way he wanted, ``with a
cast of thousands and a huge musical score and eight rock songs.''
   He was born in the Hunter Valley in New South Wales. He quit
school to work as a tire fitter so he could afford to attend art
school. It became apparent early on that he had to express himself
not with brush and paint, but with the magic of comedy.
   ``I was fed by two of the major cultures, besides having the
indigenous, sardonic, self-effacing Australian humor,'' he
recalled. ``The Monty Python influence came on TV from England. At
the same time there were all the wonderful '60s situation comedies
from here, like `Green Acres,' `The Addams Family,' `Get Smart' and
all the others. Bugs Bunny was also a huge influence.
   ``At the same time, I loved epic films, especially David Lean's.
`Lawrence of Arabia' was a huge influence on me. I loved the idea
of putting comedy in a film of epic proportions. I had no idea it
was going to be a big hit, that's all.''
   Yahoo Serious is already a notable in Australia, and he'll
certainly be the same here, with his electrocuted hair and his
uniform of flowery Hawaiian shirt and floppy white shorts. The
recognition doesn't bother him: ``I usually get `G'dy, Yahoo,'
`G'dy, Yahoo,' that sort of stuff. Like I say, the word Yahoo makes
people feel good.''
   Can we expect ``Young Einstein II''?
   ``Sequels are good when they are a small part of what is being
made,'' he said. ``When they're the bulk of what's being made, I
think it's self-defeating. Maybe when I'm a grey-haired old guy and
we've forgotten about sequels, maybe we'll see `Einstein Goes to
Princeton' or something like that. But there won't be a sequel in
the foreseeable future.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Aug 4-6</NOTE>
