<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Nissman Adv04-06   07-24 0800</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Nissman, Adv 04-06,0839</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug 4-6 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: In Love With a 20th-Century Modern</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's easy to pick out Barbara Nissman in a crowd
of pianists: She's the one who's known for playing Sergei Prokofiev
and Alberto Ginastera.
   ``What a joy to find composers in this century one can be
passionate about!'' she says. ``Prokofiev is a 20th-century modern
continuing the Romantic tradition. I believe the music cries out to
be played that way.''
   Nissman, whose parents were born in the Soviet Union, studied
Russian language and literature at the University of Michigan, as
well as music. Ginastera visited the campus in the late 1960s when
she was rehearsing his piano concerto and liked the way she played
it. They kept in touch and, during the 15 years she pursued her
career in Europe, she often played his music. The composer
dedicated his ``Third Piano Sonata'' to her.
   ``I play all three. They're wonderful. I think the first is his
masterpiece. My favorite of his works is `Argentine Dances,' which
he wrote for solo piano when he was 18,'' Nissman said.
   ``His widow, who's a cellist, and I are going to record the
cello concerto he wrote for her. It never has been recorded. I
think he would have been pleased.''
   Nissman recorded all nine Prokofiev piano sonatas for Newport
Classic, distributed on cassettes and compact discs by MCA. Volume
2 was released in July with Volume 3 set for August.
   Last season she played all nine sonatas in three concerts at New
York's Alice Tully Hall, the first time that has been done in one
season. She repeated it at Wigmore Hall in London. Next season
she'll do the cycle in the Netherlands and other American cities.
   ``There are plans for me to do the cycle in Russia _ an American
of Russian origin going to play Russian music for Russians,'' said
Nissman, who has been invited by the Central State Archives in
Moscow to go through Prokofiev's piano sketches.
   ``They've done it with his symphonies, operas and ballets. Maybe
I can find some manuscripts that haven't been discovered.''
   Asked in a recent interview what led her to play the Prokofiev
cycle, she said, ``Just following my nose, exploring music that is
not often played in concert. I had played several of the sonatas
with the BBC Symphony. I decided to look at the ones I didn't know.
I wasn't disappointed at all.
   ``I also found a fragment of a 10th sonata and a second version
of the fifth,'' she said. ``I had the first page of the fragment
and wrote the archives in Moscow to see if there was a second page.
It arrived an hour before the premiere was to be given and I
sight-read it at the concert.
   ``It transformed my conception of the first page. He went in a
completely different direction. It was very exciting to have that,
to realize that at the end of his life he was going back to the
lyrical style of the ninth sonata.''
   That fragment of the 10th sonata was the last thing Prokofiev
wrote before he died in 1953. ``It ends in the middle of a measure.
He had a fall, but kept on writing on his deathbed.''
   Nissman will make a Liszt recording this fall. ``I can't give up
Liszt. He's one of my favorites,'' she says. ``They come from the
same tradition. They all really knew and respected the piano and
delighted in virtuosity, which is very appealing to the public and
to a pianist.
   ``Prokofiev built on tradition with his own personality. That's
the essence of what modern means _ being his own man yet building
upon a foundation, using those elements to make it his own and have
something personal to say.
   ``People came to the recitals resisting Prokofiev,'' she said.
``The preconception is dissonance, that the music should be played
without emotion, with a hard, dry, brittle sound. They were amazed
at the lyricism and emotional content and what they felt when they
were listening to the music.
   ``There is so much there. In his simplicity, Prokofiev is truly
profound. I would say the essence of his music is the wonderful
simplicity. He communicates directly. That's what one wants from
any composer, to touch the soul.''
   Nissman recalled that when she was a child and heard ``Peter and
the Wolf,'' she was delighted with the melodies.
   ``And his piano music abounds with wonderful melodies. The fifth
sonata is the weakest because of the lack of melody,'' she said.
   ``But the weakest for Prokofiev is still pretty darn good.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Aug 4-6</NOTE>
