<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--LoveandRockets Adv04-06   07-24 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Love and Rockets, Adv 04-06,0723</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv04</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv05</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug 4-6 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: Eclectic English Band Finds Mainstream Acceptance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a summer dominated by ``classic rock'' radio,
and concerts by reformed 1970s supergroups, Love and Rockets has
managed to take its intriguing mix of dreamy mood music and
jackhammer metal into the Top 20.
   While the members of the British trio express no love for oldies
stations or the ubiquitous reunion tours, don't count them among
the bands complaining that a newer band can't make it in 1989.
   The band, currently on tour in support of its fourth album,
``Love and Rockets,'' has found a good outlet for its music on
college radio. And concert crowds, which include fans of Love and
Rockets' predecessor, the early '80s group Bauhaus, have been
growing on the strength of the band's first U.S. hit single, ``So
Alive.''
   ``We're over the moon, we are,'' said Daniel Ash of the band's
current success.
   Ash plays bass, guitar, and saxophone and sings about half the
band's songs. Rounding out Love and Rockets are the brother team of
David J. on guitar, bass, harmonica and vocals, and drummer Kevin
Haskins.
   David J. said each of the band's U.S. tours has found audiences
bigger and more knowledgeable of the group's work.
   ``The familiarity grows every time we come back. The songs are
more recognizable to a greater part of the audience,'' he said.
``This is the most definitive record we've done so far. That's why
we called it simply `Love and Rockets.'''
   Defining the group's sound is an elusive task, as Love and
Rockets works in a musical universe that has room for the
latter-day psychedelia of ``The Teardrop Collector,'' as well as
the noise explosion of ``No Big Deal.''
   It's almost an axiom that the rise in popularity of ``classic
rock'' radio, with its emphasis on '70s-style hard rock, has made
it difficult for less established groups to get airplay or
attention. That phenomenon has been accompanied this summer by
reunion tours by such veteran acts as The Who, the Doobie Brothers
and the Allman Brothers Band.
   But Ash said that despite the attention to older rock music, in
some ways the band has had better access to the airwaves here than
back home in England. Being heard on college radio has paved the
way to increased mainstream acceptance, he said.
   ``I think the college radio situation in the U.S.A. is
excellent; it's a great idea,'' Ash said. ``With the college
stations in America, they love playing their music and there isn't
any commercial consideration. They play what they actually like.''
   The ideal radio station, Ash said, would play new records and
also some good old music. ``Why not play something that was
recorded in 1964, and then something that was recorded last
Tuesday?'' he said.
   Ash said he felt strongly that rock 'n' roll groups have a
limited life span. He said he was opposed to the current wave of
tours by veteran rockers.
   ``The Who shouldn't exist. It's stupid,'' Ash said. ``It's like
a contradiction of what they were originally about. It's nonsense,
it's a rip-off.
   ``They're too old to do that sort of music. When you sing songs
like `My Generation' and see guys in their mid-40s ... it's
hilarious, it's wrong,'' Ash said. ``When you're involved in
something like contemporary music, it's real important to realize
when you look ridiculous.''
   He said Love and Rockets is just now hitting its prime.
   ``We just work on whatever feels right at the time,'' he said.
``We've grown close as a group. We can be open enough to know when
somebody's doing something wrong.''
   With its popularity growing, the band is recording some of its
current tour dates for a possible live album. Also in the works is
a home video compilation and mini-album of songs recorded around
the time of ``Love and Rockets'' but which did not fit in with the
sound of that album.
   David J. described the mini-album as ``a cross between the
Andrews Sisters, Glenn Miller and Captain Beefheart.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Aug 4-6</NOTE>
