<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--Life'sPrime:SunSense Adv27   07-24 0771</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Life's Prime: Sun Sense, Adv 27,0788</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, July 27, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Retransmitting to fix keyword line</HEAD>
<HEAD>Old or Young: Beware the Summer Sun</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   T. Franklin Williams, a geriatrics physician, is
director of the National Institute on Aging, one of the 13
institutes that comprise the National Institutes of Health of the
Department of Health and Human Services.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By Dr. T. Franklin Williams</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The message today is simple: BEWARE THE
SUMMER SUN!
   Too many people, especially older people, become needlessly ill
because they fail to recognize the potential dangers of the sun and
its heat. However, the two great dangers, heatstroke and skin
cancer, are largely preventable.
   Symptoms of heatstroke occur almost instantly and can be
immediately fatal, while skin cancer develops years after exposure
to the sun's rays.
   If you must be exposed to the heat, drink plenty of water or
fruit and vegetable juice, even if you aren't thirsty. Avoid
alcohol and caffeine. Dress in light-weight, light-colored, loose
clothes. Limit activity in the hottest part of the day and keep
meals simple and light. If they are available, use air conditioners
liberally. Trips to cool places are good alternatives.
   If you are a relative, friend, or neighbor of a person who is
unable to get around you may want to offer transportation.
   Older people are especially vulnerable to heat-related
illnesses. Changes in the body that may affect ability to cope with
heat include inefficient sweat glands, poor circulation and changes
in the skin. Also, some older people have illnesses that cause
weakness or fever which, in turn, affect their ability to cope with
heat. Heart, lung, and kidney diseases are good examples.
   Diseases requiring special diets also may make a person more
vulnerable to heatstroke. People with high blood pressure, for
example, reduce the amount of salt in their diets. Yet this
reduction may increase the risk of heat stress. (A word of caution
_ salt should not be increased nor salt supplements taken without
consent from a physician.)
   Medications like diuretics, sedatives, tranquilizers and certain
heart and blood-pressure drugs may contribute to a body's inability
to regulate internal temperature. But never stop medication or
change a recommended diet without consulting a doctor. Unusually
heavy or underweight people also are at risk, as are those who
drink alcoholic beverages regularly.
   Anyone suspected of suffering a heat-related illness should
receive attention. Victims of heatstroke exhibit a body temperature
of 104 degrees or higher. The pulse may be rapid. Other symptoms
include flushed skin, a faint feeling, confused and bizarre
behavior and combativeness. These symptoms require immediate
emergency medical assistance.
   Heat fatigue and heat exhaustion are milder forms of heat
stress. Should you suspect either illness look for giddiness,
nausea, profuse sweating, and a cold and clammy feeling and take
steps to prevent the condition from worsening.
   First, and perhaps most obvious, the person needs to get out of
the sun and into a cool, preferably air-conditioned place.
Encourage sponging off with cool water or taking a cool bath or
shower and non-alcoholic, non-caffeinated drink.
   Another serious danger associated with the sun and aging is skin
cancer.
   Whether you are 15 or 50 your skin is accumulating sun damage,
including wrinkling, various growths and skin cancers and change in
texture. By following some easy sun-safety tips many skin cancers
can be prevented.
   Don't sunbathe too long. Try to limit exposure between 10 a.m.
and 3 p.m. and get used to the sun gradually. Wear a hat,
long-sleeved shirt, and W-rated (ultraviolet) sunglasses. Use
sunscreens liberally and apply them at least one hour before going
out. Reapply after swimming or sweating. Sunscreens are effective
at SPF (sun protection factor) 15.
   Prolonged exposure to the sun can cause skin cancer. The most
common forms are basal cell carcinoma, squamous cell carcinoma and
malignant melanoma.
   Basal cell carcinomas are the most common and rarely harmful to
vital organs. Squamous cell carcinomas are less common but are
potentially harmful because they can grow quickly and spread to
other organs. Malignant melanomas often look like dark, irregular
moles. They can be deadly.
   If you suspect skin cancer see a doctor. Warning signs include a
new mole-type spot or changes in color, size, shape or texture of
an existing one. With early detection and prompt treatment, many
skin cancers can be cured. Even if you have had a benign cancer you
must guard against the dangers of the sun.
   With good, sound judgment and a knowledge of preventive measures
the hot summer months can be safe and fun for everyone.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890724-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1229EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--Gardening Adv27   07-24 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--Gardening, Adv 27,0774</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, July 27, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Plants Don't Care Who You Are; Hard Work Is All That Counts</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: George Bria retired from the AP in 1981 after 40
years that included coverage of World War II from Italy.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BRIA</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POUND RIDGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plants don't care how old you are. A
rose blushes as sweetly for the 80-year-old gardener as for one 50
years younger. With age, a tennis serve loses its zing and a golf
drive its distance, but your daffodils will dance in the wind as
sprightly as ever.
   Augusta Carter took to gardening before she was 10, helping her
grandmother in the red soil of a Georgia vegetable patch.
   ``I was the only one of the grandchildren she would let in the
garden because I remembered the names of things. I was alway asking
questions. I wanted to know why things grew the way they did.''
   Now 81 and ailing, Augusta still finds the garden a main
pleasure in life. People in Pound Ridge, a country town 50 miles
north of Manhattan, have long thought of Augusta and her lawyer
husband, Ray, 82, as ``Mr. and Mrs. Garden.''
   Most every town has elderly couples like them, who, seeking
beauty and flavor, have put a lifetime into raising flowers and
vegetables with skill and dedication. And many newly retired
seniors are looking to the garden to fill the leisure hours.
   But Augusta warns that a gardener ``has to get grimy and dirty
and enjoy what comes out of real work. If you're one of those
people who are afraid to get your fingernails soiled or broken and
you don't want to put on dirty old jeans and old sneakers and get
out and dig, you're not really a gardener.''
   Ailments keep her from doing as much now. She's ``concentrating
more and more on flowers and herbs.'' But, leaning on her stick,
Augusta helps out at every event put on by the Garden Club, of
which she was once president. She supervises the care of the
library grounds.
   But mostly she likes to look at her perennials renewing
themselves in the spring, like the lavender clematis that has
showed 300 blooms.
   In his youth in Florida, Ray worked as an attorney for the War
Department, but briefly tended a Victory Garden in Mamaroneck, a
suburb of New York City. Augusta remembers his vegetables were so
good that ``he was robbed often; people would come in the middle of
the night and take things.''
   After the war, the Carters moved to a 1737 house on acreage in
Pound Ridge, which since has become a National Landmark.
   Even as Ray commuted daily by train to his law firm in
Manhattan, he became more and more involved in his garden. ``I'd
get up at 4:30 and get my gardening done then. Otherwise I wouldn't
keep abreast of it. There wasn't enough time.''
   Before leaving for his train, Ray would pick a flower for his
buttonhole, and he became known to fellow commuters as the man who
always wore a flower.
   For years now the Carters have been going back South in the
winter to a house, and another garden, in the Florida Keys and
they'll define for you expertly the nuances of southern and
northern horticulture.
   Ray has also been ailing lately and has cut his outdoor work
sharply. But he likes to take you around his Pound Ridge grounds
and point out interesting plants, like his off-season Egyptian
onions. In the vegetable patch, he shows how yearly mulching with
autumn leaves has enriched the soil to a deep, dark brown. His
daughter, Quincy, helped put in the tomatoes this year.
   Keeping up the family tradition, Quincy has also headed the
Garden Club.
   Talking with the Carters in their comfortable sitting room, you
get a sense of the soul of the garden. Augusta appreciates but
doesn't agree with an old saying that people like to garden
``because the plants don't talk back.''
   She thinks plants ``have a lot to say without talking,'' that
they'll let you know by sign language if they need more sun or rain
or a richer soil. She also says, ``It's the care you give a rose
that brings out the better rose.''
   Any wisdom she'd pass on?
   ``You don't have a garden just for yourself. You have it to
share. But you have to be willing to do the work.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890724-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1229EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-PRI--NewIdeas Adv27   07-24 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-PRI--New Ideas, Adv 27,0693</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Thursday, July 27, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mom-and-Pop Research Company Builds A Better Safety Cap </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM LACEKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kids don't think like grownups.
   With that simple premise and a $50,000 grant from the National
Institutes of Health, a mom-and-pop research company has come up
with a child-proof cap it hopes will make life easier for older
Americans.
   The caps designed by Bob and Mary Hunter's Yellowstone
Environmental Science don't rely on an adult's strength or
dexterity. Instead, they require two cognitive skills that children
aged 3 to 5 don't have: Read the directions, then do some things in
a specified sequence, such as push, twist, THEN pull.
   The designs ``were similar to simple combination locks,'' said
Mary Hunter.
   The Hunters recruited 26 adults, aged 60 to 75, from the Bozeman
Senior Center, and 20 3- to 5-year-olds from the Child Development
Center, a preschool associated with Montana State University, to
test three cap designs.
   ``It was a much smaller group than you'd need to come to
definite conclusions, but two of the designs were virtually
child-proof. No children opened them. One child almost 5{ opened
one of the designs,'' Mrs. Hunter said.
   The children seemed familiar with the now-commonplace safety
caps, but were thwarted by the sequence requirements, she said.
Ninety percent of the adults opened the caps and 80 percent rated
them easy or very easy to use.
   A recent Gallup Poll of older Americans found that the No. 1
problem of daily life was opening medicine, the Hunters said.
Safety packaging is optional on prescription drugs, and many older
people, especially arthritics, refuse it.
   One result, said Bob Hunter, is that one of every six children
poisoned by a prescription medicine each year has taken a
grandparent's medication.
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission is considering a staff
proposal to test packaging for medicines and toxic household
chemicals on elderly people as well as the children it is meant to
protect. People over 65 receive 25 percent of all prescriptions,
but testing uses only 18- to 45-year-olds, Hunter said.
   Owens-Illinois, a $3 billion-a-year packaging manufacturer, has
asked to look at the Hunters' findings.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Computerized Phone Program to Monitor Elderly Living Alone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN PACENTI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A computer that makes up to 100 phone calls an
hour can alleviate one of the fears of elderly people living alone
_ being undiscovered for days after being stricken suddenly at home
by illness.
   ``There is a large percentage of elderly that live alone with a
pre-existing medical conditions and nobody to check on them,''
Youngtown Police Chief Mike Branham said recently, announcing plans
to install the system.
   The service _ R.U.O.K., coined by developer Bruce Johnson for
``Are you OK?'' _ is being installed in the Youngtown, Sun City and
Sun City West suburbs of Phoenix. R.U.O.K. was first installed in
Osage, Iowa, in March 1988 and has been started in about 15 cities,
including in Gulfport, Miss., in July.
   ``It's a real simple system,'' Branham said. ``A computer modem
hooks to a telephone and calls the elderly person. If they don't
answer the phone, the computer re-logs the number and recalls it
eight minutes later.''
   If there is no answer, a computer sends a printout of the
person's name and condition to a police dispatcher, who will send
an officer. The computer dials up to 100 phones an hour and should
be able to serve about 500 people.
   A person may have the computer call any number of times in a
day, Branham said. ``Everyone will get at least one call every 24
hours.''
   Johnson, who attended a news conference kicking off the Gulfport
system, ``If a person can answer the phone, we assume he's OK
enough to call for help. This program is aimed at those who can't
answer.''
   The cost varies. Phoenix-area civic groups raised $7,000 to
start R.U.O.K.; Gulfport police came up with $3,600 for theirs.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for July 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
