<FIRST>r f BC-BorgBusiness     07-24 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Borg Business,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bjorn Borg's Business Nearly Bust, Reports Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The business empire of Bjorn Borg is
being liquidated and could go bankrupt because the retired tennis
star has refused a bid for new working capital, media reports said
Monday.
   Bjorn Borg Enterprises was hit by a cash crisis after Borg
refused a $4.6 million infusion to cover the expansion in Bjorn
Borg Design Group, a fragrance and fashion company, the newspaper
Aftonbladet and the nationa news agency TT said.
   The financing plan was offered by Swedish financier Peter
Gyllenhammar and would have allowed Borg to remain the majority
owner, the reports said. Further details of the plan were not
disclosed.
   The Bjorn Borg company office in Stockholm did not answer the
telephone Monday. Aftonbladet quoted Borg as saying he would not
comment.
   Business partners quoted by Aftonbladet and by TT said Borg had
given ``no explanation'' for his decision to refuse the financing
plan at a board meeting Thursday.
   Aftonbladet and TT said the company board resigned, including
Hakan Frisinger, a former managing director of automaker Volvo AB.
   Borg's partner Lars Skarke, who owns a 25 percent share in the
group, told TT one reason for needing new working capital was brisk
sales. Stig Sjoholm, a lawyer and vice president of Bjorn Borg
Design group, told Aftonbladet turnover had quadrupled in the past
year.
   ``It is possible our expansion has been too rapid on certain
points,'' he said.
   The Monte Carlo-based Bjorn Borg Enterprises owned companies
which designed and marketed a line of quality fashions and
fragrances, and was involved in Swedish real estate.
   Borg, 33, founded his empire on the winnings of a 10-year
professional tennis career, including an unmatched five consecutive
championships at Wimbledon, from 1976 through 1980, and six French
Open crowns.
   By the time he retired from the circuit in 1983, he was
estimated to have amassed $75 million in prizes and endorsements.
He declared his personal wealth in his 1986 tax return as nearly $8
million.
</TEXT>
