<FIRST>u f PM-Honeywell 2ndLd-Writethru f0048 07-24 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honeywell, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0048,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honeywell Announces Sweeping Plan To Enhance Shareholder Value</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs with one graf to UPDATE with stock price.
Picks up 7th graf pvs, Renier said ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honeywell Inc., the subject of intense
takeover speculation for the past two weeks, today announced a
major restructuring program that includes reducing its weapons
business and cutting 4,000 jobs.
   The company said it also planned to repurchase up to 10 million
shares of its common stock on the open market and to sell a
``substantial portion'' of its 50 percent stake in
Yamatake-Honeywell, a Japanese controls maker. Analysts have valued
that holding at nearly $1 billion.
   The sweeping program will result in a 65-cent increase in the
Honeywell's fourth-quarter dividend, to $2.75 a share, and could
include a special cash dividend, said Chairman James J. Renier.
   Renier said he expected the restructuring to improve operating
profits by about $150 million over the next 18 months.
   Honeywell is the leading manufacturer of torpedoes for the U.S.
Navy and also supplies small, medium and large ammunition to the
U.S. Army, Tunheim said.
   Wall Street greeted today's announcement with open arms.
Honeywell jumped $3.37{ to $88.87{ in active late-morning trading
on the New York Stock Exchange, following a delayed opening.
   Renier said the reduction of Honeywell's weapons business is
part of a strategy begun in 1988 to ``concentrate on core controls
businesses that principally serve commercial markets as well as the
market for military and space controls.''
   The reduction will ``proceed over time in a responsible manner
that recognizes the U.S. government's interest in these businesses
so as not to adversely affect national security interests, our
government program obligations, or the value of these businesses to
Honeywell shareholders,'' Renier said.
   The weapons business accounts for about 20 percent of
Honeywell's revenue.
   Kathy Tunheim, a company spokeswoman, would not say whether a
sale of the business is one of the options being considered.
   However, Tunheim said negotiations to sell the company's stake
in Yamatake-Honeywell, which is listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange,
will begin within a few days. She would not identify potential
buyers. Japanese investors currently own half of the company, she
said.
   Honeywell's restructuring program will include the elimination
of 4,000 jobs worldwide over the next 18 months, including 300
corporate staff positions targeted in a previous announcement.
   Honeywell currently employs about 78,000 workers. Many of the
job cuts will be made through attrition, but layoffs will be
necessary, Tunheim said. The company had announced last month that
it would lay off 300 employees.
   Today's restructuring announcement follows speculation that
Honeywell is a takeover target. Honeywell's stock price has risen
sharply in the last two weeks following published reports that
General Electric Co. was considering acquiring the company.
   The takeover rumors began after the company announced that it
lost $435 million in fiscal 1988.
   Honeywell's second-quarter profit jumped to $74.8 million, or
$1.73 a share, from $31.6 million, or 75 cents a share, in 1988.
   John McManus, a securities analyst with Thomson McKinnon
Securities Inc. in New York, said today's announcement could deter
a takeover attempt, although it won't guarantee independence for
Honeywell.
   ``They are trying to basically boost the stock price to make it
more difficult for someone to take them over,'' McManus said. ``It
will also alleviate some of the large shareholders who have been
pounding on the door. They are doing the things they have to do to
deter a takeover.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
