Board of Trade.
   Analysts predicted lower soybean prices today because of the
rains, but the drop in early trading that exceeded 7 cents in some
contracts was a surprise, said Jerry Gidel of LIT America Inc.
   Corn prices were depressed by rumors that the Soviet Union would
enter the market. But the Soviets have yet to make an offer.
   The near completion of the wheat harvest and the purchase last
week by Egypt of 200,000 metric tons of wheat from European growers
pushed wheat futures lower.
   In early trading, wheat was 1} cents to 2\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.93} a bushel; corn was 2}
cents to 3{ cents lower with September at $2.36} a bushel; oats
were 3\ cents to 3{ cents lower with September at $1.46{ a bushel;
soybeans were 8} cents to 16 cents lower with August at $6.65 a
bushel.
   Meat and pork futures were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .03 cent to .43 cent higher with August at
72.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .13 cent to .58 cent higher
with August at 84.15 cents a pound; live hogs were .03 cent to .33
cent higher with August at 45.92 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .13 cent lower to .10 cent higher with July at 30.05 cents a
pound.
   Meat prices settled mixed and pork prices were lower in Friday
trading.
