<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-SmithKline     07-24 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-SmithKline,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quarterly Earnings Up 10 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   SmithKline Beckman Corp., the
pharmaceuticals manufacturer, said Monday its second-quarter
earnings rose 20 percent over the same period last year.
   SmithKline Beckman said net income for the quarter was $118.6
million, or 94 cents a share, compared with $98.7 million, or 79
cents a share in the second quarter of 1988.
   The company said sales rose 10 percent to $1.26 billion from
$1.14 billion in the same 1988 quarter. Sales in its clinical
laboratory services, consumer health care and eye and skin care
divisions showed the largest increases.
   The stronger U.S. dollar compared to other currencies undercut
total corporate sales by $31 million for the second quarter, the
company said.
   For the first six months of 1989, Smithkline Beckman said
earnings dropped 6 percent to $248.8 million, or $1.99 a share,
from $265.3 million, or $2.13 a share, in the first half of 1988.
   SmithKline Beckman shareholders are to vote Wednesday on a
proposal to merge with Beecham Group to form SmithKline Beecham. As
part of the merger, Beckman Instruments will be spun off as an
independent company.
   Beckman, a supplier of laboratory instruments and consumer
products for health care, became partially public in 1988.
Currently, 84 percent of Beckman shares are held by SmithKline
Beckman Corp.
   Those shares are to be redistributed as part of the
recapitalization of SmithKline Beckman if approved at Wednesday's
shareholders meeting.
   Quarterly earnings for Beckman, as reported both in Philadelphia
and at Beckman Instruments headquarters in Fullerton, Calif., were
$11.4 million, or 40 cents per share, down from $12.1 million or 42
cents per share last year.
   Beckman sales were $200.5 million, up 3 percent from $194.7
million in the second quarter of 1988.
</TEXT>
