<HEAD>Aerospace Company Profit Up 10 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin Marietta Corp. said Monday its
second-quarter earnings rose 10 percent over last year, mainly due
to increased production of the Titan IV rocket.
   The company said net income increased to $86.9 million, or $1.64
a share, from $81.4 million, or $1.53 a share, in the same period
last year.
   Second-quarter sales totaled $1.43 billion, down from $1.44
billion in the 1988 quarter.
   Earnings for the first half of 1989 were $146 million, or $2.76
a share, on sales of $2.75 billion. That compared to a profit of
$132 million, or $2.49 a share, on sales of $2.74 billion in the
first six months of 1988.
   Norman R. Augustine, Martin Marietta's chairman and chief
executive officer, attributed the strong second quarter to
increased production of the Titan IV launch rocket, which had its
first successful flight in June.
