<SECOND>BC-Sears Tower,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Canadian Developer To Buy Tower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian developer appears close to buying the
Sears Tower in a package worth more than $1 billion that could
change the name of the world's tallest building, according to a
published report Monday.
   Crain's Chicago Business reported that Toronto-based Olympia &amp;
York Developments Ltd. wants to buy the 110-story building and sign
British-based publisher Maxwell Communications Corp. as its anchor
tenant.
   ``We have no comment at all,'' Sears spokesman Douglas
Fairweather said. ``That's speculation and we're not commenting on
speculation.''
   Sears' Merchandise Group is currently the tower's anchor tenant,
but Sears is selling the building in a bid to streamline operations.
   The weekly newspaper quoted sources saying the sale could come
within two weeks and force owner Sears, Roebuck and Co. to
relinquish the right to keep its name on the 1,707-foot-high
building.
   According to earlier reports, Sears had insisted the buyer
retain the name of the landmark.
