<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Sharply Lower Due to Favorable Growing Conditions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed lower
Monday on the Chicago Board of Trade as rain and moderate
temperatures in large areas of the U.S. growing region weighed
heavily on the market.
   ``The market opened very weak'' and continued that way
throughout the day,'' said Dale Gustafson, an analyst for Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   ``The favorable growing conditions for this week, with a little
less warm temperatures than predicted, added to the bearish
sentiment,'' Gustafson said.
   He noted that the weakness in soybean and corn prices spilled
over into the wheat pit. Wheat prices also were pressured by the
good pace of the harvest.
   ``Disappointment in the export side of the market also affected
prices,'' Gustafson said.
   At the close, wheat was 6 cents to 7\ cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.88{ a bushel; corn was 6
cents to 9{ cents lower with September at $2.30 a bushel; oats were
5 cents to 7 cents lower with September at $1.43 a bushel; soybeans
were 12\ cents to 23{ cents lower with August at $6.61{ a bushel.
