<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Media     07-24 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Media,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capital Cities-ABC, Reuters, Houghton Mifflin Earnings Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Capital Cities-ABC Inc. said Monday its second-quarter earnings
rose 23.1 percent, including a double-digit increase in operating
income from broadcasting despite a flat performance by its ABC
Television Network.
   Another media concern, Reuters Holdings PLC, said its profit
jumped 34.5 percent in the first six months of the year as it
continued a cost-cutting effort begun after the October 1987 stock
market crash.
   The book publisher Houghton Mifflin Co. said its profit rose 10
percent for the second quarter on a 16 percent revenue increase.
   Capital Cities-ABC, which also has interests in the ESPN cable
network and in book, newspaper and specialty publishing, said it
earned $140.2 million, or $7.83 per share, in the three months
ended July 2 compared with $113.9 million, or $6.78 per share, a
year earlier.
   Revenue rose 6 percent to $1.23 billion in the quarter from
$1.16 billion a year earlier.
   Operating income for the New York-based communications company
rose 8 percent to $264.5 million in the quarter, including a 10
percent increase in broadcasting, 3 percent in publishing and gains
in newspapers, offsetting declines in the specialized publications.
   The ABC Television Networ had no increase in its operating
earnings as increased costs associated with coverage of major news
events and the telelcast of the mini-series ``War &amp; Remembrance''
offset revenue increases.
   In addition to the TV network, Capital Cities-ABC owns eight
television stations, six radio networks and 21 radio stations.
   Earnings in the latest quarter also benefitted from $27.1
million in interest income, up from $7.9 million for the same
period a year ago.
   For the first six months, Capital Cities-ABC had net income of
$222.9 million, or $12.40 a share, up 21 percent from $184.2
million, or $10.93 a share, a year earlier.
   Six-month revenue slipped 4.1 percent to $2.35 billion from
$2.45 billion a year earlier, reflecting the inclusion of revenue
from the Winter Olympics coverage in 1988.
   In London, Reuters said its profit came to 85.3 million pounds,
or $132.2 million. The per share increase was 20.6 pence, or 32
cents. The figures compared with 63.4 million pounds, or 15.1 pence
a share, in the same period a year earlier.
   Revenue for the half rose 16.3 percent to 548.3 million pounds,
or $849.9 million, from 471.4 million pounds a year earlier.
   As a London-based company, Reuters is not required to report
quarterly results.
   Glen Renfrew, managing director and chief executive of Reuters,
said, ``Reuters' profit growth accelerated in the first half of
1989.''
   He said the company's core products ``maintained their strong
progress despite continued problems in the financial markets.
Substantial improvements were achieved in operating and profit
margins.''
   At the same time, he said cost-cutting steps taken last year
held down the increase in several major categories of discretionary
costs.
   Reuters operates a news service and a number of information
services used by traders and businesses.
   Boston-based Houghton Mifflin said its profit rose to $10.5
million, or 74 cents a share, in the three months ended June 30
compared with $9.6 million, or 67 cents a share, a year earlier.
   Revenue for the quarter rose to $110.4 million from $95.1
million last year.
   Educational publishing sales rose 21 percent in the quarter, led
by sales gains in the school and college divisions. General
publishing sales slipped 9 percent, reflecting lower trade and
reference book sales in comparison with unusually strong sales a
year earlier.
   For the first six months of the year, Houghton Mifflin earned
$749,000, or 5 cents a share, in contrast to a loss of $15,000 for
the period last year.
   Six-month revenue rose 14.6 percent to $154 million from $134.4
million.
</TEXT>
