<DOCNO> AP890724-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1915EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-Banks     07-24 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Banks,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bankers Trust Reports Flat Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bankers Trust New York Corp. reported nearly flat second-quarter
earnings Monday, reflecting an increase in the banking company's
provision for credit losses and higher non-interest expenses.
   Net income for the three months ended June 30 totaled $174.6
million, or $2.14 a share, compared with earnings of $174.1
million, or $2.18 per share, the same time last year.
   For the first six months of this year, Bankers Trust netted
$338.9 million, or $4.16 a share, up 13 percent from $300.1
million, or $3.79 a share, in 1988.
   Chairman Charles S. Sanford Jr. said the company benefited from
a 15 percent increase in non-interest revenue, to $531.2 million,
primarily through trading activities. But he said those factors
were offset mainly by an increase in Bankers Trust's credit-loss
provision and non-interest expenses.
   The provision for credit losses for the second quarter totaled
$65 million, compared with $5 million in last year's quarter. The
provision included $25 million for refinancing the debt of Third
World countries.
   For the year, Bankers Trust's allowance for credit losses was
$1.306 billion, up slightly from $1.305 billion in 1988.
   Net charge-offs of refinancing the debt of developing countries
were $55 million in the second quarter, including $42 million of
Bankers Trust's non-performing medium- and long-term loans to
Argentina, the company said.
   Total non-interest expenses for the second quarter totaled
$444.1 million, up 8 percent over a year ago.
</TEXT>
