<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Unisys     07-24 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Unisys,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profits Drop To A Third Of Last Year's Net At Unisys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLUE BELL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp.'s earnings fell 67 percent in
the latest quarter in spite of an 8 percent increase in revenue,
the computer and defense contracting company said.
   Unisys Chairman W. Michael Blumenthal attributed the sharp
earnings drop to the expense of cutting inventories, pricing
pressures from competitors, and the temporary suspension of its
defense business by the Pentagon. Also, the rise in the dollar
decreased the dollar value of sales made in foreign currencies.
   Net income was $53.6 million, or 17 cents a share, on revenue of
$2.57 billion, for the April-to-June period, compared to $162.3
million, or 78 cents a share assuming full dilution, in the similar
1988 period. Revenue grew to $2.57 billion from $2.39 billion a
year earlier.
   For the first half of this year, Unisys recorded a loss of $25.1
million in contrast to a profit of $311.6 million, or $1.60 a share
assuming full dilution, in the year-earlier period. Revenue for the
first six months this year was $4.78 billion, up narrowly from
$4.76 billion in 1988.
   Three former units of Sperry Corp. were temporarily suspended
from bidding on Navy contracts from March 15 through June 23, 1989.
   The suspension stemmed from a federal investigation into
government contract bidding procedures. Two former employees
pleaded guilty to bribery and illegal political donations charges.
   Unisys said the incidents occurred before Sperry and Burroughs
Corp. merged and became known as Unisys, but agreed to institute a
company ethics program when the contract bidding suspension came to
an end. Unisys is rated the nation's 15th largest defense
contractor and last year received $1.4 billion in contracts from
the Pentagon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
