<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 1624EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     07-24 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0271</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices pulled back today, reined in by
uncertainty about the chances for lower interest rates anytime soon.
   The stock market moved broadly lower from the opening bell and
various market measures finished near their worst levels of the
session after an afternoon rebound ran out of steam.
   Wall Street analysts had anticipated today's selloff.
   Much of the force behind Friday's nearly 32-point surge in the
Dow Jones industrial average came from trading strategies tied to
the expiration of July stock-related futures and options.
   With the conclusion of trading in those contracts, a major
buying motivation disappeared.
   ``A lot of last week's activity was predicated on the futures
and options expirations,'' said Eugene Peroni, director of
technical research at Janney Montgomery Scott Inc.
   Attention now has returned to the interest rate outlook.
Financial markets have been building up their hopes for the Federal
Reserve Board to make a significant move toward a more generous
credit policy but so far they have been disappointed.
   ``The market must now consider that the Fed and the major
commercial banks have not acted as aggressively as was hoped,''
said Peroni.
   Earlier this month when Chase Manhattan Bank cut its prime
lending rate to 10{ percent from 11 percent, it was widely assumed
that its competitors would follow suit. But other major banks have
demurred.
   Peroni said he thinks the Fed will continue to ease its hold on
credit, but will do so in gradual, careful steps as it assesses the
economy's condition.
</TEXT>
