<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 2001EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Manville     07-24 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Manville,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second-Quarter Earnings Double</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manville Corp., the building products company,
said Monday its second-quarter profits more than doubled from the
same period a year ago, reflecting a strong performance by its
paper business.
   Manville, which emerged from Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings
last year, reported net income of $66.39 million, or 55 cents a
share, compared with $33.08 million, or 28 cents per share, in the
same 1988 period.
   Second-quarter sales were $564.6 million, 7 percent higher than
$526.7 million last year.
   Tom Stephens, Manville president and chief executive officer,
credited the company's prosperous paper business for the increased
earnings.
   For the first six months, net income totaled $103.75 million, or
80 cents per share, compared with a net loss of $38.12 million
during the first six months of 1988.
   Net sales for the first half were $1.07 billion, up from $994.2
million a year earlier, the company said.
   Manville is an international manufacturing and natural resources
company. Its products include paper and wood products, fiber glass,
roofing systems and minerals.
   Manville employs more than 18,000 people at 60 facilities and
four mines worldwide.
</TEXT>
