<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   07-24 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market moved broadly lower in light
activity Monday as traders lacked a compelling reason to buy.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials closed at 2,584.98, a
loss of 22.38, which erased much of Friday's nearly 32-point gain.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 9 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 942 down, 532 up and
507 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 136.26 million
shares, down from 174.88 million in the previous session.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 166.21 million shares.
   The stock market headed down from the opening bell and various
market measures finished near their lowest levels of the session
after an afternoon rebound ran out of steam.
   Wall Street analysts had anticipated the selloff.
   Much of the force behind Friday's surge in the Dow Jones
industrial average came from trading strategies tied to the
expiration of July stock-related futures and options.
   With the conclusion of trading in those contracts, a major
buying motivation disappeared.
   ``A lot of last week's activity was predicated on the futures
and options expirations,'' said Eugene Peroni, director of
technical research at Janney Montgomery Scott Inc.
   Attention now has returned to the interest rate outlook.
Financial markets have been building up their hopes for the Federal
Reserve Board to make a significant move toward a more generous
credit policy but so far they have been disappointed.
   ``The market must now consider that the Fed and the major
commercial banks have not acted as aggressively as was hoped,''
said Peroni.
   Earlier this month when Chase Manhattan Bank cut its prime
lending rate to 10{ percent from 11 percent, it was widely assumed
that its competitors would follow suit. But other major banks have
demurred.
   Among the stocks bucking the downtrend were Honeywell, which
climbed 3~ to 89], a 52-week high. The company, which has been
mentioned lately as a possible takeover target, announced a major
restructuring program that includes buying back about 10 million
shares of its common stock and selling a substantial portion of its
stake in Yamatake-Honeywell.
   Warner Communications also finished on the plus side and was the
most heavily traded NYSE-listed stock, as more than 4.7 million
shares changed hands. Warner rose 1| to 67[ after the Delaware
Supreme Court upheld a lower court ruling allowing Time to proceed
with its $14 billion tender offer for Warner. Time fell 1 to 137{.
   Paramount Communications, which dropped its $12.2 billion
hostile bid for Time after the court's ruling, rose 1~ to 59].
   Losers among the blue chips included McDonalds, which sank 2] to
29[. Securities analysts were unimpressed by the fast-food
restaurant company's second-quarter earnings.
   Also contributing to the decline in the Dow Jones industrial
average was Eastman Kodak, which dropped ~ to 47~. The company said
its second-quarter earnings will be reduced by about $225 million
due to a previously announced restructuring.
   Exxon lost 1|, falling to 45[. Its second-quarter income plunged
more than $1 billion due to costs associated with the Alaskan oil
spill.
   Among stocks mentioned recently as possible takeover candidates,
Holiday Corp. jumped 3} to a 52-week high of 62{.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market fell $21.52 billion, or 0.65
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
declined 1.12 to 186.03.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 2.93 to 382.38, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index finished at 333.67, off 2.23.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market went
down 3.31 to 445.98. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 369.82, off 1.46.
</TEXT>
