<FIRST>r f AM-Cray-Hitachi     07-24 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cray-Hitachi,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cray Says Hitachi Deal Does Not Include Sharing Of Trade Secrets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supercomputer rivals Cray Research Inc. and
Hitachi Ltd. on Monday confirmed that they have agreed to license
their patents to each other freely, but Cray said the pact does not
allow for joint marketing or sharing of trade secrets.
   Previous press reports were mistaken in saying the pact would
allow the two compaies to share information not yet patented, said
John Swenson, a spokesman for Minneapolis-based Cray.
   Hitachi issued a statement to confirm the existence of the
cross-licensing agreement but a spokesman in New York declined
further comment.
   Swenson said such agreements are customary in the computer
industry. But he said Hitachi is the first Japanese company to sign
such an agreement with Cray. Convex Computers of Richardson, Texas,
and Supertek Computers of California have similar agreements with
Cray, Swenson said.
   ``The agreement gives each company freedom to pursue designs
without having to be concerned about accidental design overlaps
involving a patent held by the other company,'' Swenson said. ``If
we should stumble onto one another's technology, we've agreed not
to litigate.''
   The Kyodo News Service of Japan, Japan Broadcasting Corp. and
the nationally circulated Asahi Shimbun newspaper reported earlier
that the agreement would enable Hitachi to obtain unpatented
technology from Cray, which has more experience in supercomputers.
The reports quoted unidentified ``industry sources.''
   Clyde V. Prestowitz Jr., a former Commerce Department trade
negotiator, said deals between high technology firms in the U.S.
and Japan draw the attention of the U.S. government officials
because they have been using taxpayer money to build up American
technology.
   Prestowitz, author of ``Trading Places,'' a book that advocates
U.S. industrial policy to preserve American technology, said he has
his ``eyebrows raised'' over the Cray-Hitachi deal.
   ``I wonder what lies behind it,'' he said, ``particularly why
they chose Hitachi.''
   Prestowitz said the Japanese have benefited from an imbalanced
flow of information between the two countries.
   ``If Cray gets more information than they give, more power to
them,'' he said.
</TEXT>
