<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-24 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Prices Plunge as Demand Weakens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices declined sharply Monday on the New York
Mercantile Exchange on indications that demand for crude oil
products is declining while supplies remain high.
   On other markets, copper prices were sharply higher, grain and
soybean futures fell, livestock and pork prices finished mixed and
precious metals were up slightly.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 14 cents to 77 cents
lower with the contract for delivery in September at $18.74 a
barrel; heating oil was 1.47 cents to 1.96 cents lower with August
at 49.70 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was 1.31 cents to 1.39
cents lower with August at 53.16 cents a gallon.
   ``A lot of selling was caused by reduced concern over the
availability of gas oil supplies out of the Soviet Union,'' said
James Ritterbusch, and analyst with Carson Petroleum Co. in Chicago.
   The easing of the coal strike in the Soviet Union was expected
to increase the availability of European energy products, analysts
said.
   Gasoline prices plunged as demand for the fuel declines in the
United States. Analysts said demand dropped 2.5 percent in the
first half of 1989.
   The market was also influenced by news that workers in the North
Sea oil field are calling off a work stoppage and expectations that
Tuesday's American Petroleum Institute report on oil stocks will
show increased supplies.
   Copper prices rose sharply on New York's Commodity Exchange on
news that copper stocks in London Metal Exchange-approved
warehouses declined 3,725 metric tons.
   Craig Sloane, an analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co.
in New York, said most traders expected an increase of about 5,000
metric tons in the London stocks because of production increases
and a slowing economy.
   Terrorist attacks against producers in Peru and a state of
emergency on Bougainville Island in Papua New Guinea, site of a
large copper mining operations, also have prompted worries over
supplies.
   Copper prices were 4.10 cents to 5.35 cents higher, with July at
$1.142 a pound.
   Gold and silver prices traded within a narrow range on the
Comex, with prices getting a minor boost from a weaker dollar,
Sloane said.
   Gold was 90 cents to $1 higher with July at $373.40 a troy
ounce; silver was .80 cent to 1.6 cents higher, with July at $5.202
a troy ounce.
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed lower on the Chicago
Board of Trade as rain and moderate temperatures in large areas of
the growing region weighed heavily on the market.
   ``The favorable growing conditions for this week, with a little
less warm temperatures than predicted, added to the bearish
sentiment,'' said Dale Gustafson, an analyst for Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. in Chicago. ``Disappointment in the export side of the
market also affected prices.''
   Wheat was 6 cents to 7\ cents lower with the contract for
delivery in September at $3.88{ a bushel; corn was 6 cents to 9\
cents lower with September at $2.30} a bushel; oats were 5 cents to
7 cents lower with September at $1.43 a bushel; soybeans were 12
cents to 23\ cents lower with August at $6.61} a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures were mixed in trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange as concern over high stocks of frozen pork
bellies _ the source of bacon _ weighed on meat futures. Cattle
prices were affected by concern over sluggish retail beef demand.
   Live cattle were .05 cent lower to .23 cent higher with August
at 72.60 a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .55 cent higher
with August at 83.90 a pound; hogs were .20 cent lower to .13 cent
higher with August at 45.85 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.15 cent lower to 1.03 cents higher with July at 28.92 a pound.
</TEXT>
