<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     07-24 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices fell sharply Monday, resuming
a downward pattern begun last week.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the September contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of crude oil, dropped
77 cents to settle at $18.74 a barrel. The September contract fell
17 cents on Friday, the first trading day for that contract.
   The October contract lost 74 cents to $18.45 while subsequent
months posted slightly smaller losses.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the September
contract of unleaded gasoline slid 1.36 cents to 53.16 cents a
gallon and heating oil for August delivery lost 1.70 cents to close
at 49.59 a barrel.
   Contracts for gasoline and heating oil scheduled for delivery
later in the year posted similar declines.
   Analysts said technical and other factors contributed to the
market's decline.
   ``This weakness started coming into the market last week and we
made new lows on Friday,'' said Ed Ryan, an analyst with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. ``We expected a follow-through today.''
   Reports of a possible end to the coal strike in the Soviet Union
also impacted prices, said John H. O'Connell, energy analyst with
Refco Inc.
   ``There is no longer a fear that the strike could spread to the
oil sector of the (Russian) economy,'' O'Connell said. The Soviet
Union is the world's largest oil producer.
   A report Monday in an industry trade publication also suggested
that Kuwait is increasing production, helping to weaken prices
further, O'Connell said.
</TEXT>
