<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Microsoft     07-24 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Microsoft,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Microsoft Quarterly Earnings Up 51 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDMOND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Microsoft Corp. said Monday its profit
rose 51 percent in its fourth fiscal quarter as revenue rose 29
percent from a year earlier.
   The personal computer software company said earnings rose to
$45.4 million, or 80 cents a share, from $30 million, or 54 cents a
share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $220.2 million from $170.5
million.
   For its full fiscal year, Microsoft reported a 38 percent
increase in net earnings to $170.5 million, or $3.03 per share,
from $123.9 million, or $2.22 per share, a year earlier. Revenue
rose 36 percent to $803.5 million from $590.8 million.
   ``These results represent strength across all channels of
distribution and in all product groups,'' said Jon Shirley,
president and chief operating officer.
   Shirley said international operations were particularly strong,
generating 55 percent of revenues in fiscal 1989. Overseas
operations represented 48 percent of 1988 revenues.
   A strong fourth quarter was aided by shipments of the latest
versions of Microsoft Word for both the IBM PC and the Apple
Macintosh, the company said.
