<FIRST>u f AM-Mexico-Debt 1stLd-Writethru a0698 07-24 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Debt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0698,0826</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agreement Removes Obstacle to Growth but Does Not Guarantee Recovery</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to ADD quotes; Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Mexico's
agreement ...'; Names Rogelio Ramirez de la O. and Abel Beltran-del-Rio
cq. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Mexico-Debt Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The plan for reducing Mexico's foreign debt
removes an obstacle to growth but does not guarantee recovery,
economists said Monday.
   ``The benefits go beyond what you can see in terms of the
reduction,'' said Nora Lustig, who teaches at the Colegio de
Mexico, a graduate school and think tank, and is a visiting fellow
at the Brookings Institute in Washington, D.C.
   ``It generates the impression to the world and investors who
want to go to Mexico that the financial stability is more or less
there,'' she said.
   Economists say elements still needed for recovery are
confidence, lower interest rates, investment, domestic savings,
reduction of the government deficit and continued containment of
wages and price.
   They said that, even if those conditions are met, the government
must be careful not to let the economy overheat and generate more
inflation.
   ``The agreement will let the economy grow and will gradually
raise our standard of living. It doesn't permit dreams. But with
work, we can return to sustained growth,'' Treasury Secretary Pedro
Aspe told a luncheon gathering of 500 of Mexico's elite and
powerful.
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari also spoke to the gathering
attended by Mexico's most powerful business, industry, media, labor
and farm leaders.
   In his remarks, Salinas said, ``every Mexican must now redouble
his efforts'' but that those efforts can now be made with ``spirit,
even happiness'' because they will result in progress.
   Mexico's agreement in principle with a steering committee of 15
creditor banks was seen as a test of Bush administration policy for
reducing Third World debt and as a milestone for other debtor
countries waiting to renegotiate.
   It represents the first significant reduction in a government's
debt to commercial banks.
   ``For the banks it is hard, but something they can live with,''
said M. Peter McPherson, executive vice president of Bank of
America. ``This really was a big reduction of assets for the banks,
and this was a big matter for Mexico in terms of how to get on top
of the debt problem.''
   Under the agreement, banks have three options: a 35 percent
reduction in principle, reduction of the interest rate to 6\
percent from the current average of about 10 percent, or providing
new loans equal to 25 percent of what Mexico owes the bank.
   The deal applies to about $54 billion of Mexico's foreign debt,
which totals $107 billion, second in the developing world only to
the $120 billion owed by Brazil.
   After more details are worked ut, which is expected to take a
few weeks, the agreement will be sent to the more than 500 creditor
banks for approval and choice of options.
   ``Is it enough so that Mexico is in a relatively comfortable
position to keep up with its payments? Definitely yes,'' said
Jonathan Heath of Macro-Asesoria, an economic consulting firm.
   He added, however, that savings provided by the agreement were
not necessarily enough to achieve President Carlos Salinas de
Gortari's goal of 6 percent annual economic growth by the end of
his six-year term in 1994.
   ``That point is still to be seen because the external debt is
the first step and probably the most important one,'' but those
savings alone will not be enough to finance the growth, Heath said.
   Mexico had a net inflow of resources when its economy was
growing, he said, but with the agreement, the country still will be
sending out more foreign exchange than it gets.
   Officials in Washington estimated the various options could save
Mexico about $1.5 billion annually of the $5 billion-$5.5 billion
in interest on the $54 billion of commercial debt involved.
   Rogelio Ramirez de la O., a Mexican economic consultant, said
the net transfer of funds abroad would be more than 4 percent of
the gross domestic product even with the agreement. The
government's goal was to reduce the amount from 7 percent to 2
percent.
   ``I am confident the agreement is going to boost optimism in the
private sector,'' he said, but added: ``The Mexican crisis is not
over.''
   Abel Beltran-del-Rio, director of CIEMEX-WEFA, an economic
consulting firm in Philadelphia, said the biggest risk was renewed
inflation,
   ``The greatest risk is that it may generate growing pressure on
public spending, which has fallen behind, especially in
government-owned industries, and for salary increases,'' he said.
   Beltran-del-Rio said the government wage-price plan that brought
inflation down from 159.2 percent in 1987 to an anticipated 20
percent 22 percent this year still will be needed.
</TEXT>
