<FILEID>AP-NR-07-24-89 2219EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Time 2ndLd-Writethru f0285 07-24 0912</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0285,0939</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramount Abandons Hostile Bid After Delaware Court Rules In Time's
Favor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Under its ...,' to CLARIFY that Time not paying
for tendered shares directly but through an escrow account. Picks up 8th
graf, `When the ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Communications Inc. abandoned
its $12.2 billion hostile bid for Time Inc. on Monday after the
Delaware Supreme Court upheld a lower court decision allowing Time
to proceed with its $14 billion buyout of Warner Communications Inc.
   ``We find no error of law by the Court of Chancery,'' Justice
Henry R. Horsey announced as the three-judge panel unanimously
sustained a ruling by Judge William T. Allen, thereby affirming the
rights of corporate directors to decide the future course of their
companies.
   The decision ended Paramount's seven-week bid to acquire Time.
Paramount issued a statement that it was dropping its $200 a share
buyout offer but would continue trying to expand through
acquisitions, mergers, joint ventures or partnerships.
   ``We believe in making bold moves when they are in the best
interest of Paramount Communications shareholders,'' said Paramount
Chairman Martin Davis. ``We have just demonstrated that in our
offer for Time ...''
   Paramount and several of Time's biggest shareholders
unsuccessfully had sought an injunction against Time's tender offer
for Warner, claiming that Time should be forced to consider
Paramount's buyout offer.
   The tender offer for Warner expired at 5 p.m. EDT and Time
announced it held more than 117 million Warner shares, or about 58
percent of the company's outstanding common stock. Time said it
would announce Tuesday the exact number of shares tendered under
its offer.
   Under its $70 a share offer, Time was to purchase slightly more
than half of Warner's common stock and exchange a combination of
cash and securities valued at $70 a share for the rest. Time said
shareholders would start to be paid for the tendered shares on
Monday.
   When their merger is complete _ a process expected to take
several months the new Time Warner Inc., will be the world's
largest communications concern.
   Paramount said it would not pursue a bid for Time Warner.
   Allen's ruling gave corporate directors latitude in defending
against unwanted takeover bids that they claim interfere with a
company's long-term strategy.
   The judge said the proposed Time-Warner deal, which was
announced in March, three months before Paramount launched its bid,
was the result of long-term business planning and that Paramount
and Time's shareholders could not interfere.
   Paramount has contended that once Time announced its plan to
merge with Warner it effectively placed itself up for sale and
under Delaware law therefore had to consider Paramount's offer.
   During more than two hours of arguments before the Supreme Court
Monday, Paramount attorney Melvyn Cantor said Time's board had a
fiduciary duty to inquire into Paramount's initial $175 a share
buyout offer.
   ``We don't question that Time-Warner is a good deal,'' Cantor
said, but he contended Time shareholders should have had a chance
to vote on whether Paramount's acquisition of the company would
have been a better deal in the short term.
   Michael Klein, an attorney for major Time shareholders,
including Texas investor Robert M. Bass, said thousands of the
company's stockholders opposed the Time-Warner merger. He argued
that based on previous Delaware court rulings, the board was
obligated to consider Paramount's offer.
   But Justice Andrew G.T. Moore interjected that Klein's argument
would make a board hostage ``to anyone who walked in with a bid,''
regardless of a company's long-range plans.
   Klein said after the court ruled that the decision tilted
Delaware law in favor of management. He predicted attorneys would
advise corporations to develop an ``appearance of a long-term
plan'' to ward off potential takeover bids.
   When Time attorney Robert Joffe presented his case Monday, the
justices asked why Time's tender offer for Warner _ which replaced
an earlier stock-swap merger plan _ was not submitted to a vote by
Time shareholders at the company's annual meeting in June.
   Joffe said a vote was not required because the deal did not
involve the issuing of new Time stock. Furthermore, he said, after
Paramount announced its bid on June 6, the market for Time stock
was in disarray and the price of the shares was seesawing.
   ``This was hardly the situation to have an unimpassioned
evaluation of future value and get a fair vote,'' he said.
   Joffe contended Time's plans to merge with Warner would give
shareholders greater value in the long term than Paramount's $200 a
share offer.
   The case was heard in Delaware because all three companies _
like many of the biggest U.S. corporations _ are incorporated
there. Because so many major corporations subject to Delaware laws,
the Time case likely will have implications for other companies in
the future.
   The Supreme Court planned to issue a written decision at some
point in the future.
   The justices' ruling was widely expected even before the hearing
began. As arguments proceeded _ and were televised live by Cable
News Network _ Time's stock dropped on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Time stock closed down $1 at $137.50 a share. Warner stock
rose$1.62{ to $66.12{ a share and Paramount rose $1.87{ to $59.37{
a share.
   Time stock, which traded at $126 a share before the Paramount
bid, rose to a high of $182.75 before falling back in recent weeks
as investors became increasingly pessimistic about the chances for
Paramount's success.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
