<SECOND>BC-Pulitzer-TV Purchase,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Orleans Station Sold for $46.8 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulitzer Publishing Co. has agreed to buy
WDSU-TV, the NBC affiliate in New Orleans, for $46.8 million from
Cosmos Broadcasting, Pulitzer announced Monday.
   Pulitzer, a St. Louis-based newspaper and broadcast company,
said in a news release issued here by WDSU-TV that the sale awaits
Federal Communications Commission approval.
   WDSU-TV, which went on the air in 1948, is Louisiana's oldest
television station. It was bought by Cosmos Broadcasting in 1972.
The station reported 1988 revenues of $16.5 million.
   Pulitzer's other TV properties are ABC network affiliates
KOAT-TV in Albuquerque, N.M., KETV-TV in Omaha, Neb., WPTA-TV in
Fort Wayne, Ind., and WLKY-TV, Louisville, Ky.; and NBC affiliates
WGAL-TV in Lancaster, Pa., WYFF-TV in Greenville, S.C. and WXII-TV
in Winston-Salem, N.C.
   The company also operates radio stations KTAR-AM and KKLT-FM in
Phoenix.
   Pulitzer publishes the St. Louis Post-Dispatch, The Arizona
Daily Star in Tuscon, Ariz., and the Southtown Economist and The
Daily Calumet, both in suburban Chicago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
